cue-8
00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:31.860
The version you are listening to is the
unabridged original, revised for

cue-9
00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:32.619
readability.

cue-10
00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:39.000
This brief memorial, "To What Purpose?" is
dedicated to all who have

cue-11
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.280
generously given for the spread of the
gospel in China, and in loving memory of

cue-12
00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:47.740
Emil Fischbacher's mother, who went to
meet the King and be reunited with her son

cue-13
00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:49.940
while this small book was being written.

cue-14
00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:52.870
R.W. Church said,

cue-15
00:00:53.570 --> 00:00:55.490
"As long as Christianity endures,

cue-16
00:00:56.120 --> 00:01:01.080
the heroic life must remain the standard
for all people. Christianity may

cue-17
00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:02.020
allow for weakness,

cue-18
00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:04.500
but it cannot lower its standard.

cue-19
00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:07.560
That standard cannot be moved."

cue-20
00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:11.320
The imitation of Christ can only be
written in one way.

cue-21
00:01:12.270 --> 00:01:15.980
There is strong temptation to abandon this
heroic ideal.

cue-22
00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:19.660
It often seems to fail. It is easily
faked.

cue-23
00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:25.360
Its failure can be shameful, and not only
does our desire for comfort lead

cue-24
00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:30.040
us away from it, but also our fear of
false appearances, our love of

cue-25
00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:35.000
moderation, and our so-called common sense
urge us to settle for less,

cue-26
00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:38.140
to aim only for what we think suits our
nature.

cue-27
00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:42.280
But the New Testament refuses to meet us
at that lower level.

cue-28
00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:47.720
It upholds only the heroic standard as the
only one worthy of the greatness it

cue-29
00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:48.300
reveals.

cue-30
00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:52.360
Foreword

cue-31
00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:59.260
by the author, Marshall Broomhall. Written
on October thirty-first, nineteen

cue-32
00:01:59.260 --> 00:01:59.820
thirty-three.

cue-33
00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:05.340
Tragic and unexpected events can suddenly
stir us to deep thought.

cue-34
00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:11.220
This happened when news reached us of Dr.
Emil Fischbacher's early death,

cue-35
00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:13.620
just sixteen months after he arrived in
China.

cue-36
00:02:14.709 --> 00:02:19.320
The question, "To what purpose?" naturally
came to mind, and from that

cue-37
00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:21.640
question, this little book was born.

cue-38
00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:27.540
Some may ask, "What can such a short life
offer to justify yet another

cue-39
00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:28.340
publication?"

cue-40
00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:33.820
Our answer is that apart from the value of
his life itself, a number of

cue-41
00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:37.800
stirring and significant events are
connected to his brief time in the mission

cue-42
00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:38.260
field.

cue-43
00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:42.860
There was the bombing of Shanghai, his
harsh welcome to China.

cue-44
00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:48.220
There was the rare and dangerous journey
across the Gobi Desert, vividly showing

cue-45
00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:51.900
one of the many challenges in reaching
Chinese Turkestan with the gospel.

cue-46
00:02:52.590 --> 00:02:57.280
Then came the rebellion in that distant
land, a sample of the hard and dangerous

cue-47
00:02:57.280 --> 00:02:58.920
work that pioneers may face.

cue-48
00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:03.160
All this and more is captured in this
brief account.

cue-49
00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:09.080
It has been said of Dante that he believed
wonderful stories could be found in the

cue-50
00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:10.640
unnoticed paths of life,

cue-51
00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:15.660
in the fleeting events of the moment, and
among people whose faces we have seen.

cue-52
00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:20.060
That is why he didn't limit his Divine
Comedy to famous figures.

cue-53
00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:25.880
Not only the great and well-known, such a
focus is too narrow and unreal,

cue-54
00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:26.400
he believed.

cue-55
00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:31.530
He even chose the title Comedy because he
wrote in the language of everyday people,

cue-56
00:03:31.530 --> 00:03:34.780
not in Latin, and because he wrote about
common life.

cue-57
00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.579
In the same way, the short life of this
young doctor carries a unique

cue-58
00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:43.560
significance. Its very brevity awakens
reverence and

cue-59
00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:48.560
attention. The late Dr. Eugene Stock once
reflected on how some brief

cue-60
00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:53.420
missionary lives have had lasting
influence. David Brainerd

cue-61
00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:57.980
worked among the Native Americans for less
than three years and died at twenty-nine.

cue-62
00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:02.140
Henry Martin served only six years and
died at thirty-one.

cue-63
00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:07.400
Bishop Hannington labored in Africa for
about three years before he was killed on

cue-64
00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:11.940
the way to his post. These are just a few
from a great number of such lives.

cue-65
00:04:12.700 --> 00:04:14.920
Lives cannot be measured by their length.

cue-66
00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:18.440
Of David Brainerd, Dr. Stock said,

cue-67
00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:22.880
"He did less in his lifetime than his
biography did after he was gone."

cue-68
00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:27.460
A single moment of sowing can bring
harvests for generations.

cue-69
00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:31.760
Who would measure the life of our Lord by
how long he lived on Earth?

cue-70
00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:34.620
We can only trace the surface history.

cue-71
00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.540
Only love understands the mystery.

cue-72
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.640
If this little book can help even one
reader grasp the great importance of

cue-73
00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:46.640
bringing the gospel to a land as vast and
remote as Chinese Turkestan,

cue-74
00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:49.720
the land for which Emil Fischbacher gave
his life,

cue-75
00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:52.760
then its publication will be more than
worthwhile.

cue-76
00:04:56.240 --> 00:04:59.220
Chapter one: An Introduction to China.

cue-77
00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:05.600
"We've just received news by wireless from
England that China has declared war on

cue-78
00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:06.080
Japan.

cue-79
00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:11.560
We haven't been able to reach Shanghai for
over forty-eight hours. The captain isn't

cue-80
00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:13.200
sure if we'll be able to land.

cue-81
00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:15.420
There's a lot of excitement on board."

cue-82
00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:21.320
So wrote Emil Fischbacher to his dear
family at home as the SS Naldera

cue-83
00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:25.720
steamed up the China Sea, about eighty
miles from the mouth of the Yangtze River.

cue-84
00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:30.670
Although no official declaration of war
had been made, fighting had already

cue-85
00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:31.140
begun.

cue-86
00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:34.940
In another letter written not long after,
he added...

cue-87
00:05:35.810 --> 00:05:40.530
"The pilot came on board three or four
hours ago, and apparently, he doesn't know

cue-88
00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:45.500
what to do. So here we are and will
likely stay until morning. We

cue-89
00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:49.520
still haven't been able to reach Shanghai
by wireless for nearly three days.

cue-90
00:05:50.230 --> 00:05:51.950
All our news is coming from England.

cue-91
00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:56.230
It seems the government wireless station
in Shanghai has been destroyed.

cue-92
00:05:57.150 --> 00:06:02.104
The captain is reluctant to head directly
to Japan.Since he doesn't yet have

cue-93
00:06:02.104 --> 00:06:04.583
room for the cargo he's supposed to pick
up there.

cue-94
00:06:05.224 --> 00:06:10.224
This morning at seven o'clock, HMS Suffolk
sped past us at thirty knots,

cue-95
00:06:10.224 --> 00:06:12.344
headed straight for Shanghai.

cue-96
00:06:13.064 --> 00:06:17.964
She'd been in Hong Kong when we left.
She's a large cruiser. Normally,

cue-97
00:06:17.964 --> 00:06:22.824
ships in these waters are limited to
thirteen or fourteen knots an hour, so the

cue-98
00:06:22.824 --> 00:06:25.224
Suffolk must be heading into serious
action.

cue-99
00:06:26.624 --> 00:06:31.004
Emil Fischbacher, the writer of the above,
was one of six young men on board the

cue-100
00:06:31.004 --> 00:06:35.284
Naldera, all new volunteers for the great
work of evangelizing China.

cue-101
00:06:35.984 --> 00:06:40.543
Three of them, including Emil, were
medical doctors. They were part of the

cue-102
00:06:40.544 --> 00:06:44.944
last group of the two hundred and had left
London on the final day of nineteen

cue-103
00:06:44.944 --> 00:06:45.584
thirty-one.

cue-104
00:06:46.444 --> 00:06:50.504
Their ship had sailed on Christmas Day,
but because of the special meaning of that

cue-105
00:06:50.504 --> 00:06:54.904
season, arrangements had been made for
the group to travel overland and board at

cue-106
00:06:54.904 --> 00:06:55.644
Marseille.

cue-107
00:06:56.864 --> 00:07:01.184
As it turned out, that Christmas was the
last Emil would spend with his family on

cue-108
00:07:01.184 --> 00:07:05.644
Earth, and for his loved ones, it had been
an especially joyful and

cue-109
00:07:05.644 --> 00:07:09.134
unforgettable time, filled with surprise
and gladness.

cue-110
00:07:10.104 --> 00:07:15.054
But now, back on the ship, the passengers
waited anxiously as their vessel

cue-111
00:07:15.054 --> 00:07:17.154
lay just beyond the Woosung forts.

cue-112
00:07:17.964 --> 00:07:21.844
Although the steamer couldn't go to its
usual dock, passengers were taken up the

cue-113
00:07:21.844 --> 00:07:26.804
river on a smaller boat. The group of
young missionaries, accompanied by Mr.

cue-114
00:07:26.804 --> 00:07:31.804
and Mrs. Rowe, safely arrived at the new
compound of the China Inland

cue-115
00:07:31.804 --> 00:07:32.364
Mission.

cue-116
00:07:33.454 --> 00:07:38.164
The old headquarters, only vacated seven
months earlier, had already been taken

cue-117
00:07:38.164 --> 00:07:39.274
over by the Japanese.

cue-118
00:07:40.024 --> 00:07:42.744
It was inside the area of active conflict.

cue-119
00:07:43.954 --> 00:07:48.064
This striking scene gave the new arrivals
a powerful reminder.

cue-120
00:07:49.084 --> 00:07:51.024
God had not forgotten his people.

cue-121
00:07:51.864 --> 00:07:54.244
He had already made a way for his work to
continue.

cue-122
00:07:55.084 --> 00:07:59.604
It was a harsh welcome to a foreign land,
but one that matched the disorder of the

cue-123
00:07:59.604 --> 00:08:02.454
vast country they had come to evangelize.

cue-124
00:08:03.444 --> 00:08:05.544
For miles, shops were closed.

cue-125
00:08:06.194 --> 00:08:09.884
The general post office was shut down due
to its unsafe location.

cue-126
00:08:10.494 --> 00:08:15.264
The Chinese banks were not operating. The
customs house mirrored the abnormal

cue-127
00:08:15.264 --> 00:08:17.124
state of one of the world's great ports.

cue-128
00:08:17.964 --> 00:08:20.044
Letters sent home during this time,

cue-129
00:08:20.724 --> 00:08:24.364
letters that had to be smuggled out of
Shanghai, were filled with vivid

cue-130
00:08:24.364 --> 00:08:26.224
descriptions of those tense days.

cue-131
00:08:27.184 --> 00:08:30.664
One or two more extracts from young
Fischbacher's letters will suffice to

cue-132
00:08:30.664 --> 00:08:31.404
paint the picture.

cue-133
00:08:32.304 --> 00:08:36.764
It was pretty bad, he wrote, but today,
since daybreak, we've had

cue-134
00:08:36.764 --> 00:08:41.764
continuous gunfire. These are big guns.
The Japanese clearly mean business

cue-135
00:08:41.764 --> 00:08:46.224
today. The constant booming and the shock
of the explosions have continued all

cue-136
00:08:46.224 --> 00:08:51.144
day. Tonight's papers suggest that the
Japanese have blown the Woosung forts to

cue-137
00:08:51.144 --> 00:08:51.784
pieces.

cue-138
00:08:52.524 --> 00:08:54.644
All of this has come from gunboats on the
river.

cue-139
00:08:56.084 --> 00:09:00.734
I've just been up on the roof. The sight
honestly makes you sick. For at least

cue-140
00:09:00.734 --> 00:09:05.724
three miles, there's a continuous stretch
of fire. The sky is glowing from it

cue-141
00:09:05.724 --> 00:09:10.404
all. There can't be much left standing in
the Chapei district now. It's

cue-142
00:09:10.404 --> 00:09:15.324
tragic because, as always, the innocent
are the ones who suffer

cue-143
00:09:15.324 --> 00:09:15.864
most.

cue-144
00:09:16.504 --> 00:09:21.344
There are thousands and thousands of
refugees everywhere. Every boat that can

cue-145
00:09:21.344 --> 00:09:24.834
leave is packed with Chinese trying to
escape the fighting.

cue-146
00:09:25.624 --> 00:09:28.344
Everyone here is deeply thankful for this
building.

cue-147
00:09:29.464 --> 00:09:33.844
If we had still been in the old mission
compound, we would have had to evacuate

cue-148
00:09:33.844 --> 00:09:34.824
almost a week ago.

cue-149
00:09:35.484 --> 00:09:40.004
For now, we are safe, though safe is a
relative word.

cue-150
00:09:40.744 --> 00:09:44.484
Two shells landed in Sinza Road, just
yards away.

cue-151
00:09:44.484 --> 00:09:46.624
Getting into Shanghai had been one
challenge.

cue-152
00:09:47.353 --> 00:09:51.564
Getting out and traveling up the river to
the language school in Anking would be

cue-153
00:09:51.564 --> 00:09:51.924
another.

cue-154
00:09:52.884 --> 00:09:54.544
But before that story begins,

cue-155
00:09:55.284 --> 00:09:59.544
and before we trace the records of Emil
Fischbacher's short yet impactful life in

cue-156
00:09:59.544 --> 00:09:59.904
China,

cue-157
00:10:00.504 --> 00:10:01.344
we must go back.

cue-158
00:10:02.404 --> 00:10:06.664
We need to see what it was that led him to
face the hardships and duties of a

cue-159
00:10:06.664 --> 00:10:07.764
missionary's calling.

cue-160
00:10:08.484 --> 00:10:10.384
As the writer of Ecclesiasticus says,

cue-161
00:10:11.124 --> 00:10:15.204
My son, if you come to serve the Lord,
prepare your soul for testing.

cue-162
00:10:16.084 --> 00:10:20.664
Jesus, son of Sirach, who wrote those
words, surely spoke from

cue-163
00:10:20.664 --> 00:10:21.384
experience.

cue-164
00:10:22.504 --> 00:10:27.063
It was wise and weighty counsel, and Emil
Fischbacher had not put his hand to the

cue-165
00:10:27.064 --> 00:10:30.444
plow without first fighting a deep battle
in the valley of decision.

cue-166
00:10:33.964 --> 00:10:36.744
Chapter two. It might have been.

cue-167
00:10:39.404 --> 00:10:43.804
When a woman poured her expensive
spikenard oil on Jesus' head and feet,

cue-168
00:10:43.804 --> 00:10:48.684
those who didn't understand were indignant
and said, To what purpose was this waste?

cue-169
00:10:49.284 --> 00:10:52.164
This ointment could have been sold for
over three hundred pence.

cue-170
00:10:53.104 --> 00:10:57.544
This same false thinking will always exist
wherever spiritual blindness remains.

cue-171
00:10:58.224 --> 00:11:03.164
The world especially appeals to the young,
offering them life itself, their most

cue-172
00:11:03.164 --> 00:11:04.164
precious treasure.

cue-173
00:11:05.004 --> 00:11:09.504
Temporary things dress themselves in
beauty and offer every possible charm.

cue-174
00:11:10.144 --> 00:11:14.244
The inner tempter and the pressures from
outside work together, presenting their

cue-175
00:11:14.244 --> 00:11:18.684
strongest case against breaking the vessel
of life and pouring out its contents for

cue-176
00:11:18.684 --> 00:11:19.044
God.

cue-177
00:11:19.944 --> 00:11:21.984
So it was with Emil Fischbacher.

cue-178
00:11:22.904 --> 00:11:24.424
The world made him a great offer.

cue-179
00:11:25.304 --> 00:11:30.123
He was born into a Christian home, the
fourth son and sixth child in a family of

cue-180
00:11:30.124 --> 00:11:30.484
ten.

cue-181
00:11:31.284 --> 00:11:35.344
That Emil and all his surviving brothers
and sisters committed themselves to Christ

cue-182
00:11:35.344 --> 00:11:39.824
early in life speaks volumes about their
home and their parents' influence.

cue-183
00:11:40.784 --> 00:11:44.404
All were baptized by their pastor, the
Reverend John McBeath.

cue-184
00:11:45.284 --> 00:11:49.904
We have before us a copy of a covenant
card like the one Emil signed as a young

cue-185
00:11:49.904 --> 00:11:54.884
boy. He and his brother Ernest were part
of a group of young people who, on

cue-186
00:11:54.884 --> 00:11:59.144
a memorable Sunday, signed those cards
and handed them to the pastor at the

cue-187
00:11:59.144 --> 00:11:59.564
pulpit.

cue-188
00:12:00.344 --> 00:12:05.294
There was nothing forced or artificial
about it. It was healthy, sincere, and

cue-189
00:12:05.294 --> 00:12:09.896
real.Under the covenant and the boy's
signature are these familiar

cue-190
00:12:09.896 --> 00:12:10.436
lines.

cue-191
00:12:11.256 --> 00:12:16.236
Just as I am, young, strong, and free, to
be the best that I

cue-192
00:12:16.236 --> 00:12:21.056
can be, for truth and righteousness and
thee, Lord of my life,

cue-193
00:12:21.056 --> 00:12:21.816
I come.

cue-194
00:12:22.656 --> 00:12:24.876
And on the back of the card are more
lines,

cue-195
00:12:25.536 --> 00:12:30.196
some for the boys and some for the girls,
reminding us of what Hudson Taylor used to

cue-196
00:12:30.196 --> 00:12:30.486
say,

cue-197
00:12:31.236 --> 00:12:34.106
that conversion should be called becoming
joyful,

cue-198
00:12:34.836 --> 00:12:38.715
not becoming serious, as it was often
described in his youth.

cue-199
00:12:39.996 --> 00:12:42.056
Here are the lines written for the boys.

cue-200
00:12:42.976 --> 00:12:47.856
God wants the boys, the cheerful boys, the
noisy, laughing,

cue-201
00:12:47.856 --> 00:12:50.756
playful boys, the careless boys.

cue-202
00:12:51.536 --> 00:12:55.996
God wants the boys with all their joys,
that he might make them pure as

cue-203
00:12:55.996 --> 00:13:00.856
gold and teach them how to brave and hold
through trial and test with courage

cue-204
00:13:00.856 --> 00:13:01.236
bright.

cue-205
00:13:02.056 --> 00:13:06.496
To stand for truth, defend the right. God
wants the boys.

cue-206
00:13:06.496 --> 00:13:10.276
At home, the cause of foreign missions was
always front and center.

cue-207
00:13:11.016 --> 00:13:15.796
Emil's father had one great ambition, that
at least five of his children would offer

cue-208
00:13:15.796 --> 00:13:19.816
themselves for missionary service and
that he might have the joy and privilege

cue-209
00:13:19.816 --> 00:13:23.996
of supporting them financially without the
need for mission societies.

cue-210
00:13:24.916 --> 00:13:29.536
He worked hard and built a successful
business largely for this purpose.

cue-211
00:13:29.536 --> 00:13:34.376
China held a special place in his heart,
especially through the work of the China

cue-212
00:13:34.376 --> 00:13:35.396
Inland Mission.

cue-213
00:13:36.596 --> 00:13:41.466
Yet, as Emil grew older, he strongly
resisted the idea of serving there,

cue-214
00:13:42.276 --> 00:13:46.776
even though his eldest sister had already
gone. China was the last place in the

cue-215
00:13:46.776 --> 00:13:51.135
world he wanted to go, but this may have
been for the best, because when the

cue-216
00:13:51.136 --> 00:13:55.846
decision finally came, it was entirely his
own. Not someone else's,

cue-217
00:13:55.846 --> 00:13:58.056
not even subtly suggested.

cue-218
00:13:59.046 --> 00:14:02.436
We are given a glimpse of that personal
decision in a letter he wrote to his

cue-219
00:14:02.436 --> 00:14:07.076
younger brother, dated February 15th,
1933, from the

cue-220
00:14:07.076 --> 00:14:11.996
capital of Chinese Turkestan. It reveals
part, but not all, of

cue-221
00:14:11.996 --> 00:14:14.935
the struggle that had taken place between
his soul and God.

cue-222
00:14:15.935 --> 00:14:17.536
One thing has been on my mind,

cue-223
00:14:18.516 --> 00:14:21.756
and that is foreign missions and your
relationship to them.

cue-224
00:14:22.816 --> 00:14:25.676
I knew, of course, that you didn't want to
say much.

cue-225
00:14:26.386 --> 00:14:28.576
You always went so far and no further,

cue-226
00:14:29.296 --> 00:14:34.296
but I was anxious to know, and I'm glad
you told me. I've been thinking about

cue-227
00:14:34.296 --> 00:14:39.216
you a lot recently, and praying too, that
the Lord would open a sphere of

cue-228
00:14:39.216 --> 00:14:39.996
service for you.

cue-229
00:14:41.256 --> 00:14:42.216
I'm not impatient,

cue-230
00:14:43.096 --> 00:14:45.816
but I am praying that the Lord will, in
his time,

cue-231
00:14:46.456 --> 00:14:51.416
clearly show you what he wants you to do.
I almost feel as if I make suggestions in

cue-232
00:14:51.416 --> 00:14:54.356
my prayers about what kind of service
might suit you,

cue-233
00:14:54.956 --> 00:14:57.156
but I whisper them under my breath.

cue-234
00:14:57.836 --> 00:15:02.836
I've often thought, ever since I qualified
in 1926, that surely

cue-235
00:15:02.836 --> 00:15:07.236
sometime soon I would receive the call.
Even when I wasn't eager,

cue-236
00:15:07.896 --> 00:15:11.856
I had the sense that one day I'd find
myself on the foreign field.

cue-237
00:15:12.576 --> 00:15:15.676
I would never have imagined that China
would be part of that.

cue-238
00:15:16.696 --> 00:15:21.596
As you may know, for three or four years,
Dr. W. wanted me to come and

cue-239
00:15:21.596 --> 00:15:22.196
work with him.

cue-240
00:15:22.836 --> 00:15:27.126
That would have meant £1,200 a year for
three years, and then over

cue-241
00:15:27.126 --> 00:15:28.986
£3,000 a year after that.

cue-242
00:15:29.716 --> 00:15:32.196
You can live quite comfortably on an
income like that.

cue-243
00:15:33.136 --> 00:15:37.176
But I never felt right about accepting the
offer, because I always had the

cue-244
00:15:37.176 --> 00:15:39.776
possibility of the mission field in the
back of my mind.

cue-245
00:15:40.736 --> 00:15:42.216
It's strange to think of it now.

cue-246
00:15:42.816 --> 00:15:47.456
Dr. W. was very kind about it, even though
he didn't fully understand.

cue-247
00:15:48.516 --> 00:15:51.256
In the meantime, I bounced from place to
place.

cue-248
00:15:51.976 --> 00:15:53.276
First general practice,

cue-249
00:15:53.996 --> 00:15:55.456
then a house surgeon post,

cue-250
00:15:56.176 --> 00:16:00.696
then tropical medicine, then general
surgery and major operations,

cue-251
00:16:01.296 --> 00:16:03.496
then public health and tuberculosis,

cue-252
00:16:04.156 --> 00:16:06.826
then ear, nose and throat diseases,

cue-253
00:16:07.536 --> 00:16:10.636
then another stretch of varied general
practice,

cue-254
00:16:11.256 --> 00:16:16.176
then eye diseases, and so on and on. What
a mixture!

cue-255
00:16:16.236 --> 00:16:18.306
Now I'm a kind of jack-of-all-trades here,

cue-256
00:16:19.016 --> 00:16:23.636
my own consultant and advisor, with no one
to turn to. How I

cue-257
00:16:23.636 --> 00:16:25.676
value all that varied experience!

cue-258
00:16:26.336 --> 00:16:28.116
It's more useful than I ever knew.

cue-259
00:16:29.436 --> 00:16:34.296
This long, personal letter, never meant
for public eyes, was written to

cue-260
00:16:34.296 --> 00:16:38.136
his brother, but it gives us a rare look
into Emil's inner world.

cue-261
00:16:38.836 --> 00:16:43.636
It shows what the world offered him and
what he gave up. At one point,

cue-262
00:16:43.636 --> 00:16:47.916
there was even the temptation to serve in
a support role rather than go to the

cue-263
00:16:47.916 --> 00:16:51.876
mission field himself, believing he could
do more good by financing

cue-264
00:16:51.876 --> 00:16:56.196
others. It might have been sold for 300
pence and given to the poor.

cue-265
00:16:57.276 --> 00:16:59.616
But God did not want someone else in his
place.

cue-266
00:17:00.476 --> 00:17:01.216
He wanted him.

cue-267
00:17:02.436 --> 00:17:06.976
It was at this point that God's hand
guided Emil to China in an

cue-268
00:17:06.976 --> 00:17:08.336
unmistakable way.

cue-269
00:17:09.696 --> 00:17:14.416
In June 1931, he came across an appeal
printed in China's millions.

cue-270
00:17:15.236 --> 00:17:19.126
It was addressed to young men and written
by an anonymous missionary in the field.

cue-271
00:17:20.166 --> 00:17:24.986
The article referred to the ongoing appeal
for the 200 and opened with these words.

cue-272
00:17:25.856 --> 00:17:27.196
What does that appeal mean to you?

cue-273
00:17:28.176 --> 00:17:31.555
Maybe you've had objections to the way the
appeal was made.

cue-274
00:17:31.556 --> 00:17:35.536
Will those objections still stand when you
have to answer to the Lord on the coming

cue-275
00:17:35.536 --> 00:17:35.776
day?

cue-276
00:17:37.056 --> 00:17:39.346
This was an arrow shot from far away,

cue-277
00:17:40.116 --> 00:17:41.206
but it struck home.

cue-278
00:17:42.296 --> 00:17:46.486
Not even knowing where to apply, Emil
wrote to the author of the booklet,

cue-279
00:17:46.486 --> 00:17:50.346
someone who had once stayed in his home
and played golf with him during a visit to

cue-280
00:17:50.346 --> 00:17:50.996
Scotland.

cue-281
00:17:52.076 --> 00:17:53.446
In that letter, he said

cue-282
00:17:54.196 --> 00:17:59.016
I was extremely eager to go to Africa, but
honestly, the idea of going to

cue-283
00:17:59.016 --> 00:18:03.696
China never entered my mind. I never even
liked the thought of serving there.

cue-284
00:18:03.696 --> 00:18:08.136
But last Saturday evening, I picked up
the latest issue of China's

cue-285
00:18:08.136 --> 00:18:13.136
millions and read the appeal to young men.
Since then, I've felt an

cue-286
00:18:13.136 --> 00:18:15.496
irresistible urge to write this letter.

cue-287
00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:20.579
This was in June, just before the China
Inland Mission Conference at

cue-288
00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:25.200
Swanwick. His letter was passed on to the
Reverend W.H. Aldis,

cue-289
00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:28.270
home director of the mission's work in
Great Britain.

cue-290
00:18:29.020 --> 00:18:33.400
What happened next is best told in Emil
Fischbacher's own words. In a letter he

cue-291
00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:36.770
wrote to his younger sister, who was also
in the medical profession.

cue-292
00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:42.240
I got a note from Mr. Aldis asking if I
would come over to the CIM conference at

cue-293
00:18:42.240 --> 00:18:43.390
Swanwick and meet him.

cue-294
00:18:44.140 --> 00:18:46.200
Yesterday was my half day off,

cue-295
00:18:46.980 --> 00:18:47.620
so I went.

cue-296
00:18:48.359 --> 00:18:51.980
A beautiful drive through Derbyshire,
sixty-one miles.

cue-297
00:18:52.700 --> 00:18:55.040
At that time, he was practicing near
Manchester.

cue-298
00:18:55.900 --> 00:19:00.680
Right away, I found myself in three
wonderful meetings. At nine fifteen

cue-299
00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:05.600
PM, as planned, I met Mr. Aldis and we
went for a walk.

cue-300
00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:10.540
Then, in his room, we prayed together. And
now, well, I feel

cue-301
00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:15.500
strange. I haven't quite grasped it all
yet. I wish you were here. I'd talk it all

cue-302
00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:19.480
out with you. I've been very down for
months and months because I felt I had

cue-303
00:19:19.480 --> 00:19:23.910
completely lost my direction. But God has
been good.

cue-304
00:19:23.910 --> 00:19:26.640
The letter continues in a free and
open-hearted tone,

cue-305
00:19:27.290 --> 00:19:30.700
the way some brothers can write only to a
sister with whom nothing is hidden.

cue-306
00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:36.480
At that point, he hadn't even told his
parents. His plan was to break the

cue-307
00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:39.080
news to them in person during his next
visit home.

cue-308
00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:40.200
And now,

cue-309
00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:42.840
the whole tone of the letters changes.

cue-310
00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:48.140
Streams have burst forth in the desert,
and a heavy heart has been replaced with

cue-311
00:19:48.140 --> 00:19:49.200
overflowing joy.

cue-312
00:19:49.930 --> 00:19:53.520
Through his personal letters, we get a
glimpse of his Bühler land.

cue-313
00:19:54.520 --> 00:19:57.620
Here's part of what he wrote to the same
sister.

cue-314
00:19:57.620 --> 00:20:02.440
At Swanwick, even though we were having a
wonderful time, I felt I wasn't in the

cue-315
00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:06.140
place of full blessing. I insisted on
keeping my little right,

cue-316
00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:11.800
but I was miserable. Eventually, I went to
my room and had half an hour

cue-317
00:20:11.800 --> 00:20:16.620
of heaven. That right just slipped away,
and I haven't wanted it back.

cue-318
00:20:16.620 --> 00:20:19.280
God has already given me a hundredfold in
return.

cue-319
00:20:19.960 --> 00:20:23.780
I'm already at the point of longing to go
to China. Isn't that strange?

cue-320
00:20:24.560 --> 00:20:26.880
I used to hate even the thought of China.

cue-321
00:20:27.709 --> 00:20:32.030
The question of being filled with the Holy
Spirit has been on my mind constantly for

cue-322
00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:36.959
the past ten days or two weeks. I've
spent a lot of time in prayer

cue-323
00:20:36.960 --> 00:20:41.800
about it, but somehow I still feel God has
more for me. He's

cue-324
00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:42.900
been so kind.

cue-325
00:20:43.620 --> 00:20:48.520
Last night I was facing a big difficulty.
I felt I couldn't move forward unless it

cue-326
00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:53.080
was removed. I've never liked the idea of
testing God like some people do.

cue-327
00:20:53.720 --> 00:20:58.540
It feels like asking for a sign and too
showy. But walking up the

cue-328
00:20:58.540 --> 00:20:59.330
road last night,

cue-329
00:21:00.060 --> 00:21:04.880
God put it in my heart to test him in this
way. I prayed before going to bed

cue-330
00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:09.880
and went to sleep with calm confidence
that the one who alone could help

cue-331
00:21:09.880 --> 00:21:14.380
me, and you can't imagine how big the
request was, would answer my

cue-332
00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:19.120
prayer. Just as I was about to turn off
the light, I noticed my daily light.

cue-333
00:21:19.840 --> 00:21:24.720
I read the portion for that day, and the
very first paragraph was exactly what I

cue-334
00:21:24.720 --> 00:21:25.120
needed.

cue-335
00:21:25.890 --> 00:21:30.680
What a God we serve, and to think so few
really know him. I know you'll

cue-336
00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:34.640
remember me in prayer, because that
filling of the Spirit is what I deeply

cue-337
00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:39.180
need. I've been aware of it for years, but
never really prayed through about it.

cue-338
00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:44.780
I remember reading that little book by
Andrew Murray, The True Vine, years

cue-339
00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:45.120
ago.

cue-340
00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:50.740
It made clear to me how necessary this
filling is. I stayed up most of the

cue-341
00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:51.429
night once,

cue-342
00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:57.020
then again the next night, and maybe three
or four nights, just waiting

cue-343
00:21:57.020 --> 00:21:57.580
on God.

cue-344
00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:00.100
But in the end, I gave up.

cue-345
00:22:01.060 --> 00:22:05.940
Now I know that if I had, like Jacob,
refused to let go until God gave me

cue-346
00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:10.600
the blessing, it would have saved me years
of backsliding, sorrow, and

cue-347
00:22:10.600 --> 00:22:11.040
trouble.

cue-348
00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:16.080
There's much more that could be quoted
from Emil's letters to this sister and to

cue-349
00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:20.760
his youngest brother, but the above is
enough to show that a new day had dawned

cue-350
00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:22.200
in his spiritual life.

cue-351
00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:27.380
To his own surprise, he found himself
talking to his patients about the things

cue-352
00:22:27.380 --> 00:22:28.030
of the Spirit.

cue-353
00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:33.920
His joy could not be hidden, for from the
overflow of the heart, the mouth speaks.

cue-354
00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:39.160
He even wrote to some of his patients, and
they too were brought into freedom and

cue-355
00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:44.120
light. His soul was set free, and he could
sing.

cue-356
00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:46.560
Now have I found obedience that is joy,

cue-357
00:22:47.240 --> 00:22:47.920
not pain,

cue-358
00:22:48.540 --> 00:22:53.060
not conflict of the heart and mind, but
harmony of human soul with God.

cue-359
00:22:54.060 --> 00:22:55.120
He understood the words,

cue-360
00:22:55.980 --> 00:22:58.120
I delight to do thy will, O my God.

cue-361
00:22:58.820 --> 00:23:01.060
Yes, thy law is within my heart.

cue-362
00:23:02.180 --> 00:23:06.760
He had let go of the anchor of caution and
had floated into God's vast sea of joy.

cue-363
00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:11.840
As mentioned in the first chapter, he had
left his home country on the last day of

cue-364
00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:15.580
1931 as part of the final group of the two
hundred.

cue-365
00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:19.840
We have already described the harsh
welcome he received when he arrived in

cue-366
00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:24.640
Shanghai, so now we continue the story
during the Japanese bombing of Chapei.

cue-367
00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:30.240
Chapter 3. The Language School

cue-368
00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:36.520
Under normal conditions, new workers go
straight to one of the two language

cue-369
00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:39.440
schools in China, one for men, one for
women.

cue-370
00:23:40.200 --> 00:23:43.800
But for Emil Fischbacher and his group,
the challenge was not getting into

cue-371
00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:45.720
Shanghai, but getting out again.

cue-372
00:23:46.880 --> 00:23:50.480
Thankfully, their delay was only about two
weeks, though others weren't as

cue-373
00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:51.060
fortunate.

cue-374
00:23:51.880 --> 00:23:56.580
After ten days in the tense, war-struck
atmosphere of Shanghai, he wrote home.

cue-375
00:23:57.300 --> 00:23:59.360
I've almost gotten used to the gunfire
now,

cue-376
00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:01.900
though it still shakes me up a bit at
night.

cue-377
00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:07.100
Every so often there's a huge explosion
that feels like it's right outside the

cue-378
00:24:07.100 --> 00:24:07.480
window.

cue-379
00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:10.920
Sometimes it almost throws me out of bed.

cue-380
00:24:11.620 --> 00:24:13.000
It really gets on the nerves.

cue-381
00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:16.400
I don't know why they always launch their
big attacks at night.

cue-382
00:24:17.872 --> 00:24:22.491
As a doctor, he quickly found work. The
Chinese hospitals were full of wounded

cue-383
00:24:22.492 --> 00:24:25.432
soldiers, and the local people couldn't
get medical help.

cue-384
00:24:26.132 --> 00:24:29.552
They came to him, and he was also asked to
help with other illnesses.

cue-385
00:24:30.412 --> 00:24:34.932
There were also necessary meetings with
leaders of different departments. Writing

cue-386
00:24:34.932 --> 00:24:37.102
to his family in a down-to-earth way, he
said

cue-387
00:24:37.772 --> 00:24:42.412
"I must say, the people here are amazing.
They'll do anything to help

cue-388
00:24:42.412 --> 00:24:47.332
us. You really don't grasp how massive the
China Inland Mission is until you

cue-389
00:24:47.372 --> 00:24:51.632
-see the headquarters here in Shanghai."
-Some of those helpful folks were doing all

cue-390
00:24:51.632 --> 00:24:54.622
they could to get these young newcomers
off to the language school,

cue-391
00:24:55.292 --> 00:24:56.282
but it wasn't easy.

cue-392
00:24:57.132 --> 00:25:01.712
After many tries, they finally got berths
booked and all the luggage, handbags and

cue-393
00:25:01.712 --> 00:25:06.472
all, loaded onto the ship. But the boat
wasn't leaving until noon the next day, so

cue-394
00:25:06.472 --> 00:25:08.362
they stayed at the mission house
overnight.

cue-395
00:25:09.122 --> 00:25:13.632
The next day, after hours of persuading
because the ship was docked at the

cue-396
00:25:13.632 --> 00:25:17.952
Japanese wharf, the Chinese taxi drivers
finally agreed to take

cue-397
00:25:17.952 --> 00:25:22.932
them. But when they arrived, surprise, the
boat had already

cue-398
00:25:22.932 --> 00:25:27.792
sailed, luggage and all. A break in the
fighting had given the captain a chance to

cue-399
00:25:27.792 --> 00:25:30.732
leave early, and he took it, passengers
or not.

cue-400
00:25:31.572 --> 00:25:35.892
It was frustrating but also a little
funny, and the young men began asking

cue-401
00:25:35.892 --> 00:25:39.852
around to borrow razors and pajamas until
they could catch up with their bags.

cue-402
00:25:40.912 --> 00:25:45.832
Five days later, they tried again, this
time determined to sleep on the boat

cue-403
00:25:45.832 --> 00:25:46.832
if needed.

cue-404
00:25:46.892 --> 00:25:51.612
But now no amount of pleading or money
could convince the drivers to enter the

cue-405
00:25:51.612 --> 00:25:56.532
Japanese-controlled zone. They had no
choice but to hire a river launch and

cue-406
00:25:56.532 --> 00:25:57.872
try to make their way to the ship.

cue-407
00:25:58.552 --> 00:26:03.452
"It was spooky that night," Emil wrote
home. "With all the delays, it had gotten

cue-408
00:26:03.452 --> 00:26:03.832
late.

cue-409
00:26:04.532 --> 00:26:08.652
Hardly anyone was out since there was a
ten PM curfew in Shanghai.

cue-410
00:26:09.412 --> 00:26:11.372
No one dared be seen outside.

cue-411
00:26:12.072 --> 00:26:16.452
We carefully passed at least a dozen or
more warships, Japanese,

cue-412
00:26:16.452 --> 00:26:21.192
American, and British, on our way to the
wharf. The Japanese admiral's

cue-413
00:26:21.192 --> 00:26:25.892
flagship was just a few yards away, but
nothing happened. We reached our

cue-414
00:26:25.892 --> 00:26:30.872
ship, surprised everyone, and were allowed
on board. What a sight we

cue-415
00:26:30.872 --> 00:26:35.852
saw. We had to crawl, climb, or squeeze
our way through a huge crowd of

cue-416
00:26:35.852 --> 00:26:40.832
people with all their belongings. They
were refugees fleeing Shanghai. This

cue-417
00:26:40.832 --> 00:26:45.632
was just a small boat meant for about
twenty-five second class and twenty

cue-418
00:26:45.632 --> 00:26:46.872
first class passengers,

cue-419
00:26:47.532 --> 00:26:51.932
but there were eight hundred and fifty
refugees on board along with everything

cue-420
00:26:51.932 --> 00:26:56.932
they owned. And another relief ship was
coming with one thousand five hundred

cue-421
00:26:56.932 --> 00:27:00.732
more. The air was awful. It still lingers
with me,

cue-422
00:27:01.352 --> 00:27:06.232
-but at least we were finally on board."
-The next morning, heading down the river,

cue-423
00:27:06.232 --> 00:27:11.152
they passed forty to fifty warships,
destroyers, cruisers, battleships,

cue-424
00:27:11.152 --> 00:27:12.772
mostly Japanese,

cue-425
00:27:13.512 --> 00:27:18.462
but the British were also there. Their own
boat had thick iron plates along the

cue-426
00:27:18.462 --> 00:27:20.352
deck to protect against stray bullets.

cue-427
00:27:21.282 --> 00:27:23.812
The scene along the river was horrifying.

cue-428
00:27:24.732 --> 00:27:28.592
Villages they had seen two weeks earlier
were now burned ruins.

cue-429
00:27:29.372 --> 00:27:34.352
The river, once full of boats and people,
was empty and silent.

cue-430
00:27:34.352 --> 00:27:39.292
This story reminds us that missionaries in
China, especially those in the forward

cue-431
00:27:39.292 --> 00:27:43.852
movement, were facing times as difficult
as Nehemiah when he rebuilt

cue-432
00:27:43.852 --> 00:27:45.092
Jerusalem's walls.

cue-433
00:27:45.752 --> 00:27:49.692
And to any young person preparing to go to
the mission field, it may be said,

cue-434
00:27:50.592 --> 00:27:51.752
if you choose to go with us,

cue-435
00:27:52.452 --> 00:27:54.192
following God wherever he leads,

cue-436
00:27:54.912 --> 00:27:56.392
be ready for rough roads.

cue-437
00:27:57.372 --> 00:27:58.912
But also remember this promise.

cue-438
00:27:59.852 --> 00:28:04.852
God is our Father, there as much as here,
and often nearest in the wilderness.

cue-439
00:28:06.752 --> 00:28:11.272
Hanking, nearly four hundred miles up the
Yangtze River, had been the men's language

cue-440
00:28:11.272 --> 00:28:12.952
school for over forty years.

cue-441
00:28:13.972 --> 00:28:18.672
It was first used during the great
missionary wave in 1887, known as the

cue-442
00:28:18.672 --> 00:28:19.092
Hundred.

cue-443
00:28:19.812 --> 00:28:24.192
When the Two Hundred followed over a
longer period, more housing was added to

cue-444
00:28:24.192 --> 00:28:25.071
meet the need.

cue-445
00:28:25.732 --> 00:28:30.732
There, among sixty-eight students, Emil
spent the next two months, a much

cue-446
00:28:30.732 --> 00:28:35.421
shorter time than most received. He didn't
describe the full journey upriver

cue-447
00:28:35.421 --> 00:28:39.952
through lands recently devastated by
floods, the difficult landing where there

cue-448
00:28:39.952 --> 00:28:43.082
was no pier, or the narrow, smelly streets
of the city.

cue-449
00:28:43.732 --> 00:28:46.082
But he did write about the training center
itself.

cue-450
00:28:47.242 --> 00:28:49.862
"Someday, I'll try to draw a map of the
place.

cue-451
00:28:50.652 --> 00:28:53.162
It's both a mission station and a training
home.

cue-452
00:28:53.882 --> 00:28:58.722
The church here is mostly independent, but
Mr. Martin Shepard spends most of his day

cue-453
00:28:58.722 --> 00:28:59.172
with us.

cue-454
00:28:59.952 --> 00:29:04.852
Mr. Haywood and Mr. Shepard stay busy just
keeping the classes running.

cue-455
00:29:04.852 --> 00:29:09.632
Just think of it. There are seventy-two
foreigners here. Sixty-eight of us are

cue-456
00:29:09.632 --> 00:29:14.392
learning the language. We've got seven
Germans, one Swiss, two

cue-457
00:29:14.392 --> 00:29:18.732
Swedes, two New Zealanders, eight
Australians, and people from

cue-458
00:29:18.732 --> 00:29:23.272
Texas, Arizona, Calgary, the Canadian
prairies,

cue-459
00:29:23.272 --> 00:29:25.032
faraway places,

cue-460
00:29:25.652 --> 00:29:28.052
four Scotsmen, and the rest are English.

cue-461
00:29:28.672 --> 00:29:29.932
Every one of them is great.

cue-462
00:29:30.672 --> 00:29:34.432
If people could see this place, they'd
really understand what the forward

cue-463
00:29:34.432 --> 00:29:39.352
movement of the CIM is all about. It's
amazing mixing

cue-464
00:29:39.352 --> 00:29:43.691
-with so many different nationalities."
-We won't go into the daily routine of the

cue-465
00:29:43.692 --> 00:29:47.312
training home or the many observations
Emil made in his letters.

cue-466
00:29:48.052 --> 00:29:52.252
But there is one important thing that
reveals his heart and can't be left out.

cue-467
00:29:53.072 --> 00:29:56.632
Emil's father had always hoped that his
children who became missionaries would

cue-468
00:29:56.632 --> 00:29:59.752
support themselves and not rely on mission
funds.

cue-469
00:30:00.632 --> 00:30:05.311
Emil found this idea appealing, but in the
end, he believed that being fully

cue-470
00:30:05.312 --> 00:30:08.752
united with his fellow missionaries was a
higher path.

cue-471
00:30:09.852 --> 00:30:14.371
For readers who may not know, it's worth
explaining that the mission's position on

cue-472
00:30:14.372 --> 00:30:19.272
special support was carefully worked out
by Hudson Taylor nearly forty years

cue-473
00:30:19.272 --> 00:30:23.904
earlier.To fully explain the arguments for
and against this issue would

cue-474
00:30:23.904 --> 00:30:25.343
require a long article.

cue-475
00:30:25.984 --> 00:30:30.604
In short, special financial support was
found to create many problems within a

cue-476
00:30:30.604 --> 00:30:32.754
mission based on faith principles.

cue-477
00:30:33.364 --> 00:30:36.984
From the general funds, the mission
provided for things like schools for

cue-478
00:30:36.984 --> 00:30:41.684
missionaries' children, rest homes for
their health, travel to and from Shanghai,

cue-479
00:30:41.684 --> 00:30:43.704
and other travel within China.

cue-480
00:30:44.784 --> 00:30:48.924
These funds also covered administration
and the upkeep of mission properties both

cue-481
00:30:48.924 --> 00:30:50.784
in China and at home.

cue-482
00:30:51.814 --> 00:30:56.384
A missionary's personal expenses were only
part of their overall share in this

cue-483
00:30:56.384 --> 00:31:00.024
larger structure. That's only one side of
the matter.

cue-484
00:31:01.404 --> 00:31:06.294
After careful thought, Hudson Taylor
concluded that aside from private family

cue-485
00:31:06.294 --> 00:31:10.584
arrangements, it was best for churches and
individuals wanting to support a

cue-486
00:31:10.584 --> 00:31:15.564
particular missionary to do so through the
general funds on that missionary's

cue-487
00:31:15.564 --> 00:31:16.304
behalf.

cue-488
00:31:17.704 --> 00:31:22.644
This is a broad overview of a complex
subject. In Emil Fischbacher's case,

cue-489
00:31:22.644 --> 00:31:27.124
he would have qualified under the family
exception, a matter on which the mission

cue-490
00:31:27.124 --> 00:31:28.964
had no authority to decide.

cue-491
00:31:29.564 --> 00:31:33.864
But Emil had so completely embraced the
faith-based principles of the mission that

cue-492
00:31:33.864 --> 00:31:37.724
he had no desire to be treated
differently than his fellow workers.

cue-493
00:31:38.704 --> 00:31:43.664
His hesitation in accepting his father's
offer led his father to write, saying it

cue-494
00:31:43.664 --> 00:31:48.074
was only natural and right for the family
to be his partners, not only in prayer but

cue-495
00:31:48.074 --> 00:31:53.014
financially. Emil replied, "Thank you so
much for your promise

cue-496
00:31:53.014 --> 00:31:54.504
to be my partner in the work,

cue-497
00:31:55.124 --> 00:31:57.284
not only with money but in prayer.

cue-498
00:31:58.004 --> 00:32:00.944
I'm beginning to see what that will mean
for me in the days ahead.

cue-499
00:32:01.654 --> 00:32:06.584
I've been praying that I might also be a
blessing to you at home. The

cue-500
00:32:06.584 --> 00:32:11.204
delay in accepting your offer was simply
because I wasn't sure whether it would be

cue-501
00:32:11.204 --> 00:32:15.644
better for the work if I were entirely
independent of the mission, that is

cue-502
00:32:15.644 --> 00:32:20.404
directly supported by you or supported
indirectly through the

cue-503
00:32:20.404 --> 00:32:24.664
mission. Really, before the Lord, there's
no difference between the two.

cue-504
00:32:25.344 --> 00:32:30.184
I saw that being independent had some
advantages, but being a full member of the

cue-505
00:32:30.184 --> 00:32:30.724
mission

cue-506
00:32:31.344 --> 00:32:35.984
on the exact same terms as the others
might be better for me. Honestly,

cue-507
00:32:35.984 --> 00:32:40.644
my natural tendency would be to prefer
full independence. There's

cue-508
00:32:40.644 --> 00:32:45.604
something that feels superior about it,
and I'm afraid I've often assumed that.

cue-509
00:32:46.504 --> 00:32:48.324
But now that I've joined a faith mission,

cue-510
00:32:49.064 --> 00:32:52.684
I don't think I have the right to hold
personal views on how I'd like to be

cue-511
00:32:52.684 --> 00:32:53.384
supported.

cue-512
00:32:54.064 --> 00:32:56.164
I had to take the matter seriously in
prayer.

cue-513
00:32:56.844 --> 00:33:01.004
I hope you'll see from this brief
explanation that it wasn't meant as any

cue-514
00:33:01.004 --> 00:33:01.954
kind of slight,

cue-515
00:33:02.564 --> 00:33:05.244
but just a matter of how I was relating to
God.

cue-516
00:33:05.984 --> 00:33:09.924
You mentioned how you've often wished for
a prayer partner to stand with you in the

cue-517
00:33:09.924 --> 00:33:10.444
business.

cue-518
00:33:11.184 --> 00:33:15.564
I may not understand the day-to-day
challenges, but I'll gladly take up that

cue-519
00:33:15.564 --> 00:33:19.963
role of prayer partner. I'll make it a
special point of daily prayer that God

cue-520
00:33:19.964 --> 00:33:23.544
will use you and give you the strength and
grace you need each day."

cue-521
00:33:24.964 --> 00:33:29.244
While this question was being worked out
between father and son, Emil went through

cue-522
00:33:29.244 --> 00:33:30.273
a time of testing,

cue-523
00:33:31.044 --> 00:33:36.004
somewhat like Hudson Taylor experienced
when the Chinese Evangelization Society

cue-524
00:33:36.004 --> 00:33:40.444
assumed his father was supporting him, and
his father assumed the society was.

cue-525
00:33:41.544 --> 00:33:46.284
Several times, the mission's treasurer in
Shanghai offered financial help, but

cue-526
00:33:46.284 --> 00:33:50.484
Emil, waiting to hear from his father,
held back from accepting it.

cue-527
00:33:51.444 --> 00:33:53.784
This led to a period of financial
hardship,

cue-528
00:33:54.484 --> 00:33:58.464
but it also gave him a special opportunity
to deal with God directly.

cue-529
00:33:59.444 --> 00:34:03.904
The experience had both serious and
humorous moments, but the full story can't

cue-530
00:34:03.904 --> 00:34:04.824
be told briefly.

cue-531
00:34:05.904 --> 00:34:08.444
Writing to his youngest sister, Emil said,

cue-532
00:34:09.184 --> 00:34:10.664
"Have you figured out what's going on?

cue-533
00:34:11.364 --> 00:34:13.844
Honestly, sometimes I just laugh and
laugh.

cue-534
00:34:14.604 --> 00:34:18.924
By the way, please don't say a word about
this. People will just think my letters

cue-535
00:34:18.924 --> 00:34:23.324
were delayed. It's not deception. I just
don't want anyone to know what's really

cue-536
00:34:23.324 --> 00:34:23.844
going on.

cue-537
00:34:24.484 --> 00:34:28.944
But don't think I'm discouraged or
anything like that. I'm feeling great,

cue-538
00:34:28.944 --> 00:34:29.724
better than ever.

cue-539
00:34:30.404 --> 00:34:34.964
This time in China has been one of the
most precious periods I can remember.

cue-540
00:34:35.664 --> 00:34:38.773
I thank and praise the Lord for every step
of the way.

cue-541
00:34:39.504 --> 00:34:43.384
I wouldn't have chosen it for myself, but
what a blessing it's been.

cue-542
00:34:44.384 --> 00:34:48.084
To have proven God's faithfulness is
something I wouldn't trade for anything."

cue-543
00:34:49.404 --> 00:34:53.164
This private matter has been shared here
because it shows who Emil really was,

cue-544
00:34:53.884 --> 00:34:58.824
a man who had fully and wholeheartedly
surrendered his life and everything he had

cue-545
00:34:58.824 --> 00:35:00.004
to God.

cue-546
00:35:01.104 --> 00:35:05.444
Within about six weeks of Emil
Fischbacher's arrival at Genking, Mr.

cue-547
00:35:05.444 --> 00:35:10.284
Host, the general director, came up from
Shanghai with Mr. A.B. Lewis to

cue-548
00:35:10.284 --> 00:35:13.064
assign the students to their future places
of service.

cue-549
00:35:14.204 --> 00:35:17.824
Although it was only early March, it was
important to avoid travel during the

cue-550
00:35:17.824 --> 00:35:21.144
intense summer heat, so these assignments
could not be delayed.

cue-551
00:35:22.064 --> 00:35:26.724
At this stage, Emil's letters give vivid
glimpses of what designation

cue-552
00:35:26.724 --> 00:35:28.444
fever meant in the training home.

cue-553
00:35:29.204 --> 00:35:33.684
To interview more than 60 men, discuss
with each one the direction of his life's

cue-554
00:35:33.684 --> 00:35:38.483
work, and come to a final decision in
every case was a major task for the

cue-555
00:35:38.484 --> 00:35:42.724
mission's leadership and a matter of deep
personal concern for each man.

cue-556
00:35:43.884 --> 00:35:47.164
Even before Mr. Host arrived, Emil wrote
home,

cue-557
00:35:48.114 --> 00:35:51.944
"I have a strong feeling I'm going to get
the biggest surprise of my life.

cue-558
00:35:52.784 --> 00:35:54.304
I really don't know what to think."

cue-559
00:35:55.264 --> 00:35:59.124
At Shanghai, he had often been seated next
to Mr. Hunter at meals.

cue-560
00:35:59.924 --> 00:36:04.394
"I was always put beside him," he wrote,
and he had begun to wonder if this was

cue-561
00:36:04.394 --> 00:36:05.064
intentional.

cue-562
00:36:05.964 --> 00:36:09.924
So when Mr. Host arrived, every day of
waiting became more intense.

cue-563
00:36:10.744 --> 00:36:13.923
Someone had to be interviewed first, and
someone last.

cue-564
00:36:14.764 --> 00:36:19.724
Emil turned out to be the last of all 68
students, and by then,

cue-565
00:36:19.724 --> 00:36:24.464
to use his own expression, his designation
temperature was running

cue-566
00:36:24.464 --> 00:36:29.129
high.The dinner bell rang before the final
word had been said in his interview,

cue-567
00:36:29.129 --> 00:36:31.980
and the conversation could not be
resumed.

cue-568
00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:35.240
But Emil had little doubt where he was
going.

cue-569
00:36:35.930 --> 00:36:39.600
He wrote to his family with what he had
already learned about Chinese Turkestan.

cue-570
00:36:40.940 --> 00:36:45.880
Two things were clear. First, he would be
nearly two thousand miles from his sister

cue-571
00:36:45.880 --> 00:36:47.820
in North China, and second,

cue-572
00:36:48.430 --> 00:36:52.080
there would be no hope of a hospital in
that remote region for many years.

cue-573
00:36:52.970 --> 00:36:56.240
"I had always thought of going to an
established setup," he wrote.

cue-574
00:36:56.940 --> 00:37:01.600
"It would be nice to go to a settled
hospital like Gray, Murray, and Pearce,

cue-575
00:37:01.600 --> 00:37:04.560
with a senior colleague to take
responsibility.

cue-576
00:37:05.190 --> 00:37:07.180
But, well, the work isn't mine.

cue-577
00:37:07.820 --> 00:37:12.100
It belongs to the Lord, so he has the
right to place those who would serve him."

cue-578
00:37:13.020 --> 00:37:17.240
This was the spirit in which he accepted
everything that followed. He had already

cue-579
00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:21.640
surrendered his little bit of right at
Swanwick, so he made no conditions with

cue-580
00:37:21.640 --> 00:37:26.500
God. His description of the group chosen
for Sinkiang shows how deeply

cue-581
00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:28.320
engaged he was in the assignment.

cue-582
00:37:29.210 --> 00:37:34.100
"The Sinkiang party right now," Emil
wrote, "is made up of five men,

cue-583
00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:39.160
and they're going up, God willing, with
Mr. Hunter. There's one from Tasmania,

cue-584
00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:44.140
Parsons. One from America, Scherner, a
German.

cue-585
00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:49.080
One from Australia, but born in China,
Raymond Joyce. One from

cue-586
00:37:49.080 --> 00:37:49.520
England,

cue-587
00:37:50.160 --> 00:37:54.880
raised in Singapore, Holmes. And one pure
Englishman, Drew.

cue-588
00:37:54.880 --> 00:37:59.780
If I go, it'll add even more flavor to
this mix of nationalities.

cue-589
00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:04.400
Funny thing, Scherner studied for two
years at Moody Bible Institute with Theo,"

cue-590
00:38:04.400 --> 00:38:07.760
Emil's youngest brother. "Isn't that a
coincidence?"

cue-591
00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:13.180
Just a week later, an airmail letter from
Shanghai confirmed Emil Fischbacher's

cue-592
00:38:13.180 --> 00:38:16.880
assignment to Sinkiang and asked him to
head to the coast without delay.

cue-593
00:38:17.790 --> 00:38:21.760
His sister had been called from Shaanxi to
meet him, since with nearly two thousand

cue-594
00:38:21.760 --> 00:38:26.360
miles between their stations, the chance
of seeing each other again would be slim.

cue-595
00:38:27.180 --> 00:38:28.640
Emil responded quickly.

cue-596
00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:34.200
He set his alarm for four AM, and after a
journey that he described as one

cue-597
00:38:34.200 --> 00:38:38.200
long jostling match, he safely arrived in
Shanghai once more.

cue-598
00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:44.500
Chapter Four: A School of Patience.

cue-599
00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:51.439
Being called to Shanghai by airmail
sounded urgent, but China has a way of

cue-600
00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:56.140
teaching patience, and those most eager to
serve often feel this lesson most

cue-601
00:38:56.140 --> 00:38:56.520
deeply.

cue-602
00:38:57.490 --> 00:39:01.640
Though the original purpose was to allow
him and his sister a final meeting before

cue-603
00:39:01.640 --> 00:39:05.980
his long journey to Central Asia, no one
imagined that nearly four months would

cue-604
00:39:05.980 --> 00:39:08.220
pass before travel was even possible.

cue-605
00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:13.680
Before diving into the many challenges of
the journey ahead, we pause to hear how

cue-606
00:39:13.680 --> 00:39:17.340
Emil impressed his missionary sister, who
hadn't seen him in years.

cue-607
00:39:18.340 --> 00:39:19.820
In a personal letter, she wrote...

cue-608
00:39:20.689 --> 00:39:23.030
"I expected to see a big change in my
brother,

cue-609
00:39:23.720 --> 00:39:28.240
but until we met, I kept wondering how
much of it would be just redirected

cue-610
00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:29.450
interest and energy,

cue-611
00:39:30.100 --> 00:39:32.560
and how much would be true spiritual
growth.

cue-612
00:39:33.820 --> 00:39:37.040
But even during the short drive from the
wharf to the mission house,

cue-613
00:39:37.680 --> 00:39:42.640
I saw enough to fill my heart with joy,
and that joy only deepened with each

cue-614
00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:43.870
moment we spent together.

cue-615
00:39:45.180 --> 00:39:50.060
Even my Scottish reserve, along with my
practical nature, was stretched to the

cue-616
00:39:50.060 --> 00:39:51.900
limit to keep my feelings in check.

cue-617
00:39:53.080 --> 00:39:56.040
I had to keep shaking myself to be sure I
wasn't dreaming,

cue-618
00:39:56.800 --> 00:40:01.100
and that the man beside me was really the
same brother who had carefully avoided me

cue-619
00:40:01.100 --> 00:40:03.240
almost the entire time I was home.

cue-620
00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:08.510
In the days we spent together in Shanghai,
I could almost watch him grow.

cue-621
00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:12.060
It was one of the most beautiful things
I've ever seen.

cue-622
00:40:13.060 --> 00:40:17.540
He had been awakened to the wonder of
spiritual life, and he was pressing on

cue-623
00:40:17.540 --> 00:40:21.960
quickly, drawn forward by the vision of
Christ. There were many people and

cue-624
00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:23.370
situations to talk about.

cue-625
00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:28.840
Though we had only been apart a few years,
we had so much to share of the Lord's

cue-626
00:40:28.840 --> 00:40:33.420
grace that even three full weeks in
Shanghai seemed too short for it

cue-627
00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:38.390
all. At the very beginning of our time
together, we made a promise

cue-628
00:40:38.390 --> 00:40:42.140
that our desire to be with each other
would never stand in the way of meeting

cue-629
00:40:42.140 --> 00:40:44.049
anyone else God wanted us to meet,

cue-630
00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:49.100
and God brought him quite a few such
encounters. It was a joy to see how

cue-631
00:40:49.100 --> 00:40:54.049
seriously my brother took these. One
evening, we were invited to

cue-632
00:40:54.049 --> 00:40:55.740
a small gathering of believers.

cue-633
00:40:56.460 --> 00:41:00.520
We had hoped for a chance to witness, but
the evening seemed fruitless.

cue-634
00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:03.660
Our hearts were heavy as we walked home.

cue-635
00:41:04.820 --> 00:41:05.940
Instead of going to bed,

cue-636
00:41:06.600 --> 00:41:11.480
we spent time in prayer together. It was
long past bedtime when we finally

cue-637
00:41:11.480 --> 00:41:11.940
parted,

cue-638
00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:17.100
and when I encouraged him, older sister
style, to get straight to bed,

cue-639
00:41:17.780 --> 00:41:20.500
he looked at me with a look I won't forget
and said,

cue-640
00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:22.180
'I can't go to bed.'

cue-641
00:41:23.340 --> 00:41:28.280
In his final note from Shanghai, hurriedly
written, he still made time to mention

cue-642
00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:29.580
two people he had met.

cue-643
00:41:30.200 --> 00:41:34.940
One, an assistant at a medical store where
he had shopped, and the other, a

cue-644
00:41:34.940 --> 00:41:35.820
Russian chemist.

cue-645
00:41:36.900 --> 00:41:38.500
He asked for prayer for both.

cue-646
00:41:39.810 --> 00:41:43.500
"The Russian chemist I haven't been able
to speak with again," he wrote.

cue-647
00:41:44.160 --> 00:41:48.200
"There's always someone else in the shop,
but I still have a small bill to pay.

cue-648
00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:50.200
Maybe I'll get the chance then."

cue-649
00:41:51.240 --> 00:41:55.660
So even shopping and settling bills became
opportunities for advancing the Kingdom

cue-650
00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:56.180
of God.

cue-651
00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:01.370
From the day, a couple of years ago, when
he gave his life fully to God,

cue-652
00:42:01.370 --> 00:42:04.500
the Lord tested his surrender to the
utmost.

cue-653
00:42:05.380 --> 00:42:08.100
God would not ask of everyone what he
asked of Emil,

cue-654
00:42:08.720 --> 00:42:13.590
but what God asked, Emil gave willingly.
When I came to China, God

cue-655
00:42:13.590 --> 00:42:16.160
didn't ask anything of me. He only gave.

cue-656
00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:19.030
But my brother's coming cost him dearly,

cue-657
00:42:19.720 --> 00:42:21.280
cost him at nearly every step.

cue-658
00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:26.920
Yet when we knelt together on our first
day in Shanghai, the first time I ever

cue-659
00:42:26.920 --> 00:42:27.620
heard him pray,

cue-660
00:42:28.340 --> 00:42:32.360
he thanked God with a full heart and said
words I'll never forget.

cue-661
00:42:33.124 --> 00:42:37.784
"Lord, it has not been hard at all, none
of it. You've done magnificently."

cue-662
00:42:38.684 --> 00:42:42.564
My brother had a deep hunger to know the
one whose love had captured him.

cue-663
00:42:43.604 --> 00:42:48.104
So he was allowed to walk the only path
that leads to a deeper knowledge of God,

cue-664
00:42:48.794 --> 00:42:53.784
the path of testing. One of his last and
greatest tests was

cue-665
00:42:53.784 --> 00:42:55.174
being appointed to Sinkiang.

cue-666
00:42:56.024 --> 00:42:59.714
Unlike me, Emil was very social, very
affectionate,

cue-667
00:43:00.384 --> 00:43:05.003
and for that reason and others, his whole
being recoiled at the idea of

cue-668
00:43:05.003 --> 00:43:06.944
Sinkiang when it was first suggested.

cue-669
00:43:08.224 --> 00:43:13.184
For some, Sinkiang might hold a sense of
adventure, but for him, there was no

cue-670
00:43:13.184 --> 00:43:13.644
thrill,

cue-671
00:43:14.404 --> 00:43:18.944
except the thrill of once again
surrendering his will to God. As soon as

cue-672
00:43:18.944 --> 00:43:22.704
he recognized the call as from God, he
accepted it with joy.

cue-673
00:43:23.604 --> 00:43:28.484
He wrote that it had become to him the
good, acceptable, and perfect will

cue-674
00:43:28.484 --> 00:43:28.984
of God,

cue-675
00:43:29.704 --> 00:43:33.124
acceptable simply because it was the will
of the one he loved.

cue-676
00:43:34.684 --> 00:43:35.984
The major question now was

cue-677
00:43:36.624 --> 00:43:39.864
how to get to Sinkiang given the difficult
circumstances.

cue-678
00:43:40.984 --> 00:43:45.964
There were three possible routes. Through
Kansu, the large northwestern province of

cue-679
00:43:45.964 --> 00:43:46.404
China.

cue-680
00:43:47.164 --> 00:43:49.524
It was slow but had traditionally been
reliable.

cue-681
00:43:50.164 --> 00:43:54.283
However, at that time, war had made this
path impassable.

cue-682
00:43:55.224 --> 00:43:58.684
Through India, crossing the vast mountain
range to the north.

cue-683
00:43:59.504 --> 00:44:03.924
This was extremely difficult and only open
for travel during a short window each

cue-684
00:44:03.924 --> 00:44:04.204
year.

cue-685
00:44:05.444 --> 00:44:09.964
Via Siberia, the longest route but the
most feasible under the circumstances.

cue-686
00:44:10.804 --> 00:44:14.324
The Trans-Siberian Railway offered a way
to cover much of the distance more

cue-687
00:44:14.324 --> 00:44:14.704
quickly.

cue-688
00:44:15.374 --> 00:44:17.834
This third route was the one most desired.

cue-689
00:44:18.564 --> 00:44:22.944
As early as April, an application had been
submitted to the Russian authorities for

cue-690
00:44:22.944 --> 00:44:27.824
permission and for a passport visa. But
the process dragged on with

cue-691
00:44:27.824 --> 00:44:32.164
endless delays, references sent to Moscow,
and many unknowns.

cue-692
00:44:33.384 --> 00:44:36.044
Eventually, the disappointing truth became
clear.

cue-693
00:44:36.824 --> 00:44:40.124
Soviet officials were unwilling to
cooperate with anything connected to

cue-694
00:44:40.124 --> 00:44:40.923
religious work.

cue-695
00:44:41.684 --> 00:44:44.304
So that door was firmly shut. What now?

cue-696
00:44:45.444 --> 00:44:49.544
Since the mission had committed, after
much prayer and thought, to a definite

cue-697
00:44:49.544 --> 00:44:51.644
forward movement into Chinese Turkestan,

cue-698
00:44:52.424 --> 00:44:54.984
it didn't seem right to simply wait for
doors to open.

cue-699
00:44:55.944 --> 00:45:00.844
As early as April, Mr. G. Findlay Andrew,
who had vast experience traveling in

cue-700
00:45:00.844 --> 00:45:02.904
China, even by air and motor,

cue-701
00:45:03.624 --> 00:45:05.564
quietly said to Dr. Fischbacher,

cue-702
00:45:06.184 --> 00:45:07.584
"Why not go by Mongolia?"

cue-703
00:45:09.044 --> 00:45:12.104
To some, this sounded like choosing to die
in the desert.

cue-704
00:45:12.824 --> 00:45:17.164
It was true that others had crossed that
way, but only with large, costly

cue-705
00:45:17.164 --> 00:45:18.003
expeditions.

cue-706
00:45:18.864 --> 00:45:23.814
The Citroën Trans-Asiatic Expedition, for
instance, had nine trained mechanics

cue-707
00:45:23.814 --> 00:45:26.064
and seven tractor-type vehicles.

cue-708
00:45:26.984 --> 00:45:31.404
Dr. Sven Hedin had also crossed the Gobi
Desert, but his mission was

cue-709
00:45:31.404 --> 00:45:35.124
well-funded and included scientists from
five nations.

cue-710
00:45:36.004 --> 00:45:39.064
Anything remotely like that scale was
completely out of reach,

cue-711
00:45:39.944 --> 00:45:44.124
and without such extensive resources, the
risk seemed too great,

cue-712
00:45:44.724 --> 00:45:46.584
perhaps even irresponsible.

cue-713
00:45:47.304 --> 00:45:50.984
Those who knew the desert best understood
its dangers most clearly.

cue-714
00:45:51.664 --> 00:45:56.404
But Emil Fischbacher, though he knew
nothing about the route itself, had strong

cue-715
00:45:56.404 --> 00:45:58.144
technical knowledge of vehicles.

cue-716
00:45:59.204 --> 00:46:03.704
Mr. Andrew's suggestion took hold of him,
and he quietly began researching and

cue-717
00:46:03.704 --> 00:46:08.444
planning. He even sent drawings home of
the type of truck he hoped to use.

cue-718
00:46:09.224 --> 00:46:13.484
In a letter dated June fourteenth, he
shared detailed calculations,

cue-719
00:46:14.244 --> 00:46:19.224
petrol consumption, fuel weight, baggage
allowances, the kind of vehicle he

cue-720
00:46:19.224 --> 00:46:23.644
favored, and the spare parts they would
need: propeller shafts, back

cue-721
00:46:23.644 --> 00:46:28.264
axles, crown wheels, differential gears,
pistons, connecting

cue-722
00:46:28.264 --> 00:46:33.224
rods, piston ring valves, bolts, nuts, and
ditch recovery tools

cue-723
00:46:33.224 --> 00:46:37.024
like planks, spades, picks, chains, and
ropes.

cue-724
00:46:38.304 --> 00:46:40.484
He mentioned that three in the group could
drive.

cue-725
00:46:41.124 --> 00:46:43.954
One was an engineer and another a
carpenter.

cue-726
00:46:45.034 --> 00:46:47.144
Then writing to his youngest brother, he
added,

cue-727
00:46:47.884 --> 00:46:52.403
"Do you think we're a scatterbrained lot?
Really, we're just eager to get there as

cue-728
00:46:52.403 --> 00:46:57.224
soon as we can, and this long delay seems
to be God's way of telling us to at

cue-729
00:46:57.224 --> 00:47:02.144
least consider other options. Every route
has its problems, but Mongolia,

cue-730
00:47:02.144 --> 00:47:06.204
while not without risk, seems the least
difficult overall."

cue-731
00:47:07.564 --> 00:47:10.284
In the end, the plan was officially
approved.

cue-732
00:47:11.104 --> 00:47:15.784
Emil Fischbacher, because of his technical
background, was given the responsibility

cue-733
00:47:15.784 --> 00:47:17.864
of purchasing the vehicles and equipment.

cue-734
00:47:19.024 --> 00:47:22.844
In many ways, this journey was unlike
anything in the mission's previous

cue-735
00:47:22.844 --> 00:47:23.604
experience.

cue-736
00:47:24.484 --> 00:47:29.464
Usually, young missionaries were entirely
dependent on experienced leaders.

cue-737
00:47:29.464 --> 00:47:34.124
But in this case, while Mr. George Hunter,
a veteran of over forty years in

cue-738
00:47:34.124 --> 00:47:37.814
China and the only one who knew the local
languages, was the team leader,

cue-739
00:47:38.434 --> 00:47:42.384
he had to rely fully on Emil for all
technical and transport matters.

cue-740
00:47:43.504 --> 00:47:47.524
Mr. Hunter had been so long buried in
Central Asia that he hadn't visited the

cue-741
00:47:47.524 --> 00:47:49.103
coast in twenty-five years.

cue-742
00:47:49.714 --> 00:47:54.484
The young missionaries, on the other hand,
knew nothing of Central Asia or its ways.

cue-743
00:47:54.484 --> 00:47:58.944
To prepare for the journey, Emil bought a
football for

cue-744
00:47:58.944 --> 00:48:03.624
exercise during long stretches in the Gobi
Desert. But to anyone steeped in old

cue-745
00:48:03.624 --> 00:48:07.584
Chinese culture, this seemed shocking and
out of place.

cue-746
00:48:08.444 --> 00:48:13.104
That small detail helps show just how much
this mission was an adventure of grace as

cue-747
00:48:13.104 --> 00:48:13.924
well as of faith.

cue-748
00:48:14.964 --> 00:48:18.603
Missionaries don't stop being human just
because they cross the sea.

cue-749
00:48:19.344 --> 00:48:23.824
And if the generational gap is sometimes
difficult back home, the clash between

cue-750
00:48:23.824 --> 00:48:27.804
East and West, between centuries of
difference, is even more profound.

cue-751
00:48:29.484 --> 00:48:34.364
On August sixteenth, Emil Fischbacher was
finally able to send home his first letter

cue-752
00:48:34.364 --> 00:48:39.248
from Peking, PeipingHe rejoiced that at
last, a real

cue-753
00:48:39.248 --> 00:48:40.808
move toward the field had begun.

cue-754
00:48:41.508 --> 00:48:44.608
Since we will later let Emil tell the
story of the journey himself,

cue-755
00:48:45.428 --> 00:48:49.288
only a few personal and technical notes
from his private letters are mentioned

cue-756
00:48:49.288 --> 00:48:49.488
here.

cue-757
00:48:50.388 --> 00:48:51.948
From his last letter in Shanghai.

cue-758
00:48:52.668 --> 00:48:55.988
I've long since broken all records for the
longest stay in Shanghai.

cue-759
00:48:56.748 --> 00:48:59.328
No new worker has ever been held up so
long.

cue-760
00:49:00.268 --> 00:49:00.808
Imagine,

cue-761
00:49:01.828 --> 00:49:05.968
I've been out over six months, and more
than four of those have been spent in this

cue-762
00:49:05.968 --> 00:49:06.388
city.

cue-763
00:49:07.188 --> 00:49:11.328
I can wander around Shanghai now with my
eyes practically closed.

cue-764
00:49:12.068 --> 00:49:17.008
During this long stay, Emil had served as
transport manager and had come to know the

cue-765
00:49:17.008 --> 00:49:17.608
city well.

cue-766
00:49:18.608 --> 00:49:23.088
Regarding the unrest in China, which had
to be factored into their journey, he

cue-767
00:49:23.088 --> 00:49:23.368
wrote.

cue-768
00:49:24.068 --> 00:49:28.828
Three weeks ago, Mr. Simpson was shot
dead, and just three days ago, we heard

cue-769
00:49:28.828 --> 00:49:33.488
that Mr. Tornvall, one of our associate
missionaries, and three companions were

cue-770
00:49:33.488 --> 00:49:38.388
also killed. Things are very unsettled.
There's also a fierce cholera

cue-771
00:49:38.388 --> 00:49:43.108
epidemic raging. We've just received word
that three missionaries have died.

cue-772
00:49:43.108 --> 00:49:47.828
-They were also associates.
-Emil also wrote to his medical sister

cue-773
00:49:47.828 --> 00:49:52.608
about not expecting a hospital in Sinkiang
for some time. His words show a deep

cue-774
00:49:52.608 --> 00:49:53.488
shift in purpose.

cue-775
00:49:54.208 --> 00:49:59.208
I don't want a hospital now. My mind has
been completely changed on that. I'm

cue-776
00:49:59.208 --> 00:50:04.208
truly out for souls. Don't think I've
gone batty. I really haven't.

cue-777
00:50:04.208 --> 00:50:08.568
In a small way, the Lord has given me a
vision of the need for souls and something

cue-778
00:50:08.568 --> 00:50:13.408
of the joy of leading others to Him. I
love medicine. I often

cue-779
00:50:13.408 --> 00:50:17.908
long to have a scalpel in my hand again,
but I never want it to take over all my

cue-780
00:50:17.908 --> 00:50:18.308
time.

cue-781
00:50:19.108 --> 00:50:21.788
It's a wonderful tool, surely God-given,

cue-782
00:50:22.408 --> 00:50:23.908
but it's not the goal itself.

cue-783
00:50:24.808 --> 00:50:27.448
I wouldn't write this to anyone but you
and Theo.

cue-784
00:50:28.288 --> 00:50:32.268
The balance between the spiritual and
professional aspects of medical missions

cue-785
00:50:32.268 --> 00:50:33.808
has long been discussed.

cue-786
00:50:34.488 --> 00:50:39.428
Since God created man both body and
spirit, healing the body alone can

cue-787
00:50:39.428 --> 00:50:40.788
never be the full aim.

cue-788
00:50:41.828 --> 00:50:46.807
Yet medicine is more than just a splendid
weapon. That phrase doesn't

cue-789
00:50:46.807 --> 00:50:50.568
capture the ministry of the Great
Physician or the care of a loving mother

cue-790
00:50:50.568 --> 00:50:51.787
for her child's health.

cue-791
00:50:52.928 --> 00:50:57.348
Such love is not merely a tool. It is an
expression of God's own heart.

cue-792
00:50:58.568 --> 00:51:03.568
Emil's words show a healthy resistance to
the danger every medical missionary faces,

cue-793
00:51:03.568 --> 00:51:07.468
the temptation to let the profession
overshadow the mission.

cue-794
00:51:08.508 --> 00:51:10.988
He did not want medicine to monopolize his
time.

cue-795
00:51:11.828 --> 00:51:16.638
There are always two ways to go wrong in a
calling that touches both body and soul.

cue-796
00:51:17.768 --> 00:51:22.668
We keep our balance in life not by
standing still, but by a constant series

cue-797
00:51:22.668 --> 00:51:27.668
of corrections, even while walking. So it
is in every calling, especially

cue-798
00:51:27.668 --> 00:51:29.088
one that seeks to advance.

cue-799
00:51:29.848 --> 00:51:34.188
In less than twelve months, Emil would lay
down his life through exhausting service

cue-800
00:51:34.188 --> 00:51:39.108
to men broken by war. With his God-given
skill, he could not have done

cue-801
00:51:39.108 --> 00:51:44.088
otherwise. Whether the wounded soldiers
were able to hear the gospel or whether

cue-802
00:51:44.088 --> 00:51:48.128
there was time for words at all doesn't
change what they experienced.

cue-803
00:51:48.768 --> 00:51:51.847
The love of God moving through the
surgeon's hands.

cue-804
00:51:53.048 --> 00:51:54.948
In those final difficult months,

cue-805
00:51:55.728 --> 00:51:59.988
Emil Fischbacher never spoke more
powerfully of Christ than through the way

cue-806
00:51:59.988 --> 00:52:00.597
he served.

cue-807
00:52:01.568 --> 00:52:05.548
Of old, the sick hoped that even the
shadow of Peter might fall on them,

cue-808
00:52:06.268 --> 00:52:11.028
and in the Crimea, wounded men blessed the
shadow of Florence Nightingale's lamp

cue-809
00:52:11.028 --> 00:52:13.108
as she moved among them at night.

cue-810
00:52:14.028 --> 00:52:16.008
It is the spirit that gives life.

cue-811
00:52:16.728 --> 00:52:18.148
It is the touch that tells.

cue-812
00:52:19.048 --> 00:52:21.188
This crust is my body broken for thee.

cue-813
00:52:21.928 --> 00:52:26.728
This water, his blood that died on the
tree. The Holy Supper is kept,

cue-814
00:52:26.728 --> 00:52:29.508
indeed, in whatso we share with another's
need.

cue-815
00:52:30.208 --> 00:52:32.668
Not what we give, but what we share.

cue-816
00:52:33.448 --> 00:52:35.908
For the gift without the giver is bare.

cue-817
00:52:36.638 --> 00:52:39.028
Who gives himself with his alms feeds
three.

cue-818
00:52:39.708 --> 00:52:41.608
Himself, his hungering neighbor,

cue-819
00:52:42.288 --> 00:52:42.788
and me.

cue-820
00:52:45.228 --> 00:52:49.988
After briefly considering the spiritual
side of medical work, we now turn to some

cue-821
00:52:49.988 --> 00:52:51.778
seemingly more ordinary matters.

cue-822
00:52:52.588 --> 00:52:57.568
But we don't need to be concerned about
this shift. The poet George Herbert

cue-823
00:52:57.568 --> 00:53:02.487
spoke of an elixir that makes drudgery
divine, and of that famous stone that

cue-824
00:53:02.488 --> 00:53:03.528
turns all to gold.

cue-825
00:53:04.248 --> 00:53:08.448
For whatever God touches and claims as his
cannot be called less than holy.

cue-826
00:53:09.688 --> 00:53:14.668
Now, we turn to dealing with the sand of
the desert, no small issue, and in this

cue-827
00:53:14.668 --> 00:53:17.948
matter, he earnestly sought God's
guidance.

cue-828
00:53:18.888 --> 00:53:23.668
One expedition across the Gobi Desert had
all their pistons and cylinders destroyed

cue-829
00:53:23.668 --> 00:53:26.028
because sand got in and quickly wore them
out.

cue-830
00:53:26.828 --> 00:53:30.948
This led to the need for special springs
and special air and oil filters.

cue-831
00:53:31.688 --> 00:53:34.908
Thankfully, he was helped by some
experienced advisors.

cue-832
00:53:35.828 --> 00:53:40.348
Mr. Findlay Andrew suddenly turned up in
Peking the other day, and I spent a couple

cue-833
00:53:40.348 --> 00:53:45.228
of hours discussing things with him. He's
had lots of experience with this kind of

cue-834
00:53:45.228 --> 00:53:48.208
travel, though he hasn't crossed the Gobi
himself.

cue-835
00:53:49.148 --> 00:53:53.988
Soderbom, a fellow Shaofu schoolboy,
Findlay Andrew, and I had lunch together

cue-836
00:53:53.988 --> 00:53:58.728
at a hotel. They shared so many
experiences that will be a huge help.

cue-837
00:53:59.688 --> 00:54:04.348
Findlay Andrew once drove a Ford truck up
to Lanzhou and had to dismantle the engine

cue-838
00:54:04.348 --> 00:54:05.808
three times along the way.

cue-839
00:54:06.508 --> 00:54:11.428
Soderbom, who crossed the Gobi with Sven
Hedin, told of a time at Etsingol

cue-840
00:54:11.428 --> 00:54:16.008
when his car got stuck in river mud and
slowly sank until only the top of the

cue-841
00:54:16.008 --> 00:54:20.928
windshield showed. Thankfully, the river
wasn't deep, but he had to wait until a

cue-842
00:54:20.928 --> 00:54:25.108
dozen or more camels could pull it out.
And of course, the engine had to be

cue-843
00:54:25.108 --> 00:54:27.228
completely taken apart afterwards.

cue-844
00:54:28.078 --> 00:54:29.888
Then Emil adds almost cheerfully.

cue-845
00:54:30.748 --> 00:54:35.548
Well, we're going to have quite the
picnic, aren't we? We're all young, and we

cue-846
00:54:35.548 --> 00:54:36.678
get along very well.

cue-847
00:54:37.856 --> 00:54:42.736
Finally, knowing Sinkiang's strict
censorship, Emil warned his family that

cue-848
00:54:42.736 --> 00:54:47.386
they should expect long silences from him
once he arrived, and not to be alarmed.

cue-849
00:54:48.196 --> 00:54:52.895
Besides physical and mechanical dangers,
there was also human danger on the

cue-850
00:54:52.896 --> 00:54:57.496
road. A report from the Citroën
expedition, which had crossed the Gobi

cue-851
00:54:57.496 --> 00:55:01.956
only six months before Emil's group, told
this chilling story.

cue-852
00:55:02.876 --> 00:55:07.376
Soon after midnight, we crossed into Inner
Mongolia and stopped at an inn near the

cue-853
00:55:07.376 --> 00:55:08.216
Ula Shan.

cue-854
00:55:08.876 --> 00:55:13.736
The next day, a 1919 Dodge arrived,
crammed with twenty-two men

cue-855
00:55:13.736 --> 00:55:16.416
so covered in dust they looked like
statues.

cue-856
00:55:17.336 --> 00:55:18.756
They were headed for Linggi Chang.

cue-857
00:55:19.496 --> 00:55:23.346
Before reaching it, three were killed, and
the rest were robbed of everything.

cue-858
00:55:24.656 --> 00:55:26.756
Such facts underline the serious risk

cue-859
00:55:27.516 --> 00:55:31.376
and highlight the merciful protection that
rested on the missionary team.

cue-860
00:55:32.076 --> 00:55:34.016
The good hand of God was upon them.

cue-861
00:55:36.496 --> 00:55:40.116
[gentle music] Chapter Five: Crossing the
Gobi Desert.

cue-862
00:55:42.636 --> 00:55:45.996
This whole chapter is taken from Dr. E.
Fishbucker's circular letter.

cue-863
00:55:46.776 --> 00:55:49.796
On August 13th, at Mr. Host's request,

cue-864
00:55:50.536 --> 00:55:54.556
I traveled with Mr. Hunter to Peiping,
Peking, to meet Mr.

cue-865
00:55:54.556 --> 00:55:59.276
Soderbom and make the necessary plans and
purchases for our long journey through the

cue-866
00:55:59.276 --> 00:56:04.176
desert. There were many such plans and
purchases. Each time I thought

cue-867
00:56:04.176 --> 00:56:09.036
of something we'd need, I wrote it in a
notebook. Before long, the list

cue-868
00:56:09.036 --> 00:56:13.816
was too long for one person to manage. So
when the rest of the team arrived, we

cue-869
00:56:13.816 --> 00:56:14.846
divided the work.

cue-870
00:56:15.516 --> 00:56:20.096
Otto Schoerner took responsibility for the
food supplies. Drew was in charge of

cue-871
00:56:20.096 --> 00:56:25.056
heating and lighting. Holmes became our
chief engineer. Parsons looked after

cue-872
00:56:25.056 --> 00:56:29.816
the supply of petrol, oil, radiator water,
and tire air.

cue-873
00:56:30.576 --> 00:56:35.516
Joyce became the head packer and also our
lead journalist. These titles were meant

cue-874
00:56:35.516 --> 00:56:40.476
humorously, but the division of labor
made everything run smoothly and saved us

cue-875
00:56:40.476 --> 00:56:45.196
a lot of time. For the trip, we bought a
large tent big enough for seven

cue-876
00:56:45.196 --> 00:56:49.696
people, ropes for packing and towing,
picks, a shovel, a

cue-877
00:56:49.696 --> 00:56:54.656
spade, Mongol fire-making tools, sheepskin
sleeping bags, and

cue-878
00:56:54.656 --> 00:56:59.336
much more. For the vehicles, we carried
many spare parts,

cue-879
00:56:59.336 --> 00:57:04.276
tires, springs, axle shafts, bearings, and
various electrical

cue-880
00:57:04.276 --> 00:57:09.276
items. We had to take all the petrol we
would need for the roughly thousand-mile

cue-881
00:57:09.276 --> 00:57:09.676
journey.

cue-882
00:57:10.316 --> 00:57:10.696
This,

cue-883
00:57:11.336 --> 00:57:16.216
along with the necessary oil, weighed
nearly four thousand pounds. Spare

cue-884
00:57:16.216 --> 00:57:20.505
parts, food, and other gear added another
one thousand pounds.

cue-885
00:57:21.136 --> 00:57:24.156
On top of that was the weight of eight
strong men,

cue-886
00:57:24.776 --> 00:57:27.516
six of whom brought all their belongings
with them.

cue-887
00:57:28.156 --> 00:57:33.136
That's why we bought two trucks, each able
to carry one and a half tons. There

cue-888
00:57:33.136 --> 00:57:36.636
were many challenges, but the Lord gave us
grace and wisdom.

cue-889
00:57:37.285 --> 00:57:40.516
The truck chassis had to be shipped from
Shanghai to Tientsin

cue-890
00:57:41.216 --> 00:57:43.736
while the truck bodies were being built in
Tientsin.

cue-891
00:57:44.636 --> 00:57:49.336
Once the chassis arrived, the trucks were
assembled, engines tuned, and

cue-892
00:57:49.336 --> 00:57:50.156
extras added.

cue-893
00:57:50.816 --> 00:57:53.596
Exactly fourteen days after we placed the
order,

cue-894
00:57:54.276 --> 00:57:59.176
I went from Peiping to Tientsin with
Holmes to collect the trucks. It was a

cue-895
00:57:59.176 --> 00:58:03.445
remarkable achievement and showed the
skill of the American Chinese company that

cue-896
00:58:03.445 --> 00:58:08.246
built them. We drove the eighty or so
miles from Tientsin to Peiping,

cue-897
00:58:08.246 --> 00:58:13.225
and the trucks ran beautifully. It was my
first time on Chinese roads,

cue-898
00:58:13.225 --> 00:58:15.225
and I was pleasantly surprised.

cue-899
00:58:15.886 --> 00:58:20.496
I had thought my driving days were behind
me, but it was such a joy to be behind the

cue-900
00:58:20.496 --> 00:58:21.066
wheel again.

cue-901
00:58:21.686 --> 00:58:26.516
The cabs were very comfortable, and with a
four-speed gearbox and excellent

cue-902
00:58:26.516 --> 00:58:29.436
suspension, they felt much like a light
car.

cue-903
00:58:30.196 --> 00:58:34.756
I thoroughly enjoyed the trip, especially
since Miss Deck from Kiwo,

cue-904
00:58:34.796 --> 00:58:35.276
Shansi,

cue-905
00:58:35.936 --> 00:58:40.316
rode with me and even took the wheel for a
while, driving like an expert.

cue-906
00:58:41.016 --> 00:58:45.436
It's hard to write everything I want to
tell you. There's just not enough space.

cue-907
00:58:46.166 --> 00:58:50.596
Please understand, if I seem to go on a
bit, that between any two events I

cue-908
00:58:50.596 --> 00:58:54.286
mention, there were often many others that
also deserve telling.

cue-909
00:58:55.145 --> 00:58:57.236
Some things have to be included,

cue-910
00:58:57.896 --> 00:59:01.696
even if they seem small, because they help
complete the picture of what

cue-911
00:59:01.696 --> 00:59:06.576
happened. On the evening of September
eighth, we loaded the trucks

cue-912
00:59:06.576 --> 00:59:08.936
onto railway flat cars to begin our
journey.

cue-913
00:59:09.636 --> 00:59:14.196
The experience was unforgettable and
exciting. The trucks had no

cue-914
00:59:14.196 --> 00:59:17.446
sides, so we had an open view the entire
way.

cue-915
00:59:18.136 --> 00:59:22.096
The scenery, especially through the Nankau
Pass, was

cue-916
00:59:22.096 --> 00:59:26.016
beautiful. Picture us eating lunch on the
open railway car,

cue-917
00:59:26.756 --> 00:59:31.616
one person sitting on the radiator,
another on the bumper, another on the

cue-918
00:59:31.616 --> 00:59:31.916
wing,

cue-919
00:59:32.636 --> 00:59:36.336
someone on the running board, and two
squatting on the floor with their legs

cue-920
00:59:36.336 --> 00:59:38.526
hanging over the side. Unusual?

cue-921
00:59:39.256 --> 00:59:44.226
Yes, but so enjoyable. We had little
trouble getting

cue-922
00:59:44.226 --> 00:59:48.316
the vehicles from the railway station to
the Methodist Mission compound, where we

cue-923
00:59:48.316 --> 00:59:51.426
stayed as guests of Mr. and Mrs. Soderbom
and Mr.

cue-924
00:59:52.216 --> 00:59:56.586
and Mrs. Williams. I cannot fully express
how kind they were to us,

cue-925
00:59:57.476 --> 01:00:01.076
but I must give special thanks to Mr.
Soderbom Senior,

cue-926
01:00:01.696 --> 01:00:06.356
who worked tirelessly during the three
days we stayed there. His greatest help

cue-927
01:00:06.356 --> 01:00:11.016
was in securing the necessary licenses for
both the drivers and the vehicles.

cue-928
01:00:11.016 --> 01:00:15.696
He also helped us greatly in finalizing
arrangements with our Mongol

cue-929
01:00:15.696 --> 01:00:20.496
guide, whom we had hired on the
recommendation of Mr. George Soderbom.

cue-930
01:00:21.256 --> 01:00:22.336
While in Tientsin,

cue-931
01:00:22.936 --> 01:00:26.636
I'd been warned that one of our biggest
challenges would be getting through the

cue-932
01:00:26.636 --> 01:00:28.456
customs barrier at Kalgan.

cue-933
01:00:29.496 --> 01:00:34.496
I wrote to Mr. Broomhall in Shanghai,
asking for special prayer on this matter.

cue-934
01:00:34.496 --> 01:00:38.996
Those of you who have been praying for us
may notice in this letter many clear

cue-935
01:00:38.996 --> 01:00:39.836
answers to prayer.

cue-936
01:00:40.476 --> 01:00:45.296
Sadly, because of censorship-I can't
mention many of the things that

cue-937
01:00:45.296 --> 01:00:50.216
meant the most to us, but here's one
example. It took us just ten minutes

cue-938
01:00:50.216 --> 01:00:54.555
from the time we reached the customs
barrier to the moment we shook hands and

cue-939
01:00:54.556 --> 01:00:58.386
continued on our way into what would
become our new homeland.

cue-940
01:00:59.036 --> 01:01:03.696
So it was that on the morning of September
13th, we began our unforgettable

cue-941
01:01:03.696 --> 01:01:08.676
journey. The first day gave us our
introduction to Mongolian roads.

cue-942
01:01:08.676 --> 01:01:13.636
At the time, we weren't impressed at all,
but looking back now, we'd almost have

cue-943
01:01:13.636 --> 01:01:18.636
to call it first class. The road twisted
and turned, was full of

cue-944
01:01:18.636 --> 01:01:23.606
bumps, and had many steep climbs, which
meant a lot of driving in low gear.

cue-945
01:01:24.436 --> 01:01:29.136
Since the engines were new and the
bearings tight, we had to stop several

cue-946
01:01:29.136 --> 01:01:33.756
times due to overheating. Thankfully,
water was easy to find,

cue-947
01:01:33.756 --> 01:01:38.456
so all we needed was a little patience,
especially since we knew the

cue-948
01:01:38.456 --> 01:01:43.316
engines would soon settle in. Just as
night was falling, we saw a small

cue-949
01:01:43.316 --> 01:01:46.756
village called Haishuihou, where we
decided to stop.

cue-950
01:01:47.416 --> 01:01:52.396
I'd heard many stories about Chinese inns,
but this first experience was a very

cue-951
01:01:52.396 --> 01:01:57.136
pleasant surprise. The cars drew much
attention as we unloaded what we needed

cue-952
01:01:57.136 --> 01:02:02.136
and got ready for dinner. We washed,
cooked, ate, and got ready for bed, all

cue-953
01:02:02.136 --> 01:02:06.996
under the curious eyes of a group of
Mongol onlookers. I was interested to read

cue-954
01:02:06.996 --> 01:02:11.576
in my diary for September 13th, Going
over pass to Changpei

cue-955
01:02:11.576 --> 01:02:16.156
Hsien, the toughest climb I've ever faced.
What a surface!

cue-956
01:02:17.016 --> 01:02:19.196
One car hit a mud hole and got stuck.

cue-957
01:02:19.856 --> 01:02:21.896
Our first digging-out practice.

cue-958
01:02:22.596 --> 01:02:27.316
Compared to what came later, that first
day would almost count as good going.

cue-959
01:02:28.056 --> 01:02:32.856
Still, the fact that we only managed
fifty-four miles shows you how rough the

cue-960
01:02:32.856 --> 01:02:33.516
road was.

cue-961
01:02:34.656 --> 01:02:39.616
I also noted in my diary that the cost of
the inn for the night was just one dollar

cue-962
01:02:39.616 --> 01:02:40.716
sixty cents total,

cue-963
01:02:41.896 --> 01:02:43.976
about three days each.

cue-964
01:02:44.596 --> 01:02:48.336
And before we left, we bought a sack of
potatoes for forty cents,

cue-965
01:02:49.056 --> 01:02:53.976
about five and a half days. That sack of
potatoes lasted us all the

cue-966
01:02:53.976 --> 01:02:54.616
way to Hami.

cue-967
01:02:55.436 --> 01:02:59.836
During the journey, we always referred to
the vehicles as either Holmes' car or

cue-968
01:02:59.836 --> 01:03:00.756
Fishbacker's car,

cue-969
01:03:01.376 --> 01:03:06.196
and for clarity, I'll continue using that
distinction. Each of

cue-970
01:03:06.196 --> 01:03:10.256
us usually drove the same vehicle, with
Parsons and I rarely

cue-971
01:03:10.256 --> 01:03:15.116
switching. In fact, all the younger
members of the team took turns driving

cue-972
01:03:15.116 --> 01:03:20.116
before we reached our destination. A
minor problem with Holmes' car delayed us

cue-973
01:03:20.116 --> 01:03:20.656
briefly.

cue-974
01:03:21.276 --> 01:03:26.085
That afternoon, we stopped for a short
rest at Hatin Sumu, a small Mongol

cue-975
01:03:26.085 --> 01:03:30.996
settlement. The Swedish-Mongol mission
there is doing excellent work, and we were

cue-976
01:03:30.996 --> 01:03:34.626
warmly welcomed by the Mongol pastor and
a group of schoolchildren.

cue-977
01:03:36.196 --> 01:03:39.956
Later that evening, we came across the
camp of Mr. Larson,

cue-978
01:03:40.576 --> 01:03:45.516
nicknamed the Duke of Mongolia, who had
once been part of the Sven Hedin

cue-979
01:03:45.516 --> 01:03:46.226
expedition.

cue-980
01:03:46.836 --> 01:03:48.856
With him were Mr. Lattimore,

cue-981
01:03:49.596 --> 01:03:52.936
author of The Desert Road to Turkestan,
and his wife.

cue-982
01:03:54.156 --> 01:03:59.136
Mr. Hunter had met Mr. Lattimore years
earlier during travels in Sinkiang, and

cue-983
01:03:59.136 --> 01:04:01.756
they enjoyed catching up and sharing
memories.

cue-984
01:04:03.416 --> 01:04:06.436
The next day, we traveled through rolling
steppe country,

cue-985
01:04:07.156 --> 01:04:12.156
mostly good terrain. But when I say good
roads, don't picture anything like the

cue-986
01:04:12.156 --> 01:04:14.136
main highways between Scotland and
England.

cue-987
01:04:14.776 --> 01:04:15.976
According to my diary,

cue-988
01:04:16.596 --> 01:04:21.356
I once dared to reach twenty-four miles
per hour that day, but the speed felt

cue-989
01:04:21.356 --> 01:04:25.966
so reckless that I quickly slowed to our
usual fifteen to twenty miles per hour.

cue-990
01:04:26.596 --> 01:04:31.536
The surface demanded constant attention. A
single careless moment could have led

cue-991
01:04:31.536 --> 01:04:32.436
to serious trouble,

cue-992
01:04:33.116 --> 01:04:37.976
even on these good stretches. As the sun
began to set and we crested a

cue-993
01:04:37.976 --> 01:04:38.296
hill,

cue-994
01:04:38.896 --> 01:04:43.416
we saw what looked like a beautiful little
city tucked into the landscape just a

cue-995
01:04:43.416 --> 01:04:44.436
mile or two ahead.

cue-996
01:04:45.106 --> 01:04:50.036
Our guide told us it was Sharamuren. What
we thought was a town turned

cue-997
01:04:50.036 --> 01:04:55.036
out to be a large lamassery, a monastery.
We were told the lamas

cue-998
01:04:55.036 --> 01:04:59.576
weren't particularly friendly to
outsiders, so we crossed the nearby river

cue-999
01:04:59.576 --> 01:05:04.336
and camped safely beyond it. That day, we
managed to cover another one

cue-1000
01:05:04.336 --> 01:05:09.156
hundred miles. The next morning, I vividly
remember stepping out of the

cue-1001
01:05:09.156 --> 01:05:14.156
tent and seeing the rising sun shining on
the monastery's pure white walls

cue-1002
01:05:14.156 --> 01:05:19.036
and ornate buildings. It was a strange
sight, such an elaborate place

cue-1003
01:05:19.036 --> 01:05:23.956
so far from any other sign of
civilization. Around this time, we began

cue-1004
01:05:23.956 --> 01:05:28.656
to worry about our fuel supply. We were
using much more petrol than expected,

cue-1005
01:05:28.656 --> 01:05:33.476
and it became increasingly clear that we
wouldn't have enough to reach Urumtsi at

cue-1006
01:05:33.476 --> 01:05:38.276
our current rate. So it was a great relief
when we reached Baili Miao, an

cue-1007
01:05:38.276 --> 01:05:42.496
important caravan crossroads, and were
able to buy fifty gallons of

cue-1008
01:05:42.496 --> 01:05:47.356
petrol. For reference, we had estimated
our total need at

cue-1009
01:05:47.356 --> 01:05:52.336
around three hundred and sixty gallons,
but to be safe, we carried four hundred

cue-1010
01:05:52.336 --> 01:05:56.916
and fifty. As you'll see later, even the
five hundred gallons we

cue-1011
01:05:56.916 --> 01:05:59.576
eventually had wasn't enough to complete
the journey.

cue-1012
01:06:00.696 --> 01:06:05.476
Leaving Baili Miao, we followed the camel
route toward Etsingol, passing

cue-1013
01:06:05.476 --> 01:06:07.656
many travelers, mostly Mongols,

cue-1014
01:06:08.296 --> 01:06:13.196
riding camels, horses, donkeys, or
traveling on foot

cue-1015
01:06:13.196 --> 01:06:14.036
and by cart.

cue-1016
01:06:14.676 --> 01:06:19.436
That day, we covered one hundred and ten
miles and camped in a small place called

cue-1017
01:06:19.436 --> 01:06:24.176
Chindamun, where there were only two or
three Mongol yurts. Yangchang

cue-1018
01:06:24.176 --> 01:06:24.756
Tsigo

cue-1019
01:06:25.416 --> 01:06:29.426
is the title written in our diaries for
Saturday, September 17th.

cue-1020
01:06:30.236 --> 01:06:32.416
Our official journalist simply wrote,

cue-1021
01:06:33.216 --> 01:06:38.135
Sandy, rocky, lumpy riverbed, twenty-four
miles of it.

cue-1022
01:06:38.136 --> 01:06:39.096
But for all of us,

cue-1023
01:06:39.796 --> 01:06:42.276
Yangchang Tsigo was more like a nightmare.

cue-1024
01:06:42.916 --> 01:06:47.640
It was the hardest section we had faced up
to that point.I don't want to imply that

cue-1025
01:06:47.640 --> 01:06:52.360
we were expert drivers or make much of our
efforts, but I do want you to see how

cue-1026
01:06:52.360 --> 01:06:57.080
clearly we were protected in situations
where a single mistake could have ended in

cue-1027
01:06:57.080 --> 01:07:01.920
disaster. That evening, we crossed a wide
riverbed and entered a

cue-1028
01:07:01.920 --> 01:07:06.840
narrow gully with deep, loose sand. Both
vehicles became

cue-1029
01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:11.680
hopelessly stuck. Only after much
digging, engine straining, and

cue-1030
01:07:11.680 --> 01:07:16.660
pushing were we able to get one vehicle
onto firm ground. We then

cue-1031
01:07:16.660 --> 01:07:20.320
had to tow the second one out, our first
time needing to do so.

cue-1032
01:07:22.100 --> 01:07:24.640
Sunday was a restful day spent in camp.

cue-1033
01:07:25.340 --> 01:07:29.940
A few Mongols passed by now and then, and
we were able to buy a sheep for seven

cue-1034
01:07:29.940 --> 01:07:31.710
dollars, about eight shillings.

cue-1035
01:07:32.360 --> 01:07:37.020
Seret, our guide, butchered and cooked it,
preparing excellent mutton and

cue-1036
01:07:37.020 --> 01:07:39.310
soup. We thoroughly enjoyed the meal.

cue-1037
01:07:39.940 --> 01:07:44.040
From my diary on Monday, September
nineteenth: A day of

cue-1038
01:07:44.040 --> 01:07:48.360
disappointments, and yet how can we help
praising the Lord for His goodness and

cue-1039
01:07:48.360 --> 01:07:53.340
protection over us? All the oiling,
greasing, and inspecting I did on the

cue-1040
01:07:53.340 --> 01:07:57.600
transmission couldn't uncover the cause of
a troubling knocking noise in my

cue-1041
01:07:57.600 --> 01:08:01.500
car. Sometimes it seemed to come from the
back axle,

cue-1042
01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:04.920
other times from the universal joint.

cue-1043
01:08:06.180 --> 01:08:10.900
We set off at nine-thirty AM, going
slowly. The terrain was

cue-1044
01:08:10.900 --> 01:08:15.600
unlike anything I've ever seen. The car
tilted dangerously time and again.

cue-1045
01:08:15.600 --> 01:08:20.220
Once, I went ahead and got stuck in sand,
but managed to free

cue-1046
01:08:20.220 --> 01:08:21.460
myself with some effort.

cue-1047
01:08:22.560 --> 01:08:26.340
Later, Holmes' car also sank deep into
sand,

cue-1048
01:08:26.980 --> 01:08:31.060
and we could only get it out after a lot
of digging and by using our long canvas

cue-1049
01:08:31.060 --> 01:08:34.820
strips, about a yard wide, reinforced with
rope.

cue-1050
01:08:35.540 --> 01:08:37.900
We all agreed they were worth their weight
in gold.

cue-1051
01:08:38.540 --> 01:08:43.240
Two hours later, we got stuck again, this
time in mud.

cue-1052
01:08:43.240 --> 01:08:46.600
Holmes took a different route and was able
to tow me out.

cue-1053
01:08:47.580 --> 01:08:50.780
A little while later, I hit a deep mud
hole.

cue-1054
01:08:51.540 --> 01:08:56.499
After half an hour of hard work with pick
and shovel, I finally got free again.

cue-1055
01:08:56.499 --> 01:08:58.920
The knocking sound in my car worsened
until,

cue-1056
01:08:59.520 --> 01:09:04.379
by one-thirty PM, we decided to stop. We
had only covered

cue-1057
01:09:04.380 --> 01:09:06.340
sixteen miles in four hours.

cue-1058
01:09:07.820 --> 01:09:12.760
The next day, we woke to a violent wind
and heavy rain, which made it impossible

cue-1059
01:09:12.760 --> 01:09:13.780
to work on the vehicle.

cue-1060
01:09:14.380 --> 01:09:18.880
The downpour lasted until late in the
afternoon, so we went to bed without

cue-1061
01:09:18.880 --> 01:09:23.860
making progress. But in the morning, the
weather had changed completely. The day

cue-1062
01:09:23.860 --> 01:09:28.780
was bright and clear. After a quick check
of the car, we realized we would

cue-1063
01:09:28.780 --> 01:09:33.400
have to remove the back axle and torque
rod to find the problem. It was a big

cue-1064
01:09:33.400 --> 01:09:38.380
job, but everyone got to work, and by
midday, the axle was free from the

cue-1065
01:09:38.380 --> 01:09:42.760
chassis. The differential was in perfect
condition, but after some

cue-1066
01:09:42.760 --> 01:09:47.759
searching, we found the trouble. A bearing
in the universal joint had come loose

cue-1067
01:09:47.760 --> 01:09:49.580
because its retaining spring was missing.

cue-1068
01:09:50.240 --> 01:09:54.680
Finding a replacement spring in the middle
of Mongolia seemed impossible, but that

cue-1069
01:09:54.680 --> 01:09:59.600
very morning, we had a small misfortune.
Someone broke a thermos flask.

cue-1070
01:09:59.600 --> 01:10:03.820
Seret quickly picked up the broken pieces
and pulled out the small spring

cue-1071
01:10:03.820 --> 01:10:08.680
inside. With a bit of heating and bending,
we shaped it into exactly the size we

cue-1072
01:10:08.680 --> 01:10:13.540
needed. It worked perfectly. Putting
everything back together took time and

cue-1073
01:10:13.540 --> 01:10:17.480
careful effort, but with many hands
helping, the job was finished by

cue-1074
01:10:17.480 --> 01:10:20.360
nightfall, and the back axle was fully
restored.

cue-1075
01:10:22.040 --> 01:10:25.820
Let me again quote from my diary for
September twenty-second.

cue-1076
01:10:26.460 --> 01:10:29.760
I wish I could introduce my friends to a
Mongolian dawn.

cue-1077
01:10:30.540 --> 01:10:33.220
Sunrise at six-thirty, glorious.

cue-1078
01:10:33.860 --> 01:10:38.240
Had a few issues with small repairs on the
car, but finished by eleven-thirty.

cue-1079
01:10:39.040 --> 01:10:44.040
Set off at two PM. Good progress for a
while, but then hit a few miles

cue-1080
01:10:44.040 --> 01:10:48.720
of jungle. While driving along the edge of
a dried-up riverbed, the bank

cue-1081
01:10:48.720 --> 01:10:53.520
suddenly gave way, and the rear of the car
slipped over. The two boys

cue-1082
01:10:53.520 --> 01:10:58.020
riding on top quickly jumped off, and
thankfully, the car came to rest on the

cue-1083
01:10:58.020 --> 01:11:02.960
back axle, though at a dangerously steep
angle. The doors were jammed shut,

cue-1084
01:11:02.960 --> 01:11:07.510
so Seret, Joyce, and I had to scramble out
through the near side window. I've never

cue-1085
01:11:07.510 --> 01:11:12.070
seen a car so close to flipping over. It
was another clear sign of the Lord's great

cue-1086
01:11:12.070 --> 01:11:12.790
protection.

cue-1087
01:11:13.420 --> 01:11:17.940
Sometimes, I could almost feel the prayers
being lifted up for us. I thought it

cue-1088
01:11:17.940 --> 01:11:22.400
might take twenty-four hours to get the
car out, but in just two and a half hours,

cue-1089
01:11:22.400 --> 01:11:25.600
we managed to build a road behind it and
drive it back up.

cue-1090
01:11:26.240 --> 01:11:29.620
Karat was the mastermind. An impressive
bit of work.

cue-1091
01:11:30.300 --> 01:11:33.679
We set up camp, having covered only
twenty-eight miles.

cue-1092
01:11:34.800 --> 01:11:37.520
The next day, we managed to cover a bit
more ground.

cue-1093
01:11:38.180 --> 01:11:42.540
My diary entry from September twenty-third
says, Up at four-fifteen

cue-1094
01:11:42.540 --> 01:11:47.440
AM. Brr, bitterly cold, but a beautiful
moon overhead.

cue-1095
01:11:47.440 --> 01:11:52.360
Later, seven PM. What a day. We did
seventy miles in eleven

cue-1096
01:11:52.360 --> 01:11:56.870
hours, but less than five of those were in
top gear. Each car used

cue-1097
01:11:56.870 --> 01:12:01.480
sixteen gallons of petrol. Road building
became our main task. The

cue-1098
01:12:01.480 --> 01:12:06.280
terrain is beyond description. Never
imagined a car, let alone a

cue-1099
01:12:06.280 --> 01:12:08.080
two-ton truck, could pass through it.

cue-1100
01:12:08.800 --> 01:12:13.520
On the twenty-fourth, we were up again at
five AM and on the road shortly after

cue-1101
01:12:13.520 --> 01:12:18.460
seven. The landscape was quite
mountainous, with many dried-up riverbeds.

cue-1102
01:12:19.120 --> 01:12:23.720
Later in the day, we entered a riverbed
that looked promising, smooth, and

cue-1103
01:12:23.720 --> 01:12:28.580
open. We made good progress for a few
miles, but suddenly, without

cue-1104
01:12:28.580 --> 01:12:33.020
warning, my car sank to the axles in thick
mud. I jumped

cue-1105
01:12:33.020 --> 01:12:36.620
out, only to find that the second car was
also stuck.

cue-1106
01:12:37.440 --> 01:12:42.400
Every attempt to lift the vehicles with
jacks failed. The jacks just sank further

cue-1107
01:12:42.400 --> 01:12:47.200
under the weight. It was clear we couldn't
go forward in the riverbed, so we began

cue-1108
01:12:47.200 --> 01:12:48.480
building a road out of it.

cue-1109
01:12:49.520 --> 01:12:54.100
We had to cut away a three-foot bank and
build a sloping ramp up to firm

cue-1110
01:12:54.100 --> 01:12:58.812
ground.We dug out deep channels for the
wheels and filled them with

cue-1111
01:12:58.812 --> 01:12:59.752
stones and brushwood.

cue-1112
01:13:00.432 --> 01:13:05.172
At that point, we expected to spend the
whole weekend stuck in that awful river,

cue-1113
01:13:05.172 --> 01:13:08.382
so it was a great relief, almost a
celebration,

cue-1114
01:13:09.112 --> 01:13:13.751
when after five and a half hours of
digging, shoveling, and hauling

cue-1115
01:13:13.752 --> 01:13:18.592
stones, we finally got both cars onto
solid ground. Hats flew into the

cue-1116
01:13:18.592 --> 01:13:23.571
air, and our Mongol guide shouted, "Let's
go." We then faced

cue-1117
01:13:23.572 --> 01:13:28.292
six miles of true cross-country driving,
all in second gear,

cue-1118
01:13:28.292 --> 01:13:30.732
followed by yet another riverbed crossing.

cue-1119
01:13:31.412 --> 01:13:36.412
Finally, we reached the Gobi Desert
proper. Just beyond the river, we made

cue-1120
01:13:36.412 --> 01:13:36.772
camp.

cue-1121
01:13:37.412 --> 01:13:41.232
Our speedometers only registered thirty
miles for the entire day,

cue-1122
01:13:41.932 --> 01:13:43.692
but we felt more than satisfied.

cue-1123
01:13:45.472 --> 01:13:49.412
Overall, the surface of the Gobi was
better than what we had experienced

cue-1124
01:13:49.412 --> 01:13:54.352
earlier, but it brought its own set of
problems. In many places, the ground

cue-1125
01:13:54.352 --> 01:13:58.972
was so soft that even walking caused us to
sink to our ankles. You can

cue-1126
01:13:58.972 --> 01:14:03.552
imagine what that meant for a two-ton
truck, and yet time and

cue-1127
01:14:03.552 --> 01:14:08.492
again, the vehicles, though often sunken
nearly to the axles, kept

cue-1128
01:14:08.492 --> 01:14:12.592
pushing forward. It was a hard test, and
we were continually

cue-1129
01:14:12.592 --> 01:14:17.592
amazed at how well the trucks performed
under such harsh conditions. We also

cue-1130
01:14:17.592 --> 01:14:22.112
encountered patches of deep sand, which
often forced us to take long

cue-1131
01:14:22.112 --> 01:14:27.112
detours to avoid getting stuck. My diary
entry for September twenty-sixth

cue-1132
01:14:27.112 --> 01:14:32.012
reads, "Utterly tired out, and it’s my
turn to wash the dishes. Too

cue-1133
01:14:32.012 --> 01:14:33.152
tired to cook much.

cue-1134
01:14:33.912 --> 01:14:38.212
Wish Miss Anderson, Shanghai, could have
seen how much we enjoyed her

cue-1135
01:14:38.212 --> 01:14:43.152
tea. Lots of digging and pushing today.
Incredible to watch these big

cue-1136
01:14:43.152 --> 01:14:43.652
trucks,

cue-1137
01:14:44.392 --> 01:14:49.392
sunk nearly to the axles in that soft
gypsum soil that’s so common in the

cue-1138
01:14:49.392 --> 01:14:54.292
Gobi, still pressing on. Had a stretch of
two and a half miles in

cue-1139
01:14:54.292 --> 01:14:54.842
first gear,

cue-1140
01:14:55.472 --> 01:15:00.452
flat out, the engine working its hardest,
and that alone used over two gallons

cue-1141
01:15:00.452 --> 01:15:05.412
of petrol." I mention that to show just
how much fuel we were consuming under

cue-1142
01:15:05.412 --> 01:15:10.192
such conditions. At this point, we
realized we didn’t have enough petrol

cue-1143
01:15:10.192 --> 01:15:15.072
even to reach Hami, but the Lord reminded
me of that verse from John ten, verse

cue-1144
01:15:15.072 --> 01:15:15.512
four:

cue-1145
01:15:16.182 --> 01:15:19.552
"When he puts forth his own sheep, he goes
before them."

cue-1146
01:15:20.392 --> 01:15:24.312
Even though there was little hope of
finding fuel in this remote part of the

cue-1147
01:15:24.312 --> 01:15:29.152
world, I felt completely at peace leaving
the matter in the hands of the Lord, who

cue-1148
01:15:29.152 --> 01:15:33.372
had already guided us so clearly. The
morning of the

cue-1149
01:15:33.372 --> 01:15:35.672
twenty-seventh brought fresh trouble.

cue-1150
01:15:36.592 --> 01:15:38.752
Just as we were setting off at nine AM,

cue-1151
01:15:39.412 --> 01:15:43.472
my car got stuck in soft ground after
moving less than five yards.

cue-1152
01:15:44.112 --> 01:15:49.072
Once we got going again, we had to take a
four-mile detour to avoid another bad

cue-1153
01:15:49.072 --> 01:15:49.892
patch ahead.

cue-1154
01:15:50.552 --> 01:15:54.192
Later, we stopped for quite some time to
decide on our route.

cue-1155
01:15:54.872 --> 01:15:59.872
In front of us were the wide tracks left
by the Citroën expedition that had

cue-1156
01:15:59.872 --> 01:16:04.252
come through about three years before.
They used vehicles fitted with caterpillar

cue-1157
01:16:04.252 --> 01:16:09.202
tracks. Drew commented that it looked
like Clapham Junction, and it really did.

cue-1158
01:16:09.202 --> 01:16:13.162
The ground was very soft, but we managed
to cross safely.

cue-1159
01:16:13.832 --> 01:16:17.212
Shortly afterward, the fan bearing in my
car seized.

cue-1160
01:16:17.892 --> 01:16:21.892
On checking, I found that the rubber from
the fan belt had almost completely

cue-1161
01:16:21.892 --> 01:16:26.262
melted. That gives you some idea of what
these vehicles were being put through.

cue-1162
01:16:26.872 --> 01:16:31.072
A note from my diary for September
twenty-eighth shows a different side of

cue-1163
01:16:31.072 --> 01:16:34.552
the journey. "This is the loveliest camp
we’ve had,

cue-1164
01:16:34.612 --> 01:16:39.192
tucked right away in the hills. Likely not
another living soul for miles and

cue-1165
01:16:39.192 --> 01:16:44.092
miles. Brought out the football and had a
proper stretch, just like

cue-1166
01:16:44.092 --> 01:16:45.872
back at the Anking Training Home."

cue-1167
01:16:46.652 --> 01:16:51.252
Of course, we’d had plenty of physical
labor, but this was a refreshing change.

cue-1168
01:16:52.012 --> 01:16:56.152
Although I’ve shared many of the
difficulties we faced and the hard work

cue-1169
01:16:56.152 --> 01:16:59.772
involved, I don’t want you to think we
didn’t enjoy the journey.

cue-1170
01:17:00.452 --> 01:17:03.312
I’ve often found myself wishing to be back
on the road again,

cue-1171
01:17:03.932 --> 01:17:08.872
and more than once, I’ve heard others in
the group say, "Oh, for the Gobi again."

cue-1172
01:17:08.872 --> 01:17:11.272
I haven’t written much about the scenery.

cue-1173
01:17:11.931 --> 01:17:16.112
That’s something others have described
more, but I can’t end this letter without

cue-1174
01:17:16.112 --> 01:17:19.892
quoting a few lines from my diary for
September twenty-ninth.

cue-1175
01:17:20.941 --> 01:17:22.112
"Up and away early.

cue-1176
01:17:22.872 --> 01:17:26.952
Sorry to leave this lovely camp. I’d have
loved to stay there for a week."

cue-1177
01:17:27.632 --> 01:17:32.332
Today, we went straight through a great
mountain barrier, climbing all day through

cue-1178
01:17:32.332 --> 01:17:34.212
absolutely beautiful scenery.

cue-1179
01:17:35.072 --> 01:17:39.672
One climb in particular took us up the
side of a mountain to avoid a stretch of

cue-1180
01:17:39.672 --> 01:17:42.812
sand. The gradient must have been one in
four.

cue-1181
01:17:43.532 --> 01:17:48.492
Every day, my idea of what the car can
handle is being challenged. I think

cue-1182
01:17:48.492 --> 01:17:53.172
the twin rear wheels have a lot to do with
how well it pulls. Then we reached a

cue-1183
01:17:53.172 --> 01:17:58.112
stretch that looked like a massive
highway, smooth as anything, and we sped

cue-1184
01:17:58.112 --> 01:18:02.452
along for miles. My speedometer actually
hit thirty-six

cue-1185
01:18:02.452 --> 01:18:06.482
MPH. After two weeks of crawling along,
that felt

cue-1186
01:18:06.482 --> 01:18:11.472
thrilling. Later, we hit some rough
patches and more of that dreaded

cue-1187
01:18:11.472 --> 01:18:12.542
gypsum surface,

cue-1188
01:18:13.372 --> 01:18:17.952
but what came next is hard to put into
words. It was, I think,

cue-1189
01:18:17.952 --> 01:18:21.912
one of the most beautiful and astonishing
sights I’ve ever seen.

cue-1190
01:18:22.632 --> 01:18:27.612
We came over a rise and found ourselves in
a vast basin surrounded by dozens of

cue-1191
01:18:27.612 --> 01:18:32.472
little hills, tier upon tier, one black,
one green, one

cue-1192
01:18:32.472 --> 01:18:37.412
red, one brown, one yellow, and so on.
Then we entered

cue-1193
01:18:37.412 --> 01:18:42.252
what looked like a massive amphitheater
ringed with small hills, but the

cue-1194
01:18:42.252 --> 01:18:47.112
floor was covered in wide fan-shaped bands
of color: cobalt, pale

cue-1195
01:18:47.112 --> 01:18:51.812
blue, bottle green, light green,
vermilion, brick red,

cue-1196
01:18:51.812 --> 01:18:55.162
buff, yellow, white, and more.

cue-1197
01:18:55.812 --> 01:19:00.392
I’m no expert on colors. While driving
through it, I turned to Joyce for help,

cue-1198
01:19:00.392 --> 01:19:05.220
but he was just as lost as I was. But it
was no illusion.As we passed

cue-1199
01:19:05.220 --> 01:19:09.540
through the colored bands, the ground and
stones beneath us really were those

cue-1200
01:19:09.540 --> 01:19:14.170
colors. It was truly one of the most
amazing sights I've ever witnessed.

cue-1201
01:19:14.170 --> 01:19:18.600
I've heard people talk about the Painted
Desert. Now I've seen it.

cue-1202
01:19:20.320 --> 01:19:20.970
At that point,

cue-1203
01:19:21.600 --> 01:19:25.720
we were still high in the hills, but the
road ahead of us was magnificent.

cue-1204
01:19:26.660 --> 01:19:31.440
For the next sixteen miles or so, we
descended rapidly on a surface that felt

cue-1205
01:19:31.440 --> 01:19:34.240
like a racing track, smooth and steady.

cue-1206
01:19:34.990 --> 01:19:39.920
My diary ends the day with, "And then to
see trees for the first time in many

cue-1207
01:19:39.920 --> 01:19:40.340
days,

cue-1208
01:19:40.980 --> 01:19:45.540
beautiful sand dunes, and a real river,
but it is Etsingol."

cue-1209
01:19:46.660 --> 01:19:48.400
That was a major moment for us.

cue-1210
01:19:49.020 --> 01:19:53.800
We had reached the halfway mark, and from
there on, the road ahead promised to be

cue-1211
01:19:53.800 --> 01:19:54.720
far easier.

cue-1212
01:19:55.340 --> 01:19:56.640
We left the camel path

cue-1213
01:19:57.260 --> 01:20:02.100
and headed toward a small group of four or
five tents, which our guide told us was

cue-1214
01:20:02.100 --> 01:20:04.860
the base camp of the Sino-Swedish
expedition.

cue-1215
01:20:05.530 --> 01:20:07.580
Our arrival caused quite a stir,

cue-1216
01:20:08.260 --> 01:20:10.850
and we received a warm welcome from Dr.
Horner,

cue-1217
01:20:11.480 --> 01:20:15.020
to whom we carried a letter of
introduction from a friend in Peiping.

cue-1218
01:20:15.640 --> 01:20:20.300
Before long, we were sitting on sheepskin
rugs around a table in Dr.

cue-1219
01:20:20.300 --> 01:20:25.270
Horner's tent, enjoying a splendid feast.
It was a real privilege to share

cue-1220
01:20:25.270 --> 01:20:27.280
experiences with such a gentleman.

cue-1221
01:20:28.440 --> 01:20:32.940
During our conversation, we learned that
Dr. Horner hadn't seen another foreigner

cue-1222
01:20:32.940 --> 01:20:37.830
for six months. More troubling, however,
was the news that the rivers we planned to

cue-1223
01:20:37.830 --> 01:20:42.540
cross were completely impassable.
Immediately, Dr. Horner offered his

cue-1224
01:20:42.540 --> 01:20:47.520
help, placing all twenty-five of his
camels at our disposal and offering

cue-1225
01:20:47.520 --> 01:20:52.040
us every assistance. It soon became clear
that we would need to remain at

cue-1226
01:20:52.040 --> 01:20:56.720
Oiatoroi for several days, and our host
insisted we use his Mongol

cue-1227
01:20:56.720 --> 01:21:01.680
yurt. A yurt can be described, somewhat
simply, as a portable

cue-1228
01:21:01.680 --> 01:21:06.660
Mongolian dwelling made of felt over a
light wooden frame.

cue-1229
01:21:06.660 --> 01:21:11.340
It was far warmer and more spacious than
our own tent. That's not to speak

cue-1230
01:21:11.340 --> 01:21:16.300
badly of our tent. It had stood up well to
storms of wind, rain, and sand and

cue-1231
01:21:16.300 --> 01:21:21.140
had truly been a home to us for many days.
But here in Oiatoroi,

cue-1232
01:21:21.140 --> 01:21:26.020
we felt like we were living in real
comfort. Dr. Horner would not allow

cue-1233
01:21:26.020 --> 01:21:31.020
us to cook for ourselves, insisting
instead that we share meals with him. He

cue-1234
01:21:31.020 --> 01:21:35.679
was the picture of generosity. Our time
in the Etsingol

cue-1235
01:21:35.680 --> 01:21:40.540
Delta felt like a true holiday, and we
were deeply thankful for it.

cue-1236
01:21:40.540 --> 01:21:45.500
My diary entry for October first reads,
"Sitting in my folding chair in real

cue-1237
01:21:45.500 --> 01:21:50.480
comfort. In front of me stretches a vast
desert plain with rolling hills in

cue-1238
01:21:50.480 --> 01:21:55.220
the distance, each one a different color.
To my right, more desert,

cue-1239
01:21:55.220 --> 01:22:00.160
with two small and two large lakes
visible far off. Both large

cue-1240
01:22:00.160 --> 01:22:04.730
lakes are ringed with tall trees. Behind
me, beautiful rolling sand

cue-1241
01:22:04.730 --> 01:22:09.500
dunes. To my left, a great inland sea
bordered with trees of

cue-1242
01:22:09.500 --> 01:22:14.480
every size. It's a perfect scene, a
delight to the eyes. The sight of

cue-1243
01:22:14.480 --> 01:22:19.480
water in this dry desert makes you feel
cooler just looking at it, but

cue-1244
01:22:19.480 --> 01:22:22.980
I'm glad I don't have to drink it, for
it's all a mirage."

cue-1245
01:22:24.260 --> 01:22:26.960
But our days weren't spent entirely in
rest.

cue-1246
01:22:27.830 --> 01:22:32.640
We still had serious matters to consider:
how to cross the five rivers of the

cue-1247
01:22:32.640 --> 01:22:37.620
Etsingol Valley and how to solve the
critical issue of our dwindling petrol

cue-1248
01:22:37.620 --> 01:22:40.649
supply. We also needed to find a new
guide,

cue-1249
01:22:41.280 --> 01:22:42.780
as Seret wished to return.

cue-1250
01:22:43.420 --> 01:22:48.280
At the camp, we discovered ten five-gallon
petrol tins that had been left by the

cue-1251
01:22:48.280 --> 01:22:52.960
Sven Hedin expedition. Through Dr.
Horner's kindness, we were

cue-1252
01:22:52.960 --> 01:22:57.260
allowed to purchase these fifty gallons
and arrange payment later at the

cue-1253
01:22:57.260 --> 01:22:58.780
headquarters in Peiping.

cue-1254
01:22:59.489 --> 01:23:03.480
That amount, we calculated, would at least
be enough to get us to

cue-1255
01:23:03.480 --> 01:23:06.400
Hami. You can imagine what this meant to
us.

cue-1256
01:23:07.520 --> 01:23:12.450
One great lesson this journey has taught
me is that the Lord has both material and

cue-1257
01:23:12.450 --> 01:23:15.940
spiritual resources that we never even
think of.

cue-1258
01:23:16.620 --> 01:23:21.560
Oh, that we would learn to trust him more,
to rest in his promises instead of

cue-1259
01:23:21.560 --> 01:23:25.899
living under the weight of constant fears,
worries, and cares.

cue-1260
01:23:27.520 --> 01:23:31.440
As for crossing the Etsingol Valley, we
faced two main options.

cue-1261
01:23:32.420 --> 01:23:37.400
One was to send our goods four or five
days westward by camel, while a few of

cue-1262
01:23:37.400 --> 01:23:42.140
us took the empty vehicles around the two
lakes, Sogo Nor and

cue-1263
01:23:42.140 --> 01:23:47.040
Gashun Nor, to avoid the rivers. But we
knew that the road around Gashun Nor

cue-1264
01:23:47.040 --> 01:23:52.000
was extremely bad, and this route would
add over one hundred miles to our journey,

cue-1265
01:23:52.720 --> 01:23:55.360
something our fuel supply simply wouldn't
allow.

cue-1266
01:23:56.030 --> 01:24:00.979
The second option was to circle around
just the first lake, avoiding three of

cue-1267
01:24:00.980 --> 01:24:05.980
the rivers while sending our goods one day
ahead by Dr. Horner's camels to

cue-1268
01:24:05.980 --> 01:24:10.920
a place called Nogan Deli. This plan was
chosen, and it was agreed

cue-1269
01:24:10.920 --> 01:24:13.760
that Scherner and Joyce would travel with
the camel caravan.

cue-1270
01:24:14.460 --> 01:24:18.920
So on the morning of October fifth, we
unloaded the trucks and transferred our

cue-1271
01:24:18.920 --> 01:24:23.919
goods to the camels. That afternoon, we
said goodbye to our cargo and prepared to

cue-1272
01:24:23.920 --> 01:24:25.760
depart with the vehicles the next day.

cue-1273
01:24:26.480 --> 01:24:31.020
We were sorry to leave the camp, but we
carried with us many happy memories of

cue-1274
01:24:31.020 --> 01:24:35.700
those six restful days, and especially of
our generous host, Dr.

cue-1275
01:24:35.700 --> 01:24:36.080
Horner.

cue-1276
01:24:36.770 --> 01:24:41.080
The first ten miles of the drive around
Sogo Nor were excellent.

cue-1277
01:24:41.840 --> 01:24:46.140
After that, though, we had about
twenty-five miles of difficult travel

cue-1278
01:24:46.140 --> 01:24:51.020
through alternating belts of gypsum and
sand. Although the surface was smooth,

cue-1279
01:24:51.020 --> 01:24:55.640
the engines had to work nearly at full
power the entire time since the

cue-1280
01:24:55.640 --> 01:25:00.380
wheels kept sinking deep into the soft
ground. We rarely exceeded fifteen

cue-1281
01:25:00.380 --> 01:25:05.040
miles per hour. The weather was warm, and
a tailwind meant the engines

cue-1282
01:25:05.040 --> 01:25:10.040
overheated frequently, forcing us to stop
often to let them cool. During one of

cue-1283
01:25:10.040 --> 01:25:14.790
these breaks, we took the chance to
explore the old bed of the lake.The ground

cue-1284
01:25:14.790 --> 01:25:16.500
was almost entirely white,

cue-1285
01:25:17.110 --> 01:25:21.970
a result of heavy salt deposits, and from
a distance it looked like freshly

cue-1286
01:25:21.970 --> 01:25:26.910
fallen snow. The lake itself was a
stunning deep blue, something

cue-1287
01:25:26.910 --> 01:25:28.910
an artist would be eager to paint.

cue-1288
01:25:29.570 --> 01:25:33.400
Strangely, there was no vegetation
anywhere near the lake.

cue-1289
01:25:34.170 --> 01:25:38.850
This is because both Sogo Nor and Gashuun
Nor, the Bitter Lake, are

cue-1290
01:25:38.850 --> 01:25:40.030
extremely salty.

cue-1291
01:25:40.710 --> 01:25:44.870
Animals won't drink the water, and no life
exists in either lake.

cue-1292
01:25:45.550 --> 01:25:49.350
For the first thirty-five to forty miles,
we drove due north.

cue-1293
01:25:50.010 --> 01:25:50.250
Then,

cue-1294
01:25:50.850 --> 01:25:55.850
after rounding the northern end of Sogo
Nor, we turned south again. The road took

cue-1295
01:25:55.850 --> 01:25:59.950
us into dense jungle areas, thick with
trees and shrubs,

cue-1296
01:26:00.550 --> 01:26:04.410
as this region of the Etsengol Delta is
unusually green.

cue-1297
01:26:05.110 --> 01:26:09.890
At times, we had to push our way through
the overgrowth. A few miles before

cue-1298
01:26:09.890 --> 01:26:14.690
reaching Nogoon Deli, where we were to
meet the others, we left the camel path

cue-1299
01:26:14.690 --> 01:26:19.380
and made a short detour to the Tergot
King's Palace to leave our visiting cards.

cue-1300
01:26:19.380 --> 01:26:24.250
Around four PM, we arrived at our meeting
point and found Scherner and

cue-1301
01:26:24.250 --> 01:26:28.850
Joyce already waiting for us. They had
thoroughly enjoyed their first camel

cue-1302
01:26:28.850 --> 01:26:33.129
journey and reported that the river
crossings had caused them no trouble at

cue-1303
01:26:33.130 --> 01:26:37.950
all. According to my diary, the trip
around the lake used about thirty

cue-1304
01:26:37.950 --> 01:26:42.930
gallons of petrol and ten gallons of
water, yet we had only covered just over

cue-1305
01:26:42.930 --> 01:26:47.890
fifty miles. Ahead of us now lay the
largest of all the rivers, the

cue-1306
01:26:47.890 --> 01:26:48.570
Oboingol.

cue-1307
01:26:49.330 --> 01:26:53.610
We were told that it had dropped slightly
in the last few days, but it was still

cue-1308
01:26:53.610 --> 01:26:56.210
impossible to cross using the vehicles
alone.

cue-1309
01:26:57.290 --> 01:27:01.910
After some discussion, we decided to move
our camp closer to the river and wait for

cue-1310
01:27:01.910 --> 01:27:03.990
a suitable moment to attempt the crossing.

cue-1311
01:27:04.690 --> 01:27:09.310
We returned to Wayal Taroi to borrow
camels from Dr. Horner, who kindly

cue-1312
01:27:09.310 --> 01:27:14.190
arranged for them to help us carry both
our cargo and eventually the

cue-1313
01:27:14.190 --> 01:27:15.870
cars themselves across the river.

cue-1314
01:27:16.600 --> 01:27:19.250
That day, we also said goodbye to Serat.

cue-1315
01:27:19.860 --> 01:27:24.410
Though he was eager to return, he later
came back and gave us much-needed help

cue-1316
01:27:24.410 --> 01:27:28.770
with the river crossing. He had been an
excellent guide and a tireless worker

cue-1317
01:27:28.770 --> 01:27:29.730
throughout our journey.

cue-1318
01:27:30.410 --> 01:27:35.250
Sadly, his replacement, a much older
Mongol, didn't quite

cue-1319
01:27:35.250 --> 01:27:35.830
measure up.

cue-1320
01:27:36.470 --> 01:27:38.370
He was not known for his work ethic.

cue-1321
01:27:39.070 --> 01:27:43.650
At first, we gave him the nickname Rastus,
then changed it to Ethelred the

cue-1322
01:27:43.650 --> 01:27:48.650
Unready, and finally settled on the more
dignified Sir Galahad, thanks to

cue-1323
01:27:48.650 --> 01:27:49.170
Drew.

cue-1324
01:27:50.790 --> 01:27:55.510
While we were camped at Nogoon Deli, we
received visits from many Mongols and a

cue-1325
01:27:55.510 --> 01:28:00.330
few Chinese. But the most interesting
visit came from the Tergot Mongol

cue-1326
01:28:00.330 --> 01:28:05.310
queen and her attendants. She thoroughly
inspected the vehicles and later joined us

cue-1327
01:28:05.310 --> 01:28:09.670
in our tent, where I gave her a few
biscuits. Drew brought out the gramophone

cue-1328
01:28:09.670 --> 01:28:14.660
and played some records, much to her
amusement. However, when he played

cue-1329
01:28:14.660 --> 01:28:19.650
a recording of Dame Clara Butt singing in
her deep contralto voice, the

cue-1330
01:28:19.650 --> 01:28:24.210
queen burst into fits of laughter. She and
her party later posed for a

cue-1331
01:28:24.210 --> 01:28:29.030
photo. It may seem hard to believe, but it
took us six hours to cover the

cue-1332
01:28:29.030 --> 01:28:31.890
three miles between Nogoon Deli and the
Oboingol.

cue-1333
01:28:32.590 --> 01:28:37.010
About a mile from camp, we lost our way in
thick undergrowth and didn't reach the

cue-1334
01:28:37.010 --> 01:28:41.990
river until after dark. The following day,
Sunday, we rested

cue-1335
01:28:41.990 --> 01:28:46.950
in camp. In the evening, we climbed a
nearby hill for a time of prayer and

cue-1336
01:28:46.950 --> 01:28:51.750
praise. We couldn't help singing, giving
thanks to the Lord for how faithfully he

cue-1337
01:28:51.750 --> 01:28:56.450
had led us. If those hills could speak,
they might have said they had never

cue-1338
01:28:56.450 --> 01:28:58.510
before heard the sound of a gospel hymn.

cue-1339
01:29:00.570 --> 01:29:04.710
Monday, October eleventh, was the day we
had set for the crossing.

cue-1340
01:29:05.370 --> 01:29:10.360
We rose early. My diary reads, "Cars
completely unpacked and

cue-1341
01:29:10.360 --> 01:29:11.610
brought to the crossing point.

cue-1342
01:29:12.230 --> 01:29:16.210
All electrical components removed or
covered with waterproof sheeting.

cue-1343
01:29:16.910 --> 01:29:20.030
Bed of the first car taken off entirely to
reduce weight.

cue-1344
01:29:20.760 --> 01:29:25.690
The load was taken over by camels in
relays, done very efficiently.

cue-1345
01:29:25.690 --> 01:29:28.950
Then camels were harnessed to the first
car, and off she went.

cue-1346
01:29:29.690 --> 01:29:34.330
After several minutes of shouting,
splashing, pushing, and pulling, the

cue-1347
01:29:34.330 --> 01:29:35.870
vehicle reached the far bank.

cue-1348
01:29:36.490 --> 01:29:41.330
I had expected real difficulty with the
swift current and deep mud, but the second

cue-1349
01:29:41.330 --> 01:29:43.850
time the camels knew exactly what to do,

cue-1350
01:29:44.470 --> 01:29:48.870
and the next car, with Parsons at the
wheel, almost flew across."

cue-1351
01:29:50.430 --> 01:29:53.430
That morning, camp was a hive of activity.

cue-1352
01:29:54.190 --> 01:29:56.130
Mr. Hunter was baking scones.

cue-1353
01:29:56.850 --> 01:30:01.170
Parsons was preparing a sheep we had
bought for five dollars, while Holmes and

cue-1354
01:30:01.170 --> 01:30:02.610
I dismantled the cars.

cue-1355
01:30:03.290 --> 01:30:08.170
Across the river, Scherner and Joyce were
working hard to cut down the riverbank

cue-1356
01:30:08.170 --> 01:30:12.870
so the vehicles could be driven up it.
Drew handled the receiving of our supplies

cue-1357
01:30:12.870 --> 01:30:15.430
as they were ferried over, and Sir
Galahad,

cue-1358
01:30:16.050 --> 01:30:17.430
he was sitting by the fire,

cue-1359
01:30:18.110 --> 01:30:23.090
smoking his pipe and entertaining visiting
Mongols, completely unbothered.

cue-1360
01:30:23.830 --> 01:30:28.230
Reassembly of the vehicles began
immediately, and by midday the following

cue-1361
01:30:28.230 --> 01:30:33.210
day, we were packed and ready to continue.
We had been advised to send our goods

cue-1362
01:30:33.210 --> 01:30:36.830
by camel across the last of the five
rivers, the Muringol,

cue-1363
01:30:37.450 --> 01:30:39.310
some fifty miles further west.

cue-1364
01:30:39.940 --> 01:30:44.930
We were told the terrain was too rough for
loaded trucks. After prayer and serious

cue-1365
01:30:44.930 --> 01:30:45.370
thought,

cue-1366
01:30:45.970 --> 01:30:47.970
we decided not to follow that advice.

cue-1367
01:30:48.710 --> 01:30:53.710
Imagine our joy when, by six thirty PM, we
had crossed the Muringol with

cue-1368
01:30:53.710 --> 01:30:58.220
little or no difficulty. If we had
followed the suggestion, we would have had

cue-1369
01:30:58.220 --> 01:31:03.150
to wait three extra days for the camels
to arrive and pay more expenses. It

cue-1370
01:31:03.150 --> 01:31:07.830
was yet another clear sign that the Lord
was guiding us, faithfully answering our

cue-1371
01:31:07.830 --> 01:31:12.730
prayers and the prayers of others. On
Wednesday, October twelfth, we

cue-1372
01:31:12.730 --> 01:31:15.010
broke all our previous travel records,

cue-1373
01:31:15.670 --> 01:31:20.538
covering one hundred and twenty miles in
one day.The final fifteen

cue-1374
01:31:20.538 --> 01:31:22.118
miles were driven in the dark,

cue-1375
01:31:22.738 --> 01:31:26.758
but our headlights proved strong enough to
let us follow the camel path without

cue-1376
01:31:26.758 --> 01:31:31.718
difficulty. That night, we heard wolves
howling nearby, but at no point

cue-1377
01:31:31.718 --> 01:31:36.198
during the entire journey was our camp
ever disturbed. I remember Mr.

cue-1378
01:31:36.198 --> 01:31:41.198
Soderbom in Peiping once telling me, "The
Gobi is the most peaceful

cue-1379
01:31:41.198 --> 01:31:45.998
spot in the world." That's certainly how
it seemed to us. The stillness and

cue-1380
01:31:45.998 --> 01:31:50.878
silence of a Gobi night is something that
must be experienced. It

cue-1381
01:31:50.878 --> 01:31:52.078
cannot be described.

cue-1382
01:31:52.698 --> 01:31:57.498
We later learned that, particularly toward
the end of our journey across the Gobi,

cue-1383
01:31:58.158 --> 01:32:01.478
we had been preserved from very real and
present dangers,

cue-1384
01:32:02.138 --> 01:32:06.638
things we only discovered after reaching
our destination. But the Lord's

cue-1385
01:32:06.638 --> 01:32:11.458
purposes are never hindered when we wait
on Him in quiet, trusting

cue-1386
01:32:11.458 --> 01:32:11.778
faith.

cue-1387
01:32:12.478 --> 01:32:17.058
Then, on October fourteenth, we crossed
into the province of Sinkiang,

cue-1388
01:32:17.758 --> 01:32:22.578
a moment of great significance for us. My
diary entry for that day reads,

cue-1389
01:32:22.578 --> 01:32:27.498
"Real wintry blasts, likely due to the
high altitude. Rough

cue-1390
01:32:27.498 --> 01:32:32.378
going all morning. We had to constantly
scout for a passable route. Sir

cue-1391
01:32:32.378 --> 01:32:36.678
Galahad, our guide, was uncertain and
hesitant. In the

cue-1392
01:32:36.678 --> 01:32:41.538
distance, we spotted three camels and
three horses, along with two men.

cue-1393
01:32:41.538 --> 01:32:46.498
These were the first living beings we'd
seen in three days. But as we drew

cue-1394
01:32:46.498 --> 01:32:51.298
near, the two men suddenly jumped on their
horses and rode off toward the hills as

cue-1395
01:32:51.298 --> 01:32:56.018
fast as they could, clearly terrified at
the sight of two huge monsters,

cue-1396
01:32:56.698 --> 01:32:58.798
our trucks, coming at speed.

cue-1397
01:32:59.458 --> 01:33:04.278
As we passed, we saw the camels and the
remaining horse still standing there,

cue-1398
01:33:04.278 --> 01:33:08.918
heavily loaded and calmly waiting,
completely unaware that their

cue-1399
01:33:08.918 --> 01:33:10.038
masters had fled.

cue-1400
01:33:11.198 --> 01:33:15.498
We were within view of those camels for
nearly an hour, but never saw the men

cue-1401
01:33:15.498 --> 01:33:20.378
again." Another diary note reads, "Saw
strange pyramid-like

cue-1402
01:33:20.378 --> 01:33:24.958
mounds, about seven of them. This marked
the old customs barrier.

cue-1403
01:33:24.958 --> 01:33:29.777
The area was uninhabited, dry, and barren
of any

cue-1404
01:33:29.777 --> 01:33:30.538
vegetation.

cue-1405
01:33:31.158 --> 01:33:34.098
The only water we could find was brackish
and salty.

cue-1406
01:33:34.818 --> 01:33:36.678
We stopped for the night at Mingshui.

cue-1407
01:33:37.438 --> 01:33:42.218
The next morning, the thermometer read
fifteen degrees of frost, and the wind was

cue-1408
01:33:42.218 --> 01:33:43.278
bitterly cold.

cue-1409
01:33:43.918 --> 01:33:48.838
We could hardly turn the engine cranks. It
wasn't until we lit a large fire and

cue-1410
01:33:48.838 --> 01:33:52.918
heated water to pour into the radiators
that we were finally able to get the

cue-1411
01:33:52.918 --> 01:33:53.868
engine started.

cue-1412
01:33:54.578 --> 01:33:56.518
Sunday, October sixteenth.

cue-1413
01:33:57.418 --> 01:34:02.318
A glorious scene. The most beautiful
campsite we've had yet, in

cue-1414
01:34:02.318 --> 01:34:07.178
a hollow, protected from the northern wind
and just a few yards from a

cue-1415
01:34:07.178 --> 01:34:11.898
bubbling mountain stream. To the north
stood the Karlik Mountains,

cue-1416
01:34:12.698 --> 01:34:16.067
snow-covered and rising thirteen thousand
feet above us.

cue-1417
01:34:16.978 --> 01:34:17.838
To the south

cue-1418
01:34:18.438 --> 01:34:22.058
stretched the vast Gobi Plain, looking
like a great sea."

cue-1419
01:34:23.198 --> 01:34:25.878
Could there have been a more perfect place
to spend a Sunday?

cue-1420
01:34:26.678 --> 01:34:31.658
Yet circumstances made it wise to keep
moving. So, though reluctant,

cue-1421
01:34:31.658 --> 01:34:34.518
we packed up and continued our journey.

cue-1422
01:34:35.738 --> 01:34:40.498
We entered Hami quietly, without any
announcement, and were able to go

cue-1423
01:34:40.498 --> 01:34:44.938
directly to an inn where Mr. Hunter and
the Misses French and Cable had stayed

cue-1424
01:34:44.938 --> 01:34:49.178
before. We ended up staying there for two
weeks. During that

cue-1425
01:34:49.178 --> 01:34:52.898
time, the innkeeper did everything he
could to make us comfortable.

cue-1426
01:34:53.858 --> 01:34:58.698
I was truly amazed by his generosity. He
seemed never to tire of finding

cue-1427
01:34:58.698 --> 01:34:59.597
ways to help us.

cue-1428
01:35:00.418 --> 01:35:05.378
I was glad I could offer some medical help
to his wife, especially since he firmly

cue-1429
01:35:05.378 --> 01:35:07.098
refused any payment in return.

cue-1430
01:35:07.718 --> 01:35:12.678
When we arrived in Hami, we had only about
ten gallons of petrol left for each

cue-1431
01:35:12.678 --> 01:35:13.038
car,

cue-1432
01:35:13.758 --> 01:35:18.498
barely enough to go another sixty miles.
We didn't know the exact distance from

cue-1433
01:35:18.498 --> 01:35:19.478
Kalgan to Tihwa,

cue-1434
01:35:20.178 --> 01:35:22.818
nor could we estimate how much petrol we
would need.

cue-1435
01:35:23.438 --> 01:35:27.738
We simply brought what we thought would be
enough for the whole journey. But the

cue-1436
01:35:27.738 --> 01:35:32.428
Lord knew our needs far better than we
did, and at every stage, He

cue-1437
01:35:32.428 --> 01:35:34.478
supplied exactly what we required.

cue-1438
01:35:35.078 --> 01:35:36.757
Not once did we run short.

cue-1439
01:35:38.358 --> 01:35:39.947
And what about the rest of the journey?

cue-1440
01:35:40.638 --> 01:35:42.478
Let me repeat what I wrote earlier:

cue-1441
01:35:43.078 --> 01:35:46.298
The Lord has sources of supply of which we
little dream.

cue-1442
01:35:47.438 --> 01:35:51.978
The road to Kucheung was mostly
uneventful, though still very interesting.

cue-1443
01:35:51.978 --> 01:35:56.798
It felt good to be traveling again,
especially in our own

cue-1444
01:35:56.798 --> 01:35:57.398
vehicles.

cue-1445
01:35:58.318 --> 01:36:00.658
For those interested in the details of the
route,

cue-1446
01:36:01.458 --> 01:36:03.878
I'd refer you to the book Through Jade
Gate,

cue-1447
01:36:04.558 --> 01:36:06.738
written by the Misses French and Cable.

cue-1448
01:36:07.378 --> 01:36:11.458
On page two hundred and nine and
following, they describe the road from

cue-1449
01:36:11.458 --> 01:36:12.818
Hami to Tihwa.

cue-1450
01:36:13.918 --> 01:36:16.918
If you read it while imagining cars
instead of carts,

cue-1451
01:36:17.558 --> 01:36:19.998
you'll have a good sense of what our
journey was like.

cue-1452
01:36:20.698 --> 01:36:25.518
We stayed in Kucheung for six days. Then
we made the final leg of the journey,

cue-1453
01:36:26.178 --> 01:36:28.658
a wonderful one hundred and thirty miles.

cue-1454
01:36:29.298 --> 01:36:34.258
The road was excellent, and it took only
about six hours. At noon

cue-1455
01:36:34.258 --> 01:36:38.837
on November ninth, we made our
long-anticipated arrival in

cue-1456
01:36:38.838 --> 01:36:41.578
Ürümqi, the capital of Chinese Turkestan.

cue-1457
01:36:43.058 --> 01:36:47.718
What a welcome we received from Mr.
Mather. We won't forget it. Our

cue-1458
01:36:47.718 --> 01:36:52.158
arrival brought to an end a long season of
waiting for him. That

cue-1459
01:36:52.158 --> 01:36:57.098
evening, we gathered together for a time
of prayer and praise. We especially

cue-1460
01:36:57.098 --> 01:37:01.918
thanked God for all those around the world
who had faithfully prayed for us. This

cue-1461
01:37:01.918 --> 01:37:06.678
letter gives you just a glimpse of what
the Lord did for us, but much remains

cue-1462
01:37:06.678 --> 01:37:11.658
unwritten. Still, I can confidently say
the Lord truly answered

cue-1463
01:37:11.658 --> 01:37:16.638
your prayers exceeding abundantly. That
evening, Mr. Mather read to

cue-1464
01:37:16.638 --> 01:37:21.438
us Psalm one hundred and eighteen, and
how perfectly it described our journey

cue-1465
01:37:21.438 --> 01:37:26.398
and all the Lord had brought us
through.And now, before

cue-1466
01:37:26.398 --> 01:37:30.937
I end this long letter, I must draw your
attention to one striking and

cue-1467
01:37:30.938 --> 01:37:35.938
sobering fact revealed by our journey.
Over the entire one thousand

cue-1468
01:37:35.938 --> 01:37:39.878
eight hundred miles we traveled, we passed
only one mission station,

cue-1469
01:37:40.558 --> 01:37:45.538
just one place where the gospel of Jesus
Christ is being proclaimed. What about the

cue-1470
01:37:45.538 --> 01:37:50.418
people living in the many small villages
we passed through? What of the

cue-1471
01:37:50.418 --> 01:37:53.558
tribes scattered across the vast Mongolian
plains?

cue-1472
01:37:54.538 --> 01:37:58.618
What of the Mongol communities
concentrated in places like the Etsingol

cue-1473
01:37:58.618 --> 01:38:02.538
Delta? And what of the large cities
throughout this province?

cue-1474
01:38:03.398 --> 01:38:06.718
How shall they believe in him of whom they
have not heard?

cue-1475
01:38:07.718 --> 01:38:09.738
And how shall they hear without a
preacher?

cue-1476
01:38:10.918 --> 01:38:12.338
Is this not a call to prayer?

cue-1477
01:38:13.038 --> 01:38:17.298
And does it not also come as a personal
challenge to some young people in the

cue-1478
01:38:17.298 --> 01:38:17.898
homelands

cue-1479
01:38:18.578 --> 01:38:20.658
who are seeking God's will for their
lives?

cue-1480
01:38:21.638 --> 01:38:26.458
Pray ye therefore the Lord of the harvest,
that he will send forth laborers

cue-1481
01:38:26.458 --> 01:38:27.578
into his harvest.

cue-1482
01:38:31.038 --> 01:38:31.798
Chapter six:

cue-1483
01:38:32.698 --> 01:38:34.038
Chinese Turkestan.

cue-1484
01:38:36.978 --> 01:38:41.958
Chinese Turkestan, now known as Sinkiang,
is that vast region of China

cue-1485
01:38:41.958 --> 01:38:46.938
which stretches deep into the heart of
Asia. Its area is roughly equal to

cue-1486
01:38:46.938 --> 01:38:49.798
that of Germany, France, and Spain
combined.

cue-1487
01:38:50.578 --> 01:38:54.958
It is home to a large and ethnically
diverse population numbering several

cue-1488
01:38:54.958 --> 01:38:59.858
millions. The province is remote, hard to
reach, and bordered on

cue-1489
01:38:59.858 --> 01:39:04.478
three sides by towering mountain ranges
rising between twenty thousand and

cue-1490
01:39:04.478 --> 01:39:05.998
twenty-five thousand feet.

cue-1491
01:39:06.898 --> 01:39:09.538
To the east lies the great Mongolian
desert.

cue-1492
01:39:10.258 --> 01:39:13.418
To the south stand the Himalayas and the
Tibetan Plateau.

cue-1493
01:39:14.178 --> 01:39:19.038
This isolated region has been a cradle of
ancient civilizations and is connected

cue-1494
01:39:19.038 --> 01:39:22.598
with famous historical figures like
Genghis Khan and Tamerlane.

cue-1495
01:39:23.358 --> 01:39:28.258
For two thousand years, it has remained
under Chinese control despite periods of

cue-1496
01:39:28.258 --> 01:39:30.138
violent revolutions and massacres.

cue-1497
01:39:31.238 --> 01:39:35.898
Though much of the land is arid, there are
many rich and fertile oases scattered

cue-1498
01:39:35.898 --> 01:39:36.458
throughout.

cue-1499
01:39:37.478 --> 01:39:42.398
Like Egypt, Sinkiang hides in its sands
the buried treasures of past ages,

cue-1500
01:39:42.398 --> 01:39:45.068
greatly prized by archaeologists.

cue-1501
01:39:46.068 --> 01:39:50.378
It was only about fifty years ago that it
was formally organized as a separate

cue-1502
01:39:50.378 --> 01:39:54.818
province under the name Sinkiang, meaning
new territory.

cue-1503
01:39:57.118 --> 01:40:01.358
There is strong evidence that Nestorian
Christianity once flourished throughout

cue-1504
01:40:01.358 --> 01:40:05.718
this region. Fragments of ancient
liturgies and several Christian

cue-1505
01:40:05.718 --> 01:40:10.098
cemeteries, one of them containing six
hundred twelve gravestones with Syriac

cue-1506
01:40:10.098 --> 01:40:14.458
inscriptions, testify to the zeal and
reach of the early church.

cue-1507
01:40:14.918 --> 01:40:19.898
Yet Nestorianism, like Buddhism in large
part, eventually gave way to

cue-1508
01:40:19.898 --> 01:40:22.318
the vast and forceful spread of Islam.

cue-1509
01:40:23.358 --> 01:40:27.638
For many centuries after that, the name of
Christ was no longer heard in these

cue-1510
01:40:27.638 --> 01:40:28.617
distant lands.

cue-1511
01:40:29.718 --> 01:40:33.938
In more recent times, among the first to
proclaim Christ in the heart of Central

cue-1512
01:40:33.938 --> 01:40:38.918
Asia were Dr. Lansdell and Mr. George
Parker, one of the early pioneers

cue-1513
01:40:38.918 --> 01:40:42.617
of the China Inland Mission, who came in
eighteen seventy-six.

cue-1514
01:40:43.498 --> 01:40:48.438
Even at that early stage, scripture was
being distributed in six languages,

cue-1515
01:40:48.438 --> 01:40:50.558
and distant Kolja had been reached.

cue-1516
01:40:51.958 --> 01:40:56.558
However, it was not until nineteen oh five
that a central mission station was

cue-1517
01:40:56.558 --> 01:41:00.478
established in Urumqi by Mr. George Hunter
of the same mission.

cue-1518
01:41:01.458 --> 01:41:05.698
He was later joined by Mr. Mather and more
recently by Mr. Ridley.

cue-1519
01:41:06.388 --> 01:41:11.078
Their work has been centered in Tihua, the
Mongolian name for Urumqi, the

cue-1520
01:41:11.078 --> 01:41:12.238
capital of the province.

cue-1521
01:41:13.258 --> 01:41:14.978
Other efforts have been made in the West.

cue-1522
01:41:15.798 --> 01:41:20.238
Swedish missionaries have labored some six
hundred, seven hundred miles further west

cue-1523
01:41:20.238 --> 01:41:25.188
in Yarkand and Kashgar. The Roman
Catholic Church also has a presence in the

cue-1524
01:41:25.188 --> 01:41:25.558
region.

cue-1525
01:41:26.538 --> 01:41:31.058
The population of Sinkiang is incredibly
diverse, making the knowledge of several

cue-1526
01:41:31.058 --> 01:41:33.778
languages a real necessity for the
missionary.

cue-1527
01:41:34.468 --> 01:41:35.778
Among the many peoples are

cue-1528
01:41:36.618 --> 01:41:37.958
Chinese from every province,

cue-1529
01:41:38.778 --> 01:41:41.098
Tungans, Chinese-speaking Muslims,

cue-1530
01:41:41.798 --> 01:41:43.278
deeply loyal to their faith,

cue-1531
01:41:44.258 --> 01:41:49.058
Turkish, called turbanned heads by the
Chinese, who speak their own

cue-1532
01:41:49.058 --> 01:41:49.858
Turkic tongue,

cue-1533
01:41:50.958 --> 01:41:52.958
Mongols, staunch Buddhists,

cue-1534
01:41:53.918 --> 01:41:56.698
Kalmuks, once an independent nation in
Dzungaria,

cue-1535
01:41:57.558 --> 01:41:59.378
Kazakhs, Muslim nomads,

cue-1536
01:42:00.578 --> 01:42:03.038
Kyrgyz, a distinct Central Asian people,

cue-1537
01:42:04.078 --> 01:42:08.958
Nogai, likely descended from Tatar fathers
and European mothers taken captive during

cue-1538
01:42:08.958 --> 01:42:10.058
the Tatar invasions.

cue-1539
01:42:11.378 --> 01:42:15.778
Manchus, descendants of imperial soldiers
settled there under Emperor

cue-1540
01:42:15.778 --> 01:42:16.478
Qianlong.

cue-1541
01:42:17.618 --> 01:42:20.978
Russians, many of them refugees fleeing
the Soviet regime.

cue-1542
01:42:21.938 --> 01:42:26.758
Such a complex and multilingual audience
gives the missionary full scope to use

cue-1543
01:42:26.758 --> 01:42:30.298
every linguistic and cultural gift the
Lord has given.

cue-1544
01:42:30.978 --> 01:42:34.878
But to tell the full story of Sinkiang is
beyond our present space.

cue-1545
01:42:35.958 --> 01:42:40.198
For those who want to know more, we again
recommend the book Through Jade Gate

cue-1546
01:42:40.198 --> 01:42:40.848
mentioned earlier.

cue-1547
01:42:41.678 --> 01:42:46.658
For this vast and unevangelized region, an
advance was planned as part of the

cue-1548
01:42:46.658 --> 01:42:49.048
China Inland Mission's forward movement.

cue-1549
01:42:49.988 --> 01:42:53.978
The men whose journey has been described
in this letter were the first party sent

cue-1550
01:42:53.978 --> 01:42:58.598
out under that plan, while some ladies
were appointed to labor in Kansu with a

cue-1551
01:42:58.598 --> 01:43:00.158
view to entering Sinkiang later.

cue-1552
01:43:01.278 --> 01:43:05.758
It should not be forgotten that the three
women, Evangeline French, Francesca

cue-1553
01:43:05.758 --> 01:43:07.178
French, and Mildred Cable,

cue-1554
01:43:07.778 --> 01:43:11.778
were the only women ever to undertake
evangelistic work in Eastern Turkestan.

cue-1555
01:43:12.478 --> 01:43:17.418
Chinese Turkestan, or Sinkiang as it is
now officially known, stands

cue-1556
01:43:17.418 --> 01:43:21.198
as a distant frontier of China, a land
with a stormy

cue-1557
01:43:21.198 --> 01:43:25.858
history. Its deep ethnic and religious
divisions have often erupted in

cue-1558
01:43:25.858 --> 01:43:30.818
violent conflict, especially between the
Chinese and Muslim populations, leaving a

cue-1559
01:43:30.818 --> 01:43:35.514
legacy of bloodshed.More recently, these
tensions have been

cue-1560
01:43:35.514 --> 01:43:39.414
worsened by new pressures, the spread of
communist propaganda,

cue-1561
01:43:40.594 --> 01:43:44.974
the arrival of tens of thousands of
Russian refugees escaping the harsh

cue-1562
01:43:44.974 --> 01:43:47.604
treatment of Soviet agricultural policies,

cue-1563
01:43:48.544 --> 01:43:53.434
the rise of armed banditry, with roving
gangs plundering the countryside and even

cue-1564
01:43:53.434 --> 01:43:54.814
threatening government forces.

cue-1565
01:43:55.874 --> 01:43:59.893
Since the founding of the Republic,
Sinkiang's governors have ruled as

cue-1566
01:43:59.894 --> 01:44:04.214
autocrats, adopting an isolationist stance
toward the outside world.

cue-1567
01:44:04.984 --> 01:44:06.454
Censorship has been tight.

cue-1568
01:44:07.194 --> 01:44:11.474
Chinese newspapers have often been banned,
and at various times it has been

cue-1569
01:44:11.474 --> 01:44:14.243
difficult to either enter or leave the
province at all.

cue-1570
01:44:15.354 --> 01:44:19.454
The recent Muslim uprisings seem to have
been caused by the harsh and unjust

cue-1571
01:44:19.454 --> 01:44:24.374
actions of the former governor. He had
taken land from the people and ignored

cue-1572
01:44:24.374 --> 01:44:25.914
long-standing traditions.

cue-1573
01:44:26.834 --> 01:44:31.634
Hami, one of the three holy cities in
Chinese Turkestan, is divided

cue-1574
01:44:31.634 --> 01:44:34.814
into two forts, one Chinese and one
Muslim.

cue-1575
01:44:35.534 --> 01:44:39.634
The Turkic people had been ruled by a line
of Khans going back to the time of

cue-1576
01:44:39.634 --> 01:44:40.434
Genghis Khan.

cue-1577
01:44:41.254 --> 01:44:43.774
The city's mosque was built in AD fourteen
twenty.

cue-1578
01:44:44.594 --> 01:44:49.194
A year or two ago, when the ruling Khan
died, the governor not only refused to

cue-1579
01:44:49.194 --> 01:44:54.194
recognize his son, the crown prince, but
imprisoned him and appointed a Chinese

cue-1580
01:44:54.194 --> 01:44:55.654
official to rule instead.

cue-1581
01:44:56.344 --> 01:45:01.314
The governor also betrayed and killed the
Mongol leader, a living Buddha, and his

cue-1582
01:45:01.314 --> 01:45:02.294
two top aides.

cue-1583
01:45:03.314 --> 01:45:07.894
This injustice angered both the Turkic and
Mongol peoples, and it was enough to

cue-1584
01:45:07.894 --> 01:45:09.094
start a rebellion.

cue-1585
01:45:10.054 --> 01:45:14.754
The rebels were supported by a young
Muslim bandit leader, Ma Chong-in, who led

cue-1586
01:45:14.754 --> 01:45:16.834
a well-armed group of fellow believers.

cue-1587
01:45:18.154 --> 01:45:22.204
This was the tense situation when Emil
Fischbacher and his companions passed

cue-1588
01:45:22.204 --> 01:45:24.704
through Hami and entered the provincial
capital.

cue-1589
01:45:25.434 --> 01:45:28.604
At that time, Hami was full of military
activity.

cue-1590
01:45:29.454 --> 01:45:33.614
Ma Chong-in's forces from Kansu were
important reinforcements for the rebels.

cue-1591
01:45:34.264 --> 01:45:36.854
The goal of the rebellion was to overthrow
the governor.

cue-1592
01:45:37.594 --> 01:45:42.373
In response, the governor, desperate for
reliable soldiers to strengthen his weak

cue-1593
01:45:42.373 --> 01:45:46.634
Chinese troops, forced all the Russians he
could find to join his army.

cue-1594
01:45:47.454 --> 01:45:51.954
He managed to gather about two thousand
men. To keep it short, the Russians broke

cue-1595
01:45:51.954 --> 01:45:56.834
the five-month siege of Hami, and Ma
Chong-in and his group retreated to Kansu.

cue-1596
01:45:57.694 --> 01:46:02.294
That was the state of things when the
travelers passed through Hami and, to the

cue-1597
01:46:02.294 --> 01:46:07.274
great surprise of the people, entered the
capital in November nineteen thirty-two.

cue-1598
01:46:08.274 --> 01:46:12.534
On Sunday, January the twenty-ninth,
during the morning service, the

cue-1599
01:46:12.534 --> 01:46:17.474
congregation in Urumchi, the capital, was
suddenly alarmed by a surprise

cue-1600
01:46:17.474 --> 01:46:19.094
attack from Muslim forces.

cue-1601
01:46:19.854 --> 01:46:24.374
It's important to note that the local
Muslims lived in the suburbs outside the

cue-1602
01:46:24.374 --> 01:46:25.054
city walls.

cue-1603
01:46:25.914 --> 01:46:29.114
For several weeks, the city was tightly
sealed off.

cue-1604
01:46:30.394 --> 01:46:35.354
Then on January seventeenth, the first
group of Russian troops arrived, followed

cue-1605
01:46:35.354 --> 01:46:39.934
by others from Kulja and other places,
eventually totaling around two thousand.

cue-1606
01:46:41.094 --> 01:46:46.034
On Tuesday, February the twenty-first,
those staying at the mission house woke to

cue-1607
01:46:46.034 --> 01:46:47.514
the sound of gunfire.

cue-1608
01:46:48.354 --> 01:46:51.454
Heavy fighting had broken out between the
rebels and the Russians.

cue-1609
01:46:52.174 --> 01:46:56.934
After some time, the rebels pulled back,
leaving the local Muslims in the suburbs

cue-1610
01:46:56.934 --> 01:47:01.594
to face the terrible consequences. In
brutal fashion, the suburbs were

cue-1611
01:47:01.594 --> 01:47:06.584
destroyed, and by the governor's orders,
every man, woman and child was

cue-1612
01:47:06.584 --> 01:47:07.254
massacred.

cue-1613
01:47:08.594 --> 01:47:13.144
Days of looting followed. By mid-March,
more Russian troops had

cue-1614
01:47:13.144 --> 01:47:13.634
arrived.

cue-1615
01:47:14.294 --> 01:47:17.414
Most of the soldiers in the province were
now gathered around the city.

cue-1616
01:47:18.154 --> 01:47:22.894
These troops brought around three thousand
camels, not carrying food, but

cue-1617
01:47:22.894 --> 01:47:23.934
stolen goods.

cue-1618
01:47:24.934 --> 01:47:29.834
Alongside them came thousands of Chinese
soldiers who had fled from Japanese forces

cue-1619
01:47:29.834 --> 01:47:32.214
in Manchuria by way of Siberia.

cue-1620
01:47:33.314 --> 01:47:37.574
These were well-trained troops, much
stronger than the local Chinese forces.

cue-1621
01:47:38.314 --> 01:47:41.974
But the governor had angered the Russian
conscripts by the way he treated them.

cue-1622
01:47:42.834 --> 01:47:47.114
Meanwhile, the Muslims had offered to stop
fighting if the Russians would hand over

cue-1623
01:47:47.114 --> 01:47:47.654
the governor.

cue-1624
01:47:48.434 --> 01:47:52.573
On April twelfth, the Russians attacked
the government offices, captured the

cue-1625
01:47:52.573 --> 01:47:54.554
governor, and seized the arsenal.

cue-1626
01:47:55.294 --> 01:47:59.534
However, the governor managed to escape
and fled across the border into Russian

cue-1627
01:47:59.534 --> 01:48:00.104
territory.

cue-1628
01:48:00.854 --> 01:48:04.064
A new government was then chosen by a
reconstruction committee.

cue-1629
01:48:04.754 --> 01:48:09.354
With Russian and other outside influences,
censorship was lifted and a more

cue-1630
01:48:09.354 --> 01:48:11.894
open, progressive government was formed.

cue-1631
01:48:13.274 --> 01:48:15.934
Still, many serious problems remained,

cue-1632
01:48:16.774 --> 01:48:18.754
making peace with the Muslim population,

cue-1633
01:48:19.354 --> 01:48:23.174
stabilizing the currency, and reopening
trade and travel routes.

cue-1634
01:48:24.414 --> 01:48:27.294
Sadly, the unrest was not limited to the
capital.

cue-1635
01:48:28.174 --> 01:48:33.054
As reported in the public press, cities
like Yarkand, Kashgar, and

cue-1636
01:48:33.054 --> 01:48:36.134
others were also caught up in dangerous
uprisings.

cue-1637
01:48:36.934 --> 01:48:41.564
This short and incomplete summary should
serve as a background for the letters that

cue-1638
01:48:41.564 --> 01:48:42.054
follow.

cue-1639
01:48:43.194 --> 01:48:47.754
Sadly, there isn't much written by Dr.
Fischbacher during these difficult months,

cue-1640
01:48:47.754 --> 01:48:50.934
apart from the travel account printed in
the last chapter.

cue-1641
01:48:51.834 --> 01:48:56.014
As the only trained medical worker
available, besides a Chinese doctor

cue-1642
01:48:56.014 --> 01:48:58.554
trained by Dr. Cox and an older Russian
doctor,

cue-1643
01:48:59.234 --> 01:49:04.094
he was constantly overwhelmed, working day
and night to treat the many wounded and

cue-1644
01:49:04.094 --> 01:49:05.214
neglected soldiers.

cue-1645
01:49:06.134 --> 01:49:10.734
Most of his letters were written before
censorship was lifted. Only two letters

cue-1646
01:49:10.734 --> 01:49:14.694
written after that point are known to
exist, and both were written three weeks

cue-1647
01:49:14.694 --> 01:49:19.274
before his death when he was utterly worn
out from the nonstop demand for his

cue-1648
01:49:19.274 --> 01:49:20.074
surgical help.

cue-1649
01:49:21.094 --> 01:49:24.234
These were the circumstances in which the
following letters were written.

cue-1650
01:49:27.734 --> 01:49:28.454
Chapter seven:

cue-1651
01:49:29.254 --> 01:49:30.214
Last letters.

cue-1652
01:49:33.034 --> 01:49:37.324
Urumchi, the capital of Sinkiang, was
reached on November the ninth,

cue-1653
01:49:38.134 --> 01:49:43.086
eight weeks and one day after leaving
Kalgan by motor.Of that time, only

cue-1654
01:49:43.086 --> 01:49:45.026
three weeks and a day were spent
traveling.

cue-1655
01:49:45.746 --> 01:49:49.546
The rest, five weeks, was taken up by
delays at various stops.

cue-1656
01:49:50.566 --> 01:49:53.666
It was, of course, a great moment when
they finally arrived.

cue-1657
01:49:54.506 --> 01:49:59.066
Emil Fischbacher's first letters home
after reaching the city show his joy at

cue-1658
01:49:59.066 --> 01:50:01.466
finding a large bundle of mail waiting for
him.

cue-1659
01:50:02.216 --> 01:50:06.666
There were around fifty to sixty letters
in all, nearly all from his own family,

cue-1660
01:50:06.666 --> 01:50:08.816
making it a real feast of encouragement.

cue-1661
01:50:09.926 --> 01:50:14.606
In the East, news spreads quickly, and
though he had hoped to remain unnoticed,

cue-1662
01:50:14.606 --> 01:50:19.366
word soon got out that a foreign doctor
was among the new arrivals.

cue-1663
01:50:20.326 --> 01:50:24.316
His family had been a bit worried that he
might not take the medical work seriously,

cue-1664
01:50:24.316 --> 01:50:26.836
but within two weeks of arriving, he
wrote,

cue-1665
01:50:27.926 --> 01:50:31.336
You don't need to worry about the doctor
business. Everybody knows now,

cue-1666
01:50:31.336 --> 01:50:34.906
-unfortunately.
-It was an honest statement, as it's never

cue-1667
01:50:34.906 --> 01:50:38.666
easy when a medical missionary is
surrounded by patients before having time

cue-1668
01:50:38.666 --> 01:50:39.526
to learn the language.

cue-1669
01:50:40.426 --> 01:50:44.286
He found it hard not only to study, but
even to write letters.

cue-1670
01:50:45.346 --> 01:50:47.396
Less than a month after arriving, he
wrote,

cue-1671
01:50:48.166 --> 01:50:52.886
Most of my interruptions are the result of
medical work. I'm doing as little as I

cue-1672
01:50:52.886 --> 01:50:57.426
possibly can, but it's almost impossible
to do nothing.

cue-1673
01:50:57.426 --> 01:51:00.286
Later in that same letter, he shared
another challenge.

cue-1674
01:51:01.206 --> 01:51:06.066
Everything that's a solution had to be
unpacked and moved into my room. Our

cue-1675
01:51:06.066 --> 01:51:10.446
average temperature this past week has
been between twenty and twenty-five

cue-1676
01:51:10.446 --> 01:51:15.086
degrees below freezing, and it's expected
to drop twenty to thirty degrees lower.

cue-1677
01:51:15.086 --> 01:51:20.026
Anything with water in it will freeze
solid. And worst of all,

cue-1678
01:51:20.026 --> 01:51:23.026
many of my surgical instruments are
horribly rusty.

cue-1679
01:51:23.786 --> 01:51:25.866
Shanghai is terrible for rust.

cue-1680
01:51:26.606 --> 01:51:31.566
Even the plating on some is eaten through.
It took me two full days just to get

cue-1681
01:51:31.566 --> 01:51:34.236
them all cleaned, greased, and put away
properly.

cue-1682
01:51:35.646 --> 01:51:39.346
It's clear someone had asked why they
hadn't traveled by plane instead of by car

cue-1683
01:51:39.346 --> 01:51:40.166
across the desert.

cue-1684
01:51:41.006 --> 01:51:45.206
In a letter dated December the 17th, 1932,
he replied,

cue-1685
01:51:46.066 --> 01:51:50.946
An airplane was here a few days ago, and
the cost of flying to Shanghai was said to

cue-1686
01:51:50.946 --> 01:51:53.506
be $1,400 per person,

cue-1687
01:51:54.146 --> 01:51:58.766
with only thirty pounds of luggage
allowed. My medical supplies alone weigh

cue-1688
01:51:58.766 --> 01:52:03.465
about two hundred pounds. Shipping goods
here by camel takes no less than two

cue-1689
01:52:03.466 --> 01:52:08.406
years, and some shipments have taken over
three years to arrive. It's also

cue-1690
01:52:08.406 --> 01:52:10.556
very costly to transport goods that way.

cue-1691
01:52:11.206 --> 01:52:15.426
We might have considered coming through
the desert by camel caravan, but that

cue-1692
01:52:15.426 --> 01:52:19.766
would have required at least forty camels
and taken no less than four

cue-1693
01:52:19.766 --> 01:52:24.606
months. As it turned out, if certain
things hadn't delayed us,

cue-1694
01:52:24.606 --> 01:52:26.886
we could have arrived in less than a
month.

cue-1695
01:52:27.566 --> 01:52:30.186
In the end, we traveled for twenty-two
days.

cue-1696
01:52:30.926 --> 01:52:34.356
I expect the total cost will be about half
the price of flying.

cue-1697
01:52:35.526 --> 01:52:40.226
While I'm speaking of airplanes, you'll be
glad to know that it's expected we may

cue-1698
01:52:40.226 --> 01:52:45.106
soon have a regular service between here
and the coast. That will allow any

cue-1699
01:52:45.106 --> 01:52:48.676
urgent letters to reach Shanghai in about
four or five days.

cue-1700
01:52:49.926 --> 01:52:54.786
On Tuesday, I hope to perform a small
operation, though unfortunately

cue-1701
01:52:54.786 --> 01:52:56.686
under far from ideal conditions.

cue-1702
01:52:57.326 --> 01:53:02.306
There is, of course, no hospital here.
Some of the cases are in a pitiful

cue-1703
01:53:02.306 --> 01:53:02.746
state.

cue-1704
01:53:03.406 --> 01:53:08.266
A man came in two days ago completely
blind. His left eye is entirely

cue-1705
01:53:08.266 --> 01:53:13.266
gone. A local barber had kindly scraped it
for him to improve an ulcer.

cue-1706
01:53:13.266 --> 01:53:14.326
I needn't say more.

cue-1707
01:53:15.806 --> 01:53:20.155
His next letter was written on Christmas
Day, the first he had ever spent away from

cue-1708
01:53:20.155 --> 01:53:20.606
home.

cue-1709
01:53:21.586 --> 01:53:25.606
Few families have felt the meaning of
Christmas Day more deeply, and he felt the

cue-1710
01:53:25.606 --> 01:53:30.366
difference keenly. But a joyful heart
made up for many of the missing signs of

cue-1711
01:53:30.366 --> 01:53:34.026
celebration, and in Mr. Mather he found a
kindred spirit.

cue-1712
01:53:34.886 --> 01:53:39.366
Mr. Mather, he writes, comes from
Lancashire and is great company.

cue-1713
01:53:39.366 --> 01:53:44.326
He's about forty-six, but as young at
heart as any of us. In fact,

cue-1714
01:53:44.326 --> 01:53:49.326
he seems younger than I am. It's amazing,
after twenty years in Sinkiang

cue-1715
01:53:49.326 --> 01:53:53.966
since we came, the years seem to have
fallen off him, and I know he enjoys

cue-1716
01:53:53.966 --> 01:53:54.666
having us here.

cue-1717
01:53:55.786 --> 01:53:59.826
As a newcomer, it was natural that he
should write about local conditions.

cue-1718
01:54:00.546 --> 01:54:02.486
Some excerpts help us picture them.

cue-1719
01:54:03.346 --> 01:54:07.286
There are quite a few foreigners here in
the city who speak English, he says.

cue-1720
01:54:08.046 --> 01:54:13.046
Mr. Kierkegaard is Danish, and his wife
Norwegian. He's the postal

cue-1721
01:54:13.046 --> 01:54:16.346
commissioner for Sinkiang and speaks
English as well as I do.

cue-1722
01:54:16.986 --> 01:54:20.186
Most of the other foreigners are German or
Russian.

cue-1723
01:54:20.186 --> 01:54:23.606
On the last day of the year, the first
anniversary of his leaving home,

cue-1724
01:54:24.246 --> 01:54:26.546
he wrote more freely to his youngest
sister.

cue-1725
01:54:27.636 --> 01:54:31.346
The letter is especially valuable because
it was the last time he had the leisure to

cue-1726
01:54:31.346 --> 01:54:33.146
write personally about himself.

cue-1727
01:54:34.146 --> 01:54:39.126
The date, December 31st, 1932, he writes,
you will

cue-1728
01:54:39.126 --> 01:54:43.946
no doubt recognize. It's exactly a year
since I said goodbye to you at Victoria

cue-1729
01:54:43.946 --> 01:54:48.916
Station. What a lot I have to praise God
for today. I feel almost

cue-1730
01:54:48.916 --> 01:54:53.266
overwhelmed when I think of all the Lord
has done for me this year. I was saying to

cue-1731
01:54:53.266 --> 01:54:57.556
myself the other day how little I've
given up for the Lord, and then it came to

cue-1732
01:54:57.556 --> 01:54:59.446
me how wonderful his grace is.

cue-1733
01:55:00.126 --> 01:55:04.766
If I had known all this eighteen months
ago, I would have thought the cost too

cue-1734
01:55:04.766 --> 01:55:09.206
high, the sacrifices too many. But now I
often stop and ask

cue-1735
01:55:09.206 --> 01:55:14.106
myself, what have I really given up for
the Lord? Truly, it is

cue-1736
01:55:14.106 --> 01:55:18.926
always like this. I am completely content
and truly happy. I've learned a

cue-1737
01:55:18.926 --> 01:55:22.886
little of what it means to look at
difficulties through the Lord, and not at

cue-1738
01:55:22.886 --> 01:55:27.566
the Lord through difficulties. There is
absolutely no limit to what the Lord will

cue-1739
01:55:27.566 --> 01:55:31.526
do for and through a life fully
surrendered to him.

cue-1740
01:55:32.586 --> 01:55:37.566
I truly believe that's the secret, and
it's easy enough to say, but another

cue-1741
01:55:37.566 --> 01:55:42.366
thing to live it. It's only through the
Holy Spirit's help that real surrender is

cue-1742
01:55:42.366 --> 01:55:42.906
possible,

cue-1743
01:55:43.666 --> 01:55:47.846
and surrender must be distinguished from
simple resignation to God's

cue-1744
01:55:47.846 --> 01:55:52.722
will.It's not a passive thing. It's deeply
active,

cue-1745
01:55:52.722 --> 01:55:56.982
based on a strong faith that God will
accept the offering and use it for His

cue-1746
01:55:56.982 --> 01:56:01.222
glory alone. That is one of the greatest
lessons I'm learning these days.

cue-1747
01:56:02.902 --> 01:56:07.842
This long letter, written only for his
sister, shows the heart of a man

cue-1748
01:56:07.842 --> 01:56:09.782
eager to go all the way with God.

cue-1749
01:56:10.482 --> 01:56:14.882
It reveals a holy dissatisfaction with
anything in his own life or in others

cue-1750
01:56:15.502 --> 01:56:17.362
that fell short of the highest.

cue-1751
01:56:18.362 --> 01:56:22.722
He admitted that in argument he often
failed, but this did not lessen his desire

cue-1752
01:56:22.722 --> 01:56:23.922
for spiritual depth.

cue-1753
01:56:24.842 --> 01:56:29.802
I'm no theologian, he writes, and I always
lose every argument and get beaten

cue-1754
01:56:29.802 --> 01:56:30.922
in every discussion.

cue-1755
01:56:31.582 --> 01:56:36.342
Yet, like the deer that longs for the
water brooks, his soul longed for

cue-1756
01:56:36.342 --> 01:56:36.742
God.

cue-1757
01:56:37.482 --> 01:56:41.662
In this spirit, he ended the last day of
the last full year of his life.

cue-1758
01:56:42.442 --> 01:56:45.582
On January sixth, he picked up his pen
again and wrote,

cue-1759
01:56:46.462 --> 01:56:51.322
Well, here goes for my first letter in
nineteen thirty-three. I wonder how

cue-1760
01:56:51.322 --> 01:56:54.982
many letters this year will begin with
this address. There's no telling.

cue-1761
01:56:55.762 --> 01:57:00.742
A week later, after noting how hard he
found it after his busy life as a doctor

cue-1762
01:57:00.742 --> 01:57:05.642
at home to settle down to steady study, he
described local conditions

cue-1763
01:57:05.642 --> 01:57:10.182
-and what had been accomplished.
-With all these different nationalities, we

cue-1764
01:57:10.182 --> 01:57:13.742
mix freely, and I've already met people
of every kind.

cue-1765
01:57:14.402 --> 01:57:17.292
Although, as you know, I can't speak
German,

cue-1766
01:57:17.902 --> 01:57:22.542
I can understand almost everything that's
said, and that's been a great help.

cue-1767
01:57:22.542 --> 01:57:27.542
Otto Schörner, of course, speaks German,
so we often have the pleasure of

cue-1768
01:57:27.542 --> 01:57:32.522
entertaining quite a few people.
Cossacks, Turkish, Mongols, and

cue-1769
01:57:32.522 --> 01:57:37.322
Chinese all attend the services regularly,
though for now only Chinese

cue-1770
01:57:37.322 --> 01:57:41.182
services are held. There are also Manchus
in this province.

cue-1771
01:57:41.942 --> 01:57:46.482
Mr. Hunter and Mr. Mather have done a
great deal of translation work,

cue-1772
01:57:46.482 --> 01:57:51.412
dictionaries, Pilgrim's Progress, and
parts of Scripture into nearly

cue-1773
01:57:51.412 --> 01:57:52.742
all the local languages.

cue-1774
01:57:53.522 --> 01:57:56.042
No work has yet been done among the
Manchus,

cue-1775
01:57:56.682 --> 01:58:01.282
but it is hoped someone will take that on.
As you can imagine, it

cue-1776
01:58:01.282 --> 01:58:05.882
requires a special language, and it takes
years of study and practice to gain real

cue-1777
01:58:05.882 --> 01:58:10.522
skill in it. It is almost impossible for
anyone to work in this province

cue-1778
01:58:10.522 --> 01:58:12.702
without knowing at least two languages.

cue-1779
01:58:13.522 --> 01:58:18.042
Mr. Mather speaks Chinese fluently, as
well as Kalmuck Mongol.

cue-1780
01:58:19.042 --> 01:58:23.742
He can preach in both and has a special
interest in work among the Mongols. He

cue-1781
01:58:23.742 --> 01:58:28.542
also speaks some Turkey, though he never
formally studied it. He

cue-1782
01:58:28.542 --> 01:58:33.102
simply learned through daily contact with
the people. He also knows a bit of

cue-1783
01:58:33.102 --> 01:58:33.452
Russian.

cue-1784
01:58:34.102 --> 01:58:39.052
Mr. Hunter and Mr. Mather produced a
Manchu dictionary some years ago

cue-1785
01:58:39.052 --> 01:58:41.732
and translated Pilgrim's Progress into
Turkey.

cue-1786
01:58:42.602 --> 01:58:47.602
So, as you can see, much has already been
done, though there is still plenty of

cue-1787
01:58:47.602 --> 01:58:49.742
scope for more workers of the same kind.

cue-1788
01:58:51.242 --> 01:58:55.741
The church is full every Sunday. It's
wonderful to see, but that isn't

cue-1789
01:58:55.742 --> 01:59:00.462
everything. What we long for is a greater
increase in the number of those who

cue-1790
01:59:00.502 --> 01:59:04.922
boldly take their stand for Jesus Christ.
That is not an easy thing here,

cue-1791
01:59:05.542 --> 01:59:07.202
especially among the Muslims.

cue-1792
01:59:07.862 --> 01:59:12.282
As much as Emil Fischbacher longed to
study the languages himself, his medical

cue-1793
01:59:12.282 --> 01:59:13.922
work made it nearly impossible.

cue-1794
01:59:14.622 --> 01:59:19.022
-He often mentioned this in his letters.
-Will you forgive a letter with no news? He

cue-1795
01:59:19.022 --> 01:59:19.382
writes.

cue-1796
01:59:19.982 --> 01:59:20.502
I'm very,

cue-1797
01:59:21.202 --> 01:59:21.942
very busy,

cue-1798
01:59:22.722 --> 01:59:24.042
but study is impossible.

cue-1799
01:59:24.962 --> 01:59:29.762
Yesterday, I had a rather serious
operation. I removed a bullet from a man's

cue-1800
01:59:29.762 --> 01:59:30.822
chest.

cue-1801
01:59:31.062 --> 01:59:33.702
It had passed through the right lung just
above the heart.

cue-1802
01:59:34.722 --> 01:59:38.282
I suspected it had broken a rib behind and
found that it had.

cue-1803
01:59:39.222 --> 01:59:43.922
It was embedded in a mass of splinters.
The patient is doing well. These

cue-1804
01:59:43.922 --> 01:59:48.382
operations aren't easy without an X-ray,
but one learns to do without such

cue-1805
01:59:48.382 --> 01:59:52.302
-luxuries.
-On February nineteenth, just three days

cue-1806
01:59:52.302 --> 01:59:56.302
before rebels attacked the city, a siege
that would plunge him into intense

cue-1807
01:59:56.302 --> 01:59:57.962
surgical work until the end,

cue-1808
01:59:58.642 --> 02:00:00.702
he lamented the lack of a hospital.

cue-1809
02:00:01.182 --> 02:00:05.102
In an earlier letter, he had asked his
family to imagine a town of seventy

cue-1810
02:00:05.102 --> 02:00:07.762
thousand people with no drainage system.

cue-1811
02:00:08.682 --> 02:00:13.361
He grieved over the yearly loss of life
from typhoid, typhus, dysentery,

cue-1812
02:00:13.362 --> 02:00:15.522
diphtheria, and scarlet fever,

cue-1813
02:00:16.262 --> 02:00:20.522
little realizing that within months he
himself would be numbered among the dead.

cue-1814
02:00:21.662 --> 02:00:26.042
Nor did he know when he wrote the
following lines that within three days

cue-1815
02:00:26.042 --> 02:00:29.962
hundreds of wounded soldiers would be in
desperate need of hospital care.

cue-1816
02:00:30.802 --> 02:00:35.562
Can you imagine, he writes, a city of
seventy thousand people without a

cue-1817
02:00:35.562 --> 02:00:36.112
hospital?

cue-1818
02:00:36.902 --> 02:00:41.562
Try to picture such a place, and then
you'll understand why I'm not left in

cue-1819
02:00:41.562 --> 02:00:46.502
peace to study. The nearest hospital is
forty-five days' journey away.

cue-1820
02:00:46.502 --> 02:00:51.492
If I went there, it would take over fifty
days, since I wouldn't travel on Sundays.

cue-1821
02:00:51.492 --> 02:00:56.202
That hospital is in Kashgar, in the
southwest of the province. My

cue-1822
02:00:56.202 --> 02:01:01.142
nearest CIM neighbors are at the hospital
in Lanzhou, over sixty days' journey

cue-1823
02:01:01.142 --> 02:01:01.502
away.

cue-1824
02:01:02.202 --> 02:01:06.142
Half a million square miles makes quite a
large medical district, don't you

cue-1825
02:01:06.142 --> 02:01:09.662
-think?
-On February twentieth, less than

cue-1826
02:01:09.662 --> 02:01:13.482
twenty-four hours before the surprise
attack, he wrote again.

cue-1827
02:01:13.482 --> 02:01:18.462
Another interruption. This is quite the
place. Mr. Mather just came to show

cue-1828
02:01:18.462 --> 02:01:23.402
me his tent. It has finally arrived, and
it's a fine one. But listen to

cue-1829
02:01:23.402 --> 02:01:28.382
its story. Last April, perhaps earlier, I
told you about some goods

cue-1830
02:01:28.382 --> 02:01:32.962
that had left Shanghai over two years ago
and still hadn't arrived.

cue-1831
02:01:32.962 --> 02:01:37.722
Well, they've finally come. Eight boxes in
all. Most of them

cue-1832
02:01:37.722 --> 02:01:42.362
contain tracts and gospels in various
languages and had long been given up as

cue-1833
02:01:42.362 --> 02:01:42.782
lost.

cue-1834
02:01:43.512 --> 02:01:47.782
They've been three and a half years on the
way. They came by camel through

cue-1835
02:01:47.782 --> 02:01:52.722
Mongolia but were seized and taken to
Urga.Later

cue-1836
02:01:52.722 --> 02:01:53.822
they were sent on again,

cue-1837
02:01:54.442 --> 02:01:57.142
but delayed many times by local troubles.

cue-1838
02:01:57.922 --> 02:01:58.402
Finally,

cue-1839
02:01:59.002 --> 02:02:02.162
the caravan of many camels reached Taiwa
yesterday.

cue-1840
02:02:02.842 --> 02:02:07.021
So Mr. Mather is rejoicing. That's how
things work here.

cue-1841
02:02:07.022 --> 02:02:10.642
From the letters that followed, little can
be learned about what was really

cue-1842
02:02:10.642 --> 02:02:15.482
happening. Because of censorship, he could
not mention that the city was under siege

cue-1843
02:02:15.482 --> 02:02:16.662
by Muslim rebels.

cue-1844
02:02:17.662 --> 02:02:22.202
In a letter written on February 25th, four
days after the attack began,

cue-1845
02:02:22.202 --> 02:02:27.062
there is not a single word about it. The
same is true of the letter written a week

cue-1846
02:02:27.062 --> 02:02:32.002
later. Its main topic was his photographs
of the Gobi Desert. He dared

cue-1847
02:02:32.002 --> 02:02:36.262
not send the films by post for fear of
losing them, yet at that very time he was

cue-1848
02:02:36.262 --> 02:02:38.082
tirelessly working among the wounded.

cue-1849
02:02:39.162 --> 02:02:41.962
A month later, on March 25th, he wrote,

cue-1850
02:02:42.802 --> 02:02:47.182
I'm sorry there's been almost a month's
gap in my letters, but I can assure you

cue-1851
02:02:47.182 --> 02:02:50.042
it's not from laziness. I've been very
busy,

cue-1852
02:02:50.682 --> 02:02:52.672
morning, noon and night.

cue-1853
02:02:53.362 --> 02:02:58.022
I'm operating as much as I possibly can
every day. The other fellows are doing the

cue-1854
02:02:58.022 --> 02:03:03.022
dressings and working like Trojans.
They've been splendid. All the cases

cue-1855
02:03:03.022 --> 02:03:07.622
are the result of battle injuries,
amputations, all kinds of repairs.

cue-1856
02:03:07.622 --> 02:03:10.522
I've treated empyemas and set fractures.

cue-1857
02:03:11.262 --> 02:03:12.942
I've had six broken femurs,

cue-1858
02:03:13.542 --> 02:03:14.922
three broken forearms,

cue-1859
02:03:15.642 --> 02:03:20.642
three broken upper arms, and several cases
of pierced bladders, chests

cue-1860
02:03:20.642 --> 02:03:21.442
and abdomens,

cue-1861
02:03:22.082 --> 02:03:25.742
-all caused by bullets.
-There was not a single word about what the

cue-1862
02:03:25.742 --> 02:03:28.982
fighting was, though anyone reading
between the lines could guess.

cue-1863
02:03:30.202 --> 02:03:31.482
The hard work went on.

cue-1864
02:03:32.222 --> 02:03:33.662
The next letter is dated

cue-1865
02:03:34.822 --> 02:03:35.762
April the 6th.

cue-1866
02:03:36.962 --> 02:03:41.462
I've almost forgotten how to write
letters, he says. It's been over a month

cue-1867
02:03:41.462 --> 02:03:45.712
since I last wrote, except for one short
note on March 25th.

cue-1868
02:03:46.462 --> 02:03:51.241
I suddenly had a chance to send a letter
by airmail, so I wrote a quick, messy

cue-1869
02:03:51.242 --> 02:03:55.562
one. I'm very, very busy, and not with
study.

cue-1870
02:03:56.302 --> 02:04:00.472
I'm operating a great deal now, almost as
much as I possibly can.

cue-1871
02:04:01.142 --> 02:04:04.942
The other men are looking after the wards
and call me in whenever needed.

cue-1872
02:04:05.942 --> 02:04:08.302
We now have over 300 patients.

cue-1873
02:04:09.082 --> 02:04:13.402
I can understand now what the surgeons in
France went through during the war of

cue-1874
02:04:13.402 --> 02:04:15.202
1914 and after.

cue-1875
02:04:15.922 --> 02:04:18.662
How thankful I am for my earlier
experience.

cue-1876
02:04:19.422 --> 02:04:21.611
The others are working heroically too,

cue-1877
02:04:22.262 --> 02:04:27.202
doing dressings as large as any I ever did
at home. The staff have risen to the

cue-1878
02:04:27.202 --> 02:04:32.002
challenge wonderfully. We now have plenty
of opportunities to learn the spoken

cue-1879
02:04:32.002 --> 02:04:35.152
language, though study itself is at a
standstill.

cue-1880
02:04:35.772 --> 02:04:39.802
More importantly, we have wonderful
chances to share the gospel with these

cue-1881
02:04:39.802 --> 02:04:43.502
people. After all, healing their bodies is
not enough.

cue-1882
02:04:44.202 --> 02:04:46.642
What is needed is a deep change of heart.

cue-1883
02:04:47.412 --> 02:04:52.081
Then work like this would no longer be
necessary. I have seen many stirring

cue-1884
02:04:52.082 --> 02:04:56.982
times since I came to China last February,
but none like these. We are all well

cue-1885
02:04:56.982 --> 02:04:59.462
and happy, and we long for letters from
home.

cue-1886
02:05:00.602 --> 02:05:05.042
As mentioned earlier, the local government
was overthrown on April 12th when the

cue-1887
02:05:05.042 --> 02:05:08.042
Russians captured the arsenal and took the
governor prisoner.

cue-1888
02:05:08.732 --> 02:05:12.602
The censorship ended at that time, so
later letters could be written more

cue-1889
02:05:12.602 --> 02:05:17.542
freely. Five days after the governor's
fall, though extremely busy, he

cue-1890
02:05:17.542 --> 02:05:20.422
wrote to his youngest sister, giving a
detailed account.

cue-1891
02:05:21.322 --> 02:05:26.142
Of the letters we still have, this is the
second to last from his hand, and in it he

cue-1892
02:05:26.142 --> 02:05:30.262
-says
-I want to talk medicine. I wish I could

cue-1893
02:05:30.262 --> 02:05:34.792
start at the beginning, he writes, and
tell you everything that has happened, but

cue-1894
02:05:34.792 --> 02:05:36.262
that's impossible just now.

cue-1895
02:05:36.882 --> 02:05:41.782
The censorship seems to be gone for the
moment, so I long to tell you all. These

cue-1896
02:05:41.782 --> 02:05:45.542
have been stirring days, but the Lord has
wonderfully protected us.

cue-1897
02:05:46.222 --> 02:05:47.452
We were never afraid,

cue-1898
02:05:48.222 --> 02:05:52.282
even while bullets were flying around.
I've gathered quite a collection of

cue-1899
02:05:52.282 --> 02:05:57.282
bullets now, my own souvenirs from these
troubles. At first I wasn't

cue-1900
02:05:57.282 --> 02:06:02.262
eager to help in the hospitals, because my
language skills were still poor. But in

cue-1901
02:06:02.262 --> 02:06:07.182
the end, the others and Mr. Mather agreed
to assist Dr. Marr, a Chinese

cue-1902
02:06:07.182 --> 02:06:07.592
doctor.

cue-1903
02:06:08.742 --> 02:06:13.521
Later, at the request of the former
governor, I agreed to take on any urgent

cue-1904
02:06:13.521 --> 02:06:14.802
or serious cases.

cue-1905
02:06:15.512 --> 02:06:20.442
I arranged for the five men and Mr. Mather
to do the dressings and care

cue-1906
02:06:20.442 --> 02:06:24.942
for the patients I had operated on. All
the wounds were from bullets or swords.

cue-1907
02:06:25.752 --> 02:06:28.722
The wounded kept coming, and the work
increased.

cue-1908
02:06:29.602 --> 02:06:34.382
I had a fine little operating room, with
Otto as my assistant and two Chinese

cue-1909
02:06:34.382 --> 02:06:35.142
boys to help.

cue-1910
02:06:35.922 --> 02:06:39.232
Dr. Marr and sometimes Mr. Mather gave the
anesthetics.

cue-1911
02:06:39.922 --> 02:06:44.902
Later, a Roman Catholic priest, who is
quite skilled medically,

cue-1912
02:06:44.902 --> 02:06:49.722
took charge of about 30 patients, and I
performed any operations he needed me to

cue-1913
02:06:49.722 --> 02:06:53.272
-do.
-He then went on to give a detailed, and at

cue-1914
02:06:53.272 --> 02:06:56.182
times gruesome, account of the wounds he
treated.

cue-1915
02:06:56.862 --> 02:07:01.542
The letter was written to his sister, who
was a doctor, but many readers would not

cue-1916
02:07:01.542 --> 02:07:03.322
wish to read such descriptions.

cue-1917
02:07:04.102 --> 02:07:08.622
It showed how dreadful the injuries from a
sword's slash or a bullet's impact could

cue-1918
02:07:08.622 --> 02:07:08.882
be.

cue-1919
02:07:10.082 --> 02:07:15.002
When I first went to the hospital, he
writes, I found five compound fractures of

cue-1920
02:07:15.002 --> 02:07:19.912
the thigh bone, all in dreadful
condition. The filth and stench of the

cue-1921
02:07:19.912 --> 02:07:24.862
place were beyond description. Imagine
300 wounds, large and

cue-1922
02:07:24.862 --> 02:07:29.442
small, left unattended for two weeks or
more. It was a horrifying

cue-1923
02:07:29.442 --> 02:07:30.262
experience.

cue-1924
02:07:30.862 --> 02:07:35.462
He used the word terrific more than once
in the letter. It truly was both terrible

cue-1925
02:07:35.462 --> 02:07:36.722
and overwhelming.

cue-1926
02:07:37.732 --> 02:07:39.692
The letter ended with a short postscript.

cue-1927
02:07:40.622 --> 02:07:43.962
I'm now in charge of a new hospital,
opened three weeks ago.

cue-1928
02:07:44.722 --> 02:07:49.582
The other men each have charge of a ward,
and I'm working as hard as I possibly can.

cue-1929
02:07:50.322 --> 02:07:53.002
With no equipment and little or no
medicine,

cue-1930
02:07:53.642 --> 02:07:55.222
one learns to be inventive.

cue-1931
02:07:56.690 --> 02:08:01.630
The fighting had lasted for several days,
and as around ten thousand rebels attacked

cue-1932
02:08:01.630 --> 02:08:04.750
the city, it was shut off for about six
weeks.

cue-1933
02:08:05.490 --> 02:08:10.270
Thousands were reported killed, and the
battlefield outside the city was a sight

cue-1934
02:08:10.270 --> 02:08:11.610
that could never be forgotten.

cue-1935
02:08:12.709 --> 02:08:17.130
Then came the last letter he ever wrote
home, dated May sixth, nineteen

cue-1936
02:08:17.130 --> 02:08:17.690
thirty-three.

cue-1937
02:08:18.890 --> 02:08:19.470
It began,

cue-1938
02:08:20.440 --> 02:08:24.330
"These days, I'm sorry to say, I have
absolutely no ambition,

cue-1939
02:08:24.990 --> 02:08:26.980
not even the desire to write to you all.

cue-1940
02:08:27.590 --> 02:08:32.250
The fact is, I've been out of action for
three days now, and I simply can't find

cue-1941
02:08:32.250 --> 02:08:35.079
the energy to write." Though he did not
realize it,

cue-1942
02:08:35.970 --> 02:08:40.130
this was likely the beginning of the
illness that would prove fatal. He

cue-1943
02:08:40.130 --> 02:08:40.619
continued,

cue-1944
02:08:41.439 --> 02:08:45.650
"I don't have a moment to call my own.
That's the real reason I've been laid up.

cue-1945
02:08:46.290 --> 02:08:50.470
One night, I had to go outside the city
very late and didn't have time to dress

cue-1946
02:08:50.470 --> 02:08:54.990
properly. I was given a fine horse and
went with a Russian officer, two

cue-1947
02:08:54.990 --> 02:08:59.510
soldiers, and one of the leaders of the
White Russians. The horse was very

cue-1948
02:08:59.510 --> 02:09:04.050
spirited and tried several times to throw
me. He flew like the wind.

cue-1949
02:09:04.050 --> 02:09:08.870
When I reached my destination, I was
drenched with sweat. The

cue-1950
02:09:08.870 --> 02:09:13.550
evenings here are quite cold, though the
days are already very hot. On the

cue-1951
02:09:13.550 --> 02:09:18.130
return journey, we had to wait about half
an hour for the city gates to be opened.

cue-1952
02:09:18.760 --> 02:09:23.630
There are guards everywhere inside and
outside the city, and I would have been

cue-1953
02:09:23.630 --> 02:09:28.370
shot instantly if not for the soldiers who
knew the password. Getting into the

cue-1954
02:09:28.370 --> 02:09:33.010
city at night is no easy matter. During
that wait, I must have caught a

cue-1955
02:09:33.010 --> 02:09:37.930
chill. Added to that, I was working so
hard that I wasn't getting enough

cue-1956
02:09:37.930 --> 02:09:42.070
sleep. There are four hundred wounded
spread across three hospitals,

cue-1957
02:09:42.850 --> 02:09:46.690
and I was caring for one hundred and
twenty-five of the worst cases in a

cue-1958
02:09:46.690 --> 02:09:51.350
hospital I had organized myself." He wrote
that many of these men had not been

cue-1959
02:09:51.350 --> 02:09:55.790
washed for one, two, or even three months
before they came under his care.

cue-1960
02:09:56.670 --> 02:10:01.050
The condition of their wounds, clothes,
and bedding was almost beyond

cue-1961
02:10:01.050 --> 02:10:05.870
imagination. "Not one official," he added,
"has ever come to

cue-1962
02:10:05.870 --> 02:10:08.850
inspect our work or even see what we are
doing."

cue-1963
02:10:09.650 --> 02:10:14.170
Worse still, the authorities failed to
provide food for the patients or wages for

cue-1964
02:10:14.170 --> 02:10:15.130
the Chinese staff.

cue-1965
02:10:16.010 --> 02:10:20.590
As a result, the Chinese workers went on
strike, leaving the already

cue-1966
02:10:20.590 --> 02:10:23.810
overworked foreigners to handle everything
themselves.

cue-1967
02:10:24.770 --> 02:10:29.130
"It has shown me the inner side of Chinese
life in just three months," he wrote.

cue-1968
02:10:29.790 --> 02:10:33.170
"Without this experience, it would have
taken years.

cue-1969
02:10:34.250 --> 02:10:38.750
I now hold consultations in English,
Russian, German,

cue-1970
02:10:38.750 --> 02:10:43.750
Chinese, Mongol, Turkey, Manchu, and
Cossack.

cue-1971
02:10:43.750 --> 02:10:48.230
Today, even two Poles came to see me.
Thankfully, they knew some Chinese.

cue-1972
02:10:48.890 --> 02:10:53.850
I can manage medical consultations in
Chinese on my own now. I know a fair bit

cue-1973
02:10:53.850 --> 02:10:57.080
of Russian and can ask simple questions in
that language,

cue-1974
02:10:57.690 --> 02:11:02.000
and in Mongol and Cossack too. In my
hospital, I have Mongols.

cue-1975
02:11:02.830 --> 02:11:06.230
Mr. Mather looks after them as he speaks
Mongol well.

cue-1976
02:11:06.930 --> 02:11:08.930
Chantos, Turkey people,

cue-1977
02:11:09.830 --> 02:11:10.490
Tungans,

cue-1978
02:11:11.170 --> 02:11:12.430
and of course, Chinese."

cue-1979
02:11:13.270 --> 02:11:17.830
Overwhelmed, he wrote, "I simply cannot
care for the whole population of Tihwa.

cue-1980
02:11:17.830 --> 02:11:21.410
When I refuse a case, I am often cursed.

cue-1981
02:11:22.070 --> 02:11:26.610
You might ask, 'Why do it?' But if you saw
the condition of these men,

cue-1982
02:11:26.610 --> 02:11:28.750
you couldn't help but do something."

cue-1983
02:11:30.230 --> 02:11:31.570
This was his final letter.

cue-1984
02:11:32.230 --> 02:11:36.090
Even the parts that can be printed barely
suggest the full reality of what he

cue-1985
02:11:36.090 --> 02:11:36.990
experienced.

cue-1986
02:11:37.650 --> 02:11:39.190
Much cannot be published.

cue-1987
02:11:39.830 --> 02:11:44.750
Though censorship had been lifted, a
missionary cannot freely share all he sees

cue-1988
02:11:44.750 --> 02:11:45.390
and knows.

cue-1989
02:11:46.110 --> 02:11:47.950
His position is one of trust.

cue-1990
02:11:48.870 --> 02:11:53.510
That Emil Fischbacher gave his life
through tireless labor is clearly shown in

cue-1991
02:11:53.510 --> 02:11:54.630
what has been written here.

cue-1992
02:11:57.470 --> 02:11:58.810
[gentle music] Chapter eight:

cue-1993
02:11:59.830 --> 02:12:01.390
Faithful unto death.

cue-1994
02:12:03.830 --> 02:12:07.710
Exactly three weeks after the Saturday
when Emil Fischbacher wrote his last

cue-1995
02:12:07.710 --> 02:12:11.710
letter, he laid down his life for God and
for others in the land he had come to

cue-1996
02:12:11.710 --> 02:12:11.970
love.

cue-1997
02:12:12.850 --> 02:12:16.620
In the words of Christina Rossetti, if we
may change a pronoun, it was,

cue-1998
02:12:17.230 --> 02:12:19.640
"One step more, and the goal receives him.

cue-1999
02:12:20.350 --> 02:12:25.330
One word more, and life's task is done.
One toil more, and the cross is

cue-2000
02:12:25.330 --> 02:12:26.990
carried and sets the sun."

cue-2001
02:12:27.950 --> 02:12:30.649
Emil Fischbacher had obeyed the heavenly
call.

cue-2002
02:12:31.430 --> 02:12:34.950
He had learned the joy of serving and the
peace of full surrender.

cue-2003
02:12:35.790 --> 02:12:40.410
His heart burned with zeal for his
master's cause and for the salvation of

cue-2004
02:12:40.410 --> 02:12:40.890
souls.

cue-2005
02:12:41.770 --> 02:12:43.510
He was faithful unto death.

cue-2006
02:12:44.950 --> 02:12:49.570
Though still unwell, as mentioned in his
last letter, he returned to his work among

cue-2007
02:12:49.570 --> 02:12:50.760
the sick and dying.

cue-2008
02:12:51.510 --> 02:12:54.990
Five days later, he collapsed and had to
be put to bed.

cue-2009
02:12:55.830 --> 02:13:00.170
Two days before this, Mr. Mather had also
been confined to bed with fever.

cue-2010
02:13:01.010 --> 02:13:05.710
In that lonely mission outpost, Mr.
Hunter, already over seventy years

cue-2011
02:13:05.710 --> 02:13:10.690
old, and the five new workers gathered
around the two sick beds, caring for them

cue-2012
02:13:10.690 --> 02:13:15.370
with deep love and devotion. Whether the
illness was typhus or typhoid was

cue-2013
02:13:15.370 --> 02:13:19.690
uncertain, both to the doctor himself and
to those who nursed

cue-2014
02:13:19.690 --> 02:13:23.990
him. Yet all human care was powerless to
save them.

cue-2015
02:13:25.020 --> 02:13:29.930
Mr. Mather went home to be with the Lord
on May twenty-fourth, and Emil Fischbacher

cue-2016
02:13:29.930 --> 02:13:31.180
followed three days later.

cue-2017
02:13:32.310 --> 02:13:37.270
To the east of the city, in sight of the
mountains, they were laid to rest side by

cue-2018
02:13:37.270 --> 02:13:37.690
side.

cue-2019
02:13:38.520 --> 02:13:43.230
The land for which they gave their lives
holds their dust until the great trumpet

cue-2020
02:13:43.230 --> 02:13:44.550
of God shall sound.

cue-2021
02:13:45.610 --> 02:13:50.210
Then their mortal bodies will be clothed
with immortality, and the promise will be

cue-2022
02:13:50.210 --> 02:13:50.850
fulfilled.

cue-2023
02:13:51.550 --> 02:13:53.450
Death is swallowed up in victory.

cue-2024
02:13:54.450 --> 02:13:59.350
Therefore, my beloved brothers, be
steadfast, immovable, always

cue-2025
02:13:59.350 --> 02:14:03.570
abounding in the work of the Lord, knowing
that your labor is not in vain in the

cue-2026
02:14:03.570 --> 02:14:08.240
Lord.Chapter nine.

cue-2027
02:14:09.380 --> 02:14:10.300
To what purpose?

cue-2028
02:14:12.940 --> 02:14:16.920
It was on the last Saturday in May
nineteen thirty-one that Emil Fischbacher

cue-2029
02:14:16.920 --> 02:14:20.380
picked up China's Millions and read the
Appeal to Young Men.

cue-2030
02:14:21.360 --> 02:14:25.320
On the last Saturday in May nineteen
thirty-three, exactly two years later,

cue-2031
02:14:25.980 --> 02:14:27.480
his earthly service ended,

cue-2032
02:14:28.230 --> 02:14:30.180
and he returned to God who had called him.

cue-2033
02:14:31.420 --> 02:14:33.340
The call to leave home came in one way.

cue-2034
02:14:33.960 --> 02:14:38.940
The call to leave his work in China came
in another, only two years apart. Such a

cue-2035
02:14:38.940 --> 02:14:43.920
brief span stirs the mind and raises deep
questions. To what purpose was

cue-2036
02:14:43.920 --> 02:14:46.520
the first call if the second was to follow
so soon?

cue-2037
02:14:47.540 --> 02:14:49.540
How should life's worth be measured?

cue-2038
02:14:50.880 --> 02:14:52.860
Can we measure life by years alone?

cue-2039
02:14:53.620 --> 02:14:57.880
Is length of time of little value in the
light of eternity? What did Emil

cue-2040
02:14:57.880 --> 02:15:00.360
Fischbacher himself think about his
service?

cue-2041
02:15:01.100 --> 02:15:05.700
What did his loved ones feel? And what can
we say? The things of the

cue-2042
02:15:05.700 --> 02:15:08.300
spirit cannot be measured by human
standards.

cue-2043
02:15:09.180 --> 02:15:13.420
It is good sometimes to pause and think
deeply. Was the poet right who said,

cue-2044
02:15:14.120 --> 02:15:16.480
"Measure thy life by loss instead of gain,

cue-2045
02:15:17.100 --> 02:15:20.020
not by the wine drunk but the wine poured
forth"?

cue-2046
02:15:21.160 --> 02:15:25.900
It is fitting now to look again at that
appeal to young men which came to young

cue-2047
02:15:25.900 --> 02:15:27.620
Fischbacher as God's call.

cue-2048
02:15:28.640 --> 02:15:30.160
One paragraph will suffice.

cue-2049
02:15:30.910 --> 02:15:35.560
"If ease and comfort at home hold you back
from suffering for Christ in China, then

cue-2050
02:15:35.560 --> 02:15:40.060
much of what you accomplish at home will
not endure at the judgment seat of Christ.

cue-2051
02:15:40.680 --> 02:15:45.480
But if you do the will of God, and if that
will means China for you, your life will

cue-2052
02:15:45.480 --> 02:15:49.240
never be lost. It will live forever in
soul-saving work."

cue-2053
02:15:50.760 --> 02:15:54.640
These are striking words, especially those
at the end of the statement.

cue-2054
02:15:55.300 --> 02:16:00.100
But is it true that if God chose China for
Emil Fischbacher, his life will never

cue-2055
02:16:00.100 --> 02:16:03.360
end but will remain forever in soul-saving
work?

cue-2056
02:16:04.640 --> 02:16:07.520
Is this simply poetic language or plain
truth?

cue-2057
02:16:08.820 --> 02:16:11.200
Two verses from scripture answer that
question.

cue-2058
02:16:12.280 --> 02:16:13.580
Our Lord himself said,

cue-2059
02:16:14.300 --> 02:16:19.140
"Not everyone who says to me, 'Lord,
Lord,' shall enter the kingdom of heaven,

cue-2060
02:16:19.140 --> 02:16:22.520
but only those who do the will of my
Father in heaven."

cue-2061
02:16:23.600 --> 02:16:25.460
And through his servant John, he said,

cue-2062
02:16:26.080 --> 02:16:28.360
"The world passes away and its desires,

cue-2063
02:16:29.080 --> 02:16:31.400
but whoever does the will of God lives
forever."

cue-2064
02:16:32.520 --> 02:16:33.500
Do we believe this?

cue-2065
02:16:34.520 --> 02:16:37.449
One of the most respected men in the
church today recently said-

cue-2066
02:16:38.290 --> 02:16:42.680
"I believe the greatest weakness in every
church is the inability to take Jesus

cue-2067
02:16:42.680 --> 02:16:45.560
Christ seriously and to take him at his
word."

cue-2068
02:16:46.160 --> 02:16:50.190
Another writer from a very different
background expressed it this way.

cue-2069
02:16:50.190 --> 02:16:54.360
"The truth is, the Galilean has been too
great for our small hearts."

cue-2070
02:16:55.180 --> 02:16:59.020
Emil Fischbacher had no doubts about the
wisdom and joy of obedience.

cue-2071
02:16:59.880 --> 02:17:03.859
Writing to his youngest brother from the
heart of Asia, fully aware of its

cue-2072
02:17:03.860 --> 02:17:04.580
difficulties,

cue-2073
02:17:05.470 --> 02:17:08.820
he declared his confidence that God had
guided him in every detail.

cue-2074
02:17:10.120 --> 02:17:14.400
Speaking of his delays at home and the
wide medical experience he had gained, he

cue-2075
02:17:14.400 --> 02:17:14.640
wrote-

cue-2076
02:17:15.490 --> 02:17:20.360
"Yes, I did move about a great deal, and I
can't help thinking that from that

cue-2077
02:17:20.360 --> 02:17:23.500
point of view, the timing of my call was
just right."

cue-2078
02:17:24.980 --> 02:17:29.180
Then, referring to his journey across the
Gobi Desert, he continued.

cue-2079
02:17:29.970 --> 02:17:34.100
"But there is something even more
convincing. It's the fact of the journey

cue-2080
02:17:34.100 --> 02:17:34.520
up here."

cue-2081
02:17:35.180 --> 02:17:38.980
Recalling, as one brother might to
another, his experience with motor

cue-2082
02:17:38.980 --> 02:17:42.540
vehicles and the responsibilities he had
carried, he added.

cue-2083
02:17:43.460 --> 02:17:48.400
"Such expeditions are usually planned by
men with long experience in that kind

cue-2084
02:17:48.400 --> 02:17:48.900
of travel.

cue-2085
02:17:49.620 --> 02:17:53.940
Well, the story of our journey is proof
enough of the Lord's wonderful

cue-2086
02:17:53.940 --> 02:17:57.530
leading. I don't know of a single thing we
left behind,

cue-2087
02:17:58.260 --> 02:18:01.609
though to have forgotten something in the
Gobi might have been fatal.

cue-2088
02:18:02.460 --> 02:18:05.290
And I say this humbly and only to you,

cue-2089
02:18:06.030 --> 02:18:09.560
I believe the Lord delayed my call for
just such a time as this.

cue-2090
02:18:10.620 --> 02:18:15.400
It was work I thoroughly enjoyed, and I
believe, humanly speaking,

cue-2091
02:18:16.120 --> 02:18:17.520
I was somewhat fitted for it.

cue-2092
02:18:18.120 --> 02:18:22.809
Let that encourage you. The Lord may seem
a little late to our weak senses,

cue-2093
02:18:22.809 --> 02:18:27.739
but even if the explanation is delayed or
never given, I

cue-2094
02:18:27.739 --> 02:18:29.740
know the truth will always prove true."

cue-2095
02:18:31.280 --> 02:18:32.620
Such was his testimony.

cue-2096
02:18:33.290 --> 02:18:38.260
His letters show no trace of regret, only
joy in doing his father's will.

cue-2097
02:18:38.260 --> 02:18:42.940
In Shanghai, during prayer with his
missionary sister, he thanked God for his

cue-2098
02:18:42.940 --> 02:18:46.240
gracious guidance and then exclaimed with
simple sincerity.

cue-2099
02:18:46.920 --> 02:18:51.080
"Lord, it has not been hard at all. None
of it. You've done

cue-2100
02:18:51.080 --> 02:18:52.160
magnificently."

cue-2101
02:18:52.860 --> 02:18:54.220
But did his family regret it?

cue-2102
02:18:54.960 --> 02:18:57.160
Let us hear first from his sister in
China.

cue-2103
02:18:57.920 --> 02:19:01.980
Her letter not only shows her heart, but
also reflects something of what her

cue-2104
02:19:01.980 --> 02:19:03.700
brother believed about second causes.

cue-2105
02:19:04.570 --> 02:19:08.980
"When I received the telegram," she wrote,
"telling me that we would never meet

cue-2106
02:19:08.980 --> 02:19:13.940
again on Earth, the Lord gave me a share
in my brother's joy and a share in

cue-2107
02:19:13.940 --> 02:19:18.380
his own far greater joy as he welcomed
his beloved servant home.

cue-2108
02:19:19.360 --> 02:19:21.260
My heart echoed the refrain,

cue-2109
02:19:21.940 --> 02:19:23.309
'You've done magnificently.'

cue-2110
02:19:24.980 --> 02:19:29.720
Worthy is the Lamb that was slain to
receive power and riches and

cue-2111
02:19:29.720 --> 02:19:34.680
wisdom and strength and honor and glory
and blessing.

cue-2112
02:19:35.980 --> 02:19:40.240
While I was in Shanghai, my brother and I
talked about the question of second

cue-2113
02:19:40.240 --> 02:19:42.540
causes. They were no problem to him.

cue-2114
02:19:43.660 --> 02:19:47.860
In a letter received just after he went
home, though written as far back as

cue-2115
02:19:47.860 --> 02:19:51.940
-February fifth, he said..."
-"Oh, I'm so grateful that I have learned

cue-2116
02:19:51.940 --> 02:19:53.560
to take everything from the Lord."

cue-2117
02:19:54.750 --> 02:19:58.500
-That same letter says...
-"You are always looking for a new thing.

cue-2118
02:19:59.660 --> 02:20:03.940
I too have learned something of the
blessing that comes when we break away

cue-2119
02:20:03.940 --> 02:20:05.960
from the old pattern of stagnation.

cue-2120
02:20:07.120 --> 02:20:08.200
Isn't it amazing,

cue-2121
02:20:08.820 --> 02:20:10.800
the endless supply of new things?"

cue-2122
02:20:11.916 --> 02:20:15.576
Isn't it wonderful to realize that the
promise in Isaiah 43

cue-2123
02:20:16.216 --> 02:20:20.956
is always living and unfailing? Oh, how
poor we make ourselves by not

cue-2124
02:20:20.956 --> 02:20:22.236
claiming his promises.

cue-2125
02:20:23.136 --> 02:20:26.696
I've been discovering many unclaimed
promises in my reading lately.

cue-2126
02:20:28.016 --> 02:20:32.776
Little did he imagine what a glorious new
thing God had waiting for him just a

cue-2127
02:20:32.776 --> 02:20:34.216
little further along the road.

cue-2128
02:20:35.776 --> 02:20:39.876
From every point of view I am satisfied
with God's choice for him, completely

cue-2129
02:20:39.876 --> 02:20:40.526
satisfied.

cue-2130
02:20:41.516 --> 02:20:44.056
I would never have dared to choose
anything so good for him,

cue-2131
02:20:44.856 --> 02:20:49.016
but I am glad that the one who loves him
far more than I do made the choice.

cue-2132
02:20:49.896 --> 02:20:53.836
Bless the Lord, O my soul, and all that is
within me,

cue-2133
02:20:54.596 --> 02:20:55.896
bless his holy name.

cue-2134
02:20:56.956 --> 02:21:01.056
O magnify the Lord with me, and let us
exalt his name together.

cue-2135
02:21:02.436 --> 02:21:06.036
Lord, it has not been hard at all, none of
it. You've done

cue-2136
02:21:06.036 --> 02:21:07.716
magnificently.

cue-2137
02:21:09.636 --> 02:21:14.236
In that letter from my brother, received
after his home call, he spoke of the

cue-2138
02:21:14.236 --> 02:21:19.176
vastness of the task and the special
difficulties of the work in Sinkiang, then

cue-2139
02:21:19.176 --> 02:21:22.636
referred to the promise of the rivers of
living water, adding,

cue-2140
02:21:23.316 --> 02:21:27.696
I have not been able to find any condition
under which that supply is ever to be

cue-2141
02:21:27.696 --> 02:21:32.596
stopped, but I do fully believe that this
kind goeth not out

cue-2142
02:21:32.596 --> 02:21:34.366
but by prayer and fasting.

cue-2143
02:21:36.106 --> 02:21:40.356
Do you think God intended the flow of
those living waters to be reduced by

cue-2144
02:21:40.356 --> 02:21:42.956
taking two of his children from that
thirsty land?

cue-2145
02:21:44.096 --> 02:21:49.056
I believe their going is part of his plan
to increase that flow. And I believe that

cue-2146
02:21:49.056 --> 02:21:51.016
truth carries a message for some of you.

cue-2147
02:21:51.876 --> 02:21:53.876
That is why I have shared so much.

cue-2148
02:21:54.776 --> 02:21:58.076
I make no special appeal for Sinkiang or
for any place,

cue-2149
02:21:58.676 --> 02:22:02.916
though one of my sorrows is that I can
answer only one of the many calls that

cue-2150
02:22:02.916 --> 02:22:03.936
echo in my ears.

cue-2151
02:22:04.796 --> 02:22:07.656
The need is so great and the workers so
few.

cue-2152
02:22:08.556 --> 02:22:13.516
But I do make an appeal for my Lord, the
one who gave his life and who still

cue-2153
02:22:13.516 --> 02:22:14.436
gives it for us.

cue-2154
02:22:15.356 --> 02:22:17.086
Will you give yourself wholly to him?

cue-2155
02:22:17.786 --> 02:22:19.516
He will do magnificently for you,

cue-2156
02:22:20.276 --> 02:22:21.116
and he is worthy.

cue-2157
02:22:22.036 --> 02:22:23.996
And their father at home wrote to the
author,

cue-2158
02:22:24.905 --> 02:22:29.836
This news came to us as a great shock, but
it was not long before

cue-2159
02:22:29.836 --> 02:22:34.836
we could look up again to the blue sky,
listen to the song of the birds,

cue-2160
02:22:34.836 --> 02:22:39.116
and hear the music of the eternal in our
souls.

cue-2161
02:22:39.996 --> 02:22:44.726
We are content to trust him who has so
graciously helped, blessed,

cue-2162
02:22:44.726 --> 02:22:49.716
and upheld us until now. We have often
prayed

cue-2163
02:22:49.716 --> 02:22:54.476
that the Lord would make Emil's life and
service fruitful for his glory, and we

cue-2164
02:22:54.476 --> 02:22:58.576
gladly leave to him the way he has chosen
to answer that prayer.

cue-2165
02:22:59.576 --> 02:23:01.256
And last but not least,

cue-2166
02:23:02.056 --> 02:23:06.636
Emil Fischbacher's youngest brother
accepted both his brother's death and the

cue-2167
02:23:06.636 --> 02:23:09.176
needs of the mission field as a personal
challenge.

cue-2168
02:23:09.936 --> 02:23:14.096
He offered himself to take, as far as
possible, his brother's place.

cue-2169
02:23:15.016 --> 02:23:19.416
We share these deeply personal details
only for the glory of Emil Fischbacher's

cue-2170
02:23:19.416 --> 02:23:24.136
God. It should also be mentioned that
another doctor and his wife have

cue-2171
02:23:24.136 --> 02:23:29.056
volunteered to serve in that same distant
region. When news of Dr.

cue-2172
02:23:29.056 --> 02:23:33.276
Fischbacher's death reached England, less
than seven months after his arrival in

cue-2173
02:23:33.276 --> 02:23:37.836
Sinkiang, many asked, To what purpose was
this life poured out?

cue-2174
02:23:38.816 --> 02:23:43.136
Here was a young man, bright, capable, and
full of promise,

cue-2175
02:23:43.916 --> 02:23:48.256
thoroughly trained for medical service,
one of the few doctors in a vast land,

cue-2176
02:23:49.036 --> 02:23:53.275
and yet called home so soon, just as his
life's work had begun.

cue-2177
02:23:54.296 --> 02:23:57.136
It is easy for us to dwell on what might
have been.

cue-2178
02:23:58.036 --> 02:24:02.676
But the words of Christ, spoken in Bethany
in the house of Simon the Leper,

cue-2179
02:24:02.676 --> 02:24:07.616
remind us that God's judgments are not
like ours, nor his thoughts like ours.

cue-2180
02:24:08.876 --> 02:24:11.495
He alone can rightly measure the worth of
a life.

cue-2181
02:24:12.576 --> 02:24:16.296
It is a remarkable fact that at the
farewell meeting in London for Emil

cue-2182
02:24:16.296 --> 02:24:20.736
Fischbacher and his companions, the last
group of the two hundred to set sail,

cue-2183
02:24:21.376 --> 02:24:26.336
the Reverend W. H. Aldis spoke on the
story of the alabaster box

cue-2184
02:24:26.336 --> 02:24:27.516
of precious ointment.

cue-2185
02:24:28.736 --> 02:24:32.306
He drew attention to the sharp contrast
between the disciples' reaction,

cue-2186
02:24:33.095 --> 02:24:36.576
To what purpose is this waste? and our
Lord's response,

cue-2187
02:24:37.416 --> 02:24:42.046
She hath wrought a beautiful thing unto
me. Liddell and Scott's

cue-2188
02:24:42.046 --> 02:24:46.836
lexicon translates the Greek word kalos as
something fair, lovely,

cue-2189
02:24:46.836 --> 02:24:49.116
morally right, and beautiful.

cue-2190
02:24:50.416 --> 02:24:55.396
That contrast between human judgment and
God's continues to this day, except as

cue-2191
02:24:55.396 --> 02:24:57.176
we learn to see life in his light.

cue-2192
02:24:58.196 --> 02:25:03.036
The fragrance of that ointment poured from
the broken vessel filled the house, and

cue-2193
02:25:03.036 --> 02:25:07.836
the devotion that prompted the gift filled
and satisfied the heart of Christ.

cue-2194
02:25:08.936 --> 02:25:13.716
But Judas, along with others who resented
such lavish love, protested,

cue-2195
02:25:13.716 --> 02:25:16.336
To what purpose has this waste been made?

cue-2196
02:25:17.456 --> 02:25:22.276
With deep irony, Jesus later spoke of
Judas as the son of perdition,

cue-2197
02:25:22.276 --> 02:25:27.116
literally the son of waste, for the same
Greek word is used in both

cue-2198
02:25:27.116 --> 02:25:31.496
expressions. And what a true son of waste
Judas was.

cue-2199
02:25:32.256 --> 02:25:35.096
He embodied the very fault he imagined he
saw in Mary.

cue-2200
02:25:35.816 --> 02:25:40.596
How terribly he had squandered his
opportunities. How he had misused the

cue-2201
02:25:40.596 --> 02:25:44.996
privileges and profaned the blessings that
had been given to him. Lifted to the

cue-2202
02:25:44.996 --> 02:25:49.456
heights of fellowship with Christ, he cast
himself down to ruin by wasting the

cue-2203
02:25:49.456 --> 02:25:51.856
riches of grace offered to him.

cue-2204
02:25:52.376 --> 02:25:57.136
Nowhere in Scripture do we find a more
vivid and solemn contrast between

cue-2205
02:25:57.136 --> 02:25:59.486
God's and man's standards of value.

cue-2206
02:26:00.716 --> 02:26:03.606
As we think of Emil Fischbacher's life
poured out for God,

cue-2207
02:26:04.356 --> 02:26:07.656
we remember the lesson of the precious
ointment and the words of Christ.

cue-2208
02:26:08.376 --> 02:26:12.956
Whoever desires to save his life will lose
it, but whoever loses his life for my

cue-2209
02:26:12.956 --> 02:26:15.116
sake and the gospel's will save it.

cue-2210
02:26:16.036 --> 02:26:20.506
It is surely significant that this is the
only one of our Lord's sayings recorded in

cue-2211
02:26:20.506 --> 02:26:21.796
all four Gospels.

cue-2212
02:26:22.456 --> 02:26:24.416
Nor is that its only distinction.

cue-2213
02:26:25.376 --> 02:26:30.056
With meaningful variations, Jesus spoke
these words on at least four

cue-2214
02:26:30.056 --> 02:26:31.076
different occasions.

cue-2215
02:26:31.796 --> 02:26:36.476
When he sent out the twelve, when he
rebuked Peter for urging him to turn aside

cue-2216
02:26:36.476 --> 02:26:41.416
from the cross, and twice again as his
earthly ministry neared its end and he

cue-2217
02:26:41.416 --> 02:26:44.156
faced death in its most painful form.

cue-2218
02:26:45.376 --> 02:26:50.356
Slow as we are to believe and understand,
this is God's law of life. We

cue-2219
02:26:50.356 --> 02:26:51.976
ask, to what purpose?

cue-2220
02:26:52.876 --> 02:26:53.716
Christ answers,

cue-2221
02:26:54.496 --> 02:26:58.036
it is a beautiful thing and one that
brings forth much fruit.

cue-2222
02:27:01.376 --> 02:27:01.996
Epilogue

cue-2223
02:27:04.436 --> 02:27:09.056
Sorrow of saints is sorrow of a day.
Gladness of saints is gladness

cue-2224
02:27:09.056 --> 02:27:09.596
evermore.

cue-2225
02:27:10.356 --> 02:27:15.276
Send on thy hope, send on thy will before
to chant God's praise along the

cue-2226
02:27:15.276 --> 02:27:15.946
narrow way.

cue-2227
02:27:16.816 --> 02:27:21.516
Stir up his praises if the flesh would
sway. Exalt his praises if the world press

cue-2228
02:27:21.516 --> 02:27:26.436
sore. Peel out his praises if black Satan
roar a hundred thousand lies to

cue-2229
02:27:26.436 --> 02:27:27.156
say them nay.

cue-2230
02:27:27.876 --> 02:27:31.136
Devil and death and Hades, threefold cord.

cue-2231
02:27:32.356 --> 02:27:34.996
Not quickly broken, front thee to thy
face.

cue-2232
02:27:35.636 --> 02:27:40.356
Front thou them with a face of tenfold
flint. Shout for the battle, David.

cue-2233
02:27:40.956 --> 02:27:45.796
Never stint body or breath or blood, but
proof in grace die for thy

cue-2234
02:27:45.796 --> 02:27:47.856
Lord as once for thee thy Lord.

